-- planificacion-proyectos-cronograma-recursos
UPDATE public.blog_posts SET
  blocks_es = '[{"id":"a0f9ae87-2442-4669-82b2-b16e4a360386","type":"paragraph","html":"Has visto el patrón una y otra vez: el cronograma dice que el proyecto termina en marzo, pero en abril siguen reasignando gente. El presupuesto se aprobó en enero y en junio descubres que llevas el doble de horas consumidas. La gestión de proyectos se queda en el tablero de tareas y nadie conecta esas tareas con quién hace qué, cuántas horas tiene cada uno y qué margen deja el proyecto."},{"id":"69f1791a-1e61-4885-912e-1e5a0c0a4a5b","type":"callout","tone":"info","html":"Cuando el cronograma, el presupuesto y los recursos no van de la mano, los proyectos se retrasan, se disparan los costes o el equipo termina sobrecargado. Esta guía recorre cómo unir las tres piezas: cronograma, presupuesto por proyectos y capacidad del equipo, con ejemplos prácticos y un repaso a las herramientas que realmente ayudan."},{"id":"dd1f37ce-2a78-4e9d-91c2-d79d10843da0","type":"toc"},{"id":"74556eae-a79e-456d-80ce-978204551898","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"1. Qué es la planificación de proyectos","anchorId":"que-es-planificacion"},{"id":"2fcaf7de-536d-4fc5-8241-8a187cb4e16d","type":"paragraph","html":"La planificación de proyectos es la parte de la gestión de proyectos en la que defines qué hay que hacer, en qué orden, con qué recursos y en qué plazos. No es solo una lista de tareas: es decidir las fases de un proyecto, asignar responsabilidades, estimar tiempos y costes y dejar un marco claro para el seguimiento y la evaluación. La cicatriz aparece cuando nadie lo “acuerda” en serio y luego el proyecto se re-plantea en la primera crisis."},{"id":"8494e3ec-599f-4754-8acf-ee468867a969","type":"paragraph","html":"En la práctica, la planificación suele organizarse en fases. Aunque cada metodología las nombra distinto (project management clásico, Scrum, etc.), suele haber un inicio (alcance y objetivos), una fase de planificación (cronograma, presupuesto, recursos), la ejecución y el cierre. Lo que nos interesa aquí es que en la fase de planificación es donde se construye el cronograma, se fija el presupuesto del proyecto y se decide cómo se cubren los recursos para llevarlo a cabo."},{"id":"a5429750-392d-45de-bc13-8b97a2b225d2","type":"paragraph","html":"Sin esa base, el proyecto se convierte en una sucesión de urgencias: no sabes si vas bien o mal hasta que llega la facturación o el cliente reclama. Por eso tiene sentido tratar el cronograma, el presupuesto y los recursos como un mismo sistema, no como tres documentos sueltos."},{"id":"fa348802-5c4f-4bc9-9c9f-fffa6da27834","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Las fases de un proyecto (resumen)"},{"id":"435dde64-201a-4e14-847e-d665039dfc71","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Inicio"},{"id":"04231dd9-0df7-4049-acb2-ce0a4d43a59b","type":"paragraph","html":"Alcance y objetivos"},{"id":"14ff7491-a4f8-44b8-8845-68e28a39f1af","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Planificación"},{"id":"cf627037-38e0-4eb3-9dcb-8b575f6a0078","type":"paragraph","html":"Cronograma, presupuesto, recursos"},{"id":"96588bb2-b36b-4141-a890-f420b9259b09","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Ejecución"},{"id":"fd4d8922-6f1c-46ad-b887-e51c4e1832c3","type":"paragraph","html":"Seguimiento y ajustes"},{"id":"05b7c3f3-4a39-419d-a1c5-1493d9cddd20","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Cierre"},{"id":"3d42f844-1090-4bf9-9990-6cc8a2ecb84d","type":"paragraph","html":"Evaluación y lecciones"},{"id":"6541b233-b9ef-4226-8853-b72d274f01de","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"2. El cronograma y el diagrama de Gantt","anchorId":"cronograma-gantt"},{"id":"b7336554-7896-4b2b-aa9b-24b5f46cb958","type":"paragraph","html":"El cronograma de un proyecto es la línea temporal de hitos y tareas: qué se hace y cuándo. La forma más visual de representarlo es el diagrama de Gantt: barras sobre una escala de tiempo que muestran la duración de cada actividad y, en muchas herramientas, las dependencias entre ellas. Sirve para ver de un vistazo si las fechas encajan y qué tareas son críticas. La cicatriz es que el Gantt “cuadra” en pantalla… pero cuando se repiten urgencias, el mismo recurso aparece en tres frentes."},{"id":"48ec30af-d653-4b27-a68d-524424675284","type":"paragraph","html":"Un diagrama de Gantt bien usado te ayuda a responder preguntas como: ¿cuándo empieza y termina cada fase?, ¿qué tareas bloquean a otras?, ¿hay huecos o solapamientos evidentes? Herramientas como cronogramas online o software de project management suelen incluir una vista Gantt; también puedes hacer un diagrama de Gantt en Excel con una plantilla o usar una herramienta específica. Lo importante es que el cronograma sea creíble: que refleje dependencias reales y que, en la medida de lo posible, esté alineado con la capacidad de quien va a ejecutar el trabajo."},{"id":"5738e6bf-c441-4445-8d22-af6a33551c48","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Cronograma solo por tareas vs. cronograma con recursos"},{"id":"12ad2f90-84b2-4c4e-999b-0574e6d4f648","type":"paragraph","html":"El Gantt clásico muestra plazos; no suele mostrar quién hace qué ni cuántas horas tiene cada uno."},{"id":"b6f2be53-bd7f-41c4-a7ad-07ec68bd956e","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Solo tareas y plazos"},{"id":"66d9ba7b-c0b7-40c2-8f2e-ef24c202c307","type":"paragraph","html":"Ves fechas y dependencias. No ves si la misma persona está en tres proyectos la misma semana."},{"id":"3c19b71c-749e-4e22-bbc4-66b1a8f43aea","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Tareas + recursos y horas"},{"id":"f9a0962e-7c28-42c0-9ad2-226fb10ba89b","type":"paragraph","html":"Cronograma alineado con capacidad: quién hace qué y con cuántas horas. Evita sobrecargas ocultas."},{"id":"41308423-6495-4f78-abdb-f7d9672aa606","type":"callout","tone":"warning","html":"<strong>Limitación habitual del Gantt</strong> Puedes tener un cronograma perfecto en el papel y, en la realidad, que tres proyectos pidan al mismo recurso en la misma semana. Por eso el siguiente paso lógico es conectar el cronograma con los recursos: quién hace qué y con cuántas horas."},{"id":"d87625dc-1cc4-4ff1-96d9-97f606b8e971","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"3. Presupuesto del proyecto","anchorId":"presupuesto-triangulo"},{"id":"0d690d24-1313-443d-a5e8-519c2b48b1ae","type":"paragraph","html":"El presupuesto de un proyecto fija cuánto vas a gastar (o cuánto vas a invertir en horas y costes) para entregar el alcance acordado. En muchas agencias y equipos de servicios, el presupuesto por proyectos se construye a partir de las horas: horas estimadas por rol o por persona, multiplicadas por un coste o por un precio de venta. Una matriz de presupuesto del proyecto puede desglosar por fases, por paquetes de trabajo o por mes, según cómo factures o controles. La cicatriz suele ser ese enero en que aprueban el “X horas”, y en el primer cambio de alcance el número deja de protegerte."},{"id":"de6eec63-778a-47c5-be22-18465eb53e0c","type":"paragraph","html":"La relación con el cronograma es directa: si el cronograma se alarga, las horas reales suelen dispararse y el presupuesto se desvía. El famoso triángulo de la gestión de proyectos (alcance, tiempo, coste) sigue vigente: si cambias uno, sueles afectar a los otros."},{"id":"1a288d30-dea6-4b4b-be9d-d4184347e33f","type":"paragraph","html":"Por eso tiene sentido que el presupuesto no sea un número suelto, sino horas y costes asignados a las mismas fases y tareas que ya tienes en el cronograma. Así, cuando hagas el seguimiento, podrás comparar horas presupuestadas con horas reales y ver si el proyecto sigue dentro del margen."},{"id":"9bea9bdc-62a9-4f97-b979-f7c24513e427","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"El triángulo alcance – tiempo – coste"},{"id":"a181136c-5615-46c7-93b7-f78ec252b834","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Alcance"},{"id":"54c5ce12-2f18-48ba-a120-25e37ea9186b","type":"paragraph","html":"Qué se entrega (entregables, requisitos)"},{"id":"4396d122-3c47-445f-85e9-4d481c222202","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Tiempo"},{"id":"01af4553-bc7c-4ec1-ad0b-1fcaa9a703f2","type":"paragraph","html":"Plazos y cronograma"},{"id":"d7ea6d44-7123-4577-b726-be432d33479d","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Coste"},{"id":"8e2eef11-3065-443e-a186-b6de435d6a75","type":"paragraph","html":"Presupuesto (horas × tarifa, otros costes)"},{"id":"823c5f03-7862-4268-8441-303369094ff1","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Cambiar uno suele impactar en los otros dos. Por eso el presupuesto debe ligarse a las mismas fases y tareas del cronograma.</em>"},{"id":"5dd2fa3a-dce6-4334-8ba5-16e6b173b293","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"4. Recursos y capacidad","anchorId":"recursos-capacidad"},{"id":"a3deb824-e7dd-49c0-9465-80b2a9499e52","type":"paragraph","html":"Los recursos para llevar a cabo un proyecto son, en la mayoría de los casos, las personas: su tiempo y su capacidad. La capacidad del equipo es la cantidad de horas disponibles en un periodo (día, semana, mes) descontando vacaciones, bajas y otras ausencias. Si no tienes claro cuántas horas tiene cada persona por semana, es muy fácil asignar más trabajo del que pueden hacer o, al revés, dejar capacidad sin usar. Lo que duele es asignar “capacidad bruta” y descubrir, dos semanas después, que la capacidad neta real era bastante menos."},{"id":"caeeeb7d-d18c-4c14-9263-11786fabe33d","type":"paragraph","html":"La asignación de horas es el puente entre el cronograma y el presupuesto: quién dedica cuántas horas a qué proyecto en cada semana. Cuando esa asignación se hace de forma explícita (por ejemplo con un planificador semanal o mensual por horas), puedes ver sobrecargas e infrautilización antes de que se conviertan en retrasos o en márgenes comidos."},{"id":"f4d9f0c5-9e07-4680-b32e-0b6b71ba2020","type":"paragraph","html":"Esta forma de trabajar está muy alineada con el timeboxing: asignar bloques de tiempo concretos a proyectos o tareas en lugar de solo listar tareas sin tiempo. La técnica la recogemos con más detalle en la guía sobre qué es el timeboxing."},{"id":"5b7047e2-fa12-4891-a813-e472d8034287","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Sin visibilidad de capacidad"},{"id":"ed543ac2-5dff-4c83-b7b9-9c9e96d70f49","type":"paragraph","html":"Asignas tareas sin saber cuántas horas tiene cada persona. Resultado: sobrecarga, retrasos y márgenes que se comen sin que nadie lo vea a tiempo."},{"id":"1b30d06a-b559-413e-993e-04cbda70e517","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Planificación por horas"},{"id":"7e2c83ea-d483-473b-836f-583db160de64","type":"paragraph","html":"Ves quién tiene cuántas horas libres y cuántas asignadas por proyecto. Detectas sobrecargas antes de que ocurran y ajustas el cronograma o el alcance."},{"id":"5de20ce2-d9c3-498a-9796-4650b34b92b0","type":"paragraph","html":"qué es el timeboxing"},{"id":"4110cf1e-c38b-46d4-b362-de4e6edd86cd","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>En resumen: el cronograma te dice cuándo; el presupuesto, cuánto; los recursos y la capacidad, quién y con cuántas horas. Unir los tres evita que los proyectos vivan solo en el tablero de tareas y que la rentabilidad se descubra cuando ya es tarde.</strong>"},{"id":"7ee95fbd-d9d0-4f70-b129-5b3cd6b337f9","type":"callout","tone":"highlight","html":"<strong>💡 Cápsula Taimbox: Cronograma y capacidad en un solo sitio</strong> En Taimbox el planificador muestra semana a semana quién hace qué y con cuántas horas. Así unes cronograma, presupuesto por proyectos y recursos sin tener que cruzar tres herramientas."},{"id":"8d84228e-516e-4e5a-8ff2-975bd286f736","type":"cta","text":"Ver planificador de recursos","href":"/planificador-recursos","variant":"primary"},{"id":"37746774-502e-4146-ae52-5528ed407c17","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"5. Seguimiento, KPIs y dashboard de proyectos","anchorId":"seguimiento-kpis"},{"id":"c52727af-677e-4179-8914-674b85500381","type":"paragraph","html":"El seguimiento y la evaluación de proyectos consisten en comparar lo planificado con lo real: avance, horas consumidas, costes y, si aplica, satisfacción del cliente. Para eso sirven los indicadores: el KPI de un proyecto puede ser el avance frente al plan, las horas reales frente a las presupuestadas o el margen actual del proyecto. La cicatriz es cuando el dashboard “te da la razón” tarde: el cliente ya se enfadó y ya consumiste el buffer."},{"id":"c684dfff-6c56-4f40-8953-3bdfa9543057","type":"paragraph","html":"Un dashboard de proyectos que merezca la pena suele mostrar al menos: estado de cada proyecto (en plazo, en riesgo, retrasado), horas asignadas vs. horas reales (o vs. presupuesto) y carga por persona o por equipo. Así ves si un proyecto se está comiendo más horas de las previstas y si alguien está sobreasignado."},{"id":"bf94948b-363b-4332-94bb-5a0380747767","type":"paragraph","html":"En una agencia pequeña o mediana, tener un único lugar donde cruzar cronograma, presupuesto y horas reales suele marcar la diferencia entre reaccionar a tiempo y enterarte cuando el cliente ya está enfadado."},{"id":"08d91eb4-a3e1-410b-8263-6f72d00a5dab","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Avance vs. plan"},{"id":"3815c47b-b394-466a-ba71-3787ba27c52b","type":"paragraph","html":"¿Vamos por donde tocaba? Porcentaje de tareas o hitos completados respecto al cronograma."},{"id":"384bf392-e056-4c09-a0aa-f8c06aa77dd8","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Horas reales vs. presupuestadas"},{"id":"20ad1081-ef4e-47ba-b433-c00e4f078ade","type":"paragraph","html":"¿Nos estamos pasando de horas? Si las reales superan las previstas, el margen cae."},{"id":"55602e83-8bb3-4700-be6c-a76f31dfc54c","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Margen del proyecto"},{"id":"49ae5710-f2f0-40be-a16f-52608c7022ef","type":"paragraph","html":"Ingresos menos costes (horas × tarifa, etc.). El indicador que conecta tiempo y rentabilidad."},{"id":"38490420-5211-4f18-90ef-07cc63a0b6b5","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"6. Herramientas de gestión de proyectos","anchorId":"herramientas"},{"id":"452612ae-3471-4db3-92c4-16a4aed5a0af","type":"paragraph","html":"Las herramientas de gestión de proyectos cubren necesidades distintas. Los tableros tipo Kanban (Trello, Asana, ClickUp, Notion para proyectos) son muy útiles para el estado de las tareas y el flujo de trabajo; muchos incluyen también vista de cronograma o diagrama de Gantt. La cicatriz es tener “tres verdades”: una para tareas, otra para horas y otra para margen, y terminar decidiendo a dedo en cada crisis."},{"id":"0fbebd77-592c-4149-a839-513d97b6442d","type":"paragraph","html":"Para conectar tiempo, capacidad y rentabilidad hacen falta herramientas que trabajen con horas de forma explícita. En Taimbox nos centramos en ese tramo: planificación de recursos por horas, cronograma de quién hace qué cada semana, y reportes de rentabilidad por proyecto y por cliente."},{"id":"17e34742-cbca-435d-8dfc-d74b03cb1d71","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"¿Qué resuelve cada tipo de herramienta?"},{"id":"cd2e2d1e-a4e9-4644-9b27-b5651be94c31","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Tableros y Gantt"},{"id":"4823c2c9-a31a-4211-aa83-f534fa17abc1","type":"paragraph","html":"Estado de tareas, flujo de trabajo, dependencias y plazos. No suelen mostrar capacidad ni horas por persona ni margen por proyecto."},{"id":"6bc1ad42-e3cf-403a-bed2-c54b6194170c","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Planificación por horas y recursos"},{"id":"5d434481-3ebb-46d9-8a14-3060cf67f212","type":"paragraph","html":"Quién hace qué y con cuántas horas. Presupuesto por proyectos ligado a esas horas y reportes de margen (asignado vs. real)."},{"id":"97fc1312-57f1-4688-bd18-9821a1ee5e7c","type":"callout","tone":"highlight","html":"<strong>📊 Cápsula Taimbox: Planificador + reportes de rentabilidad</strong> Planifica por horas en el planificador, sigue el avance en el dashboard y revisa margen por proyecto y por cliente en los reportes de rentabilidad. Todo en una sola plataforma."},{"id":"9633d895-8194-4832-9f28-296b7c163f50","type":"cta","text":"Planificador","href":"/planificador-recursos","variant":"primary"},{"id":"f2d14e9c-b84a-49ff-8e9f-0f28a44e03d4","type":"cta","text":"Reportes de rentabilidad","href":"/reportes-rentabilidad","variant":"secondary"},{"id":"cf47ea96-2a86-4ddb-b8d6-7aedff77875f","type":"paragraph","html":"Tarifas y planes concretos en la página de precios"},{"id":"be5f2265-7e64-4c77-bfb0-428785bda864","type":"paragraph","html":"Planificar un proyecto de forma sólida implica alinear cronograma, presupuesto y recursos: qué se hace y cuándo, cuánto cuesta y quién lo hace con cuántas horas. El diagrama de Gantt y el cronograma son la base visual; el presupuesto por proyectos y la asignación de horas son lo que evita que todo se quede en intenciones. El seguimiento con KPIs y un dashboard sencillo te permite corregir antes de que el proyecto se desvíe del todo."},{"id":"2d2cba3d-3327-4578-8a51-4bd9dd96f5f6","type":"paragraph","html":"Si en tu agencia o equipo ya usáis tableros de tareas pero os falta ese enlace entre tiempo, capacidad y rentabilidad, probar un planificador por horas puede ser el siguiente paso."},{"id":"dde602e5-6196-4ba8-972c-62fbddcf5e73","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Preguntas frecuentes sobre planificación de proyectos","anchorId":"preguntas-frecuentes"},{"id":"555ca992-259f-42a2-bd64-3d72ac4fb4f4","type":"faq","items":[{"q":"¿El diagrama de Gantt es suficiente para gestionar un proyecto?","a":"Para plazos y dependencias sí. Para saber si vas a cumplir el presupuesto y si tu equipo tiene capacidad real, no: necesitas cruzar el cronograma con las horas por persona y con el presupuesto por proyecto."},{"q":"¿Qué KPI de proyecto tiene más sentido en una agencia?","a":"Horas reales vs. presupuestadas y margen por proyecto (o por cliente). Son los que conectan el tiempo con la rentabilidad. El avance frente al cronograma ayuda, pero sin horas y margen no ves si el proyecto es rentable."},{"q":"¿Puedo usar un tablero Kanban y un planificador por horas a la vez?","a":"Sí. Muchos equipos usan Trello, Asana o similar para el día a día de las tareas y una herramienta de planificación por horas (como Taimbox) para capacidad, presupuesto y margen. Se complementan: el tablero para el flujo, el planificador para el tiempo y el dinero."}]},{"id":"5e665bb6-a49d-42bc-99f3-c4362876f56e","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Planifica por horas y recupera el control del margen","anchorId":"cta-final"},{"id":"de820b99-be7b-4ec3-ab51-3b6ecb1a928b","type":"paragraph","html":"Cronograma, presupuesto y recursos en un solo lugar; Taimbox se puede explorar sin compromiso."},{"id":"c6e5f4aa-9ab6-4c8d-859f-3916866877f8","type":"cta","text":"Ver planificador de recursos","href":"/planificador-recursos","variant":"primary"},{"id":"49b18246-36f2-42c4-b586-86e45fcddeb9","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Escrito por el equipo de Taimbox — Gestión de recursos y rentabilidad para agencias.</em>"},{"id":"f73f6405-f488-46ba-af53-aa90948d0577","type":"relatedPost","slug":"que-es-timeboxing"}]'::jsonb,
  blocks_en = '[{"id":"814d6cf7-8cef-436e-97c1-038a2d4ab412","type":"paragraph","html":"You have seen the pattern again and again: the schedule says the project ends in March, but in April people are still being reassigned. The budget was approved in January and by June you discover you have burned twice the planned hours. Project management stays in the task board and nobody connects those tasks with who does what, how many hours each person has, and what margin the project leaves."},{"id":"1ef3f44c-ff09-4e43-acc9-8e82fae9b565","type":"callout","tone":"info","html":"When schedule, budget, and resources are not aligned, projects get delayed, costs explode, or the team ends up overloaded. This guide walks through how to connect the three pieces: schedule, project budgets, and team capacity, with practical examples and a review of the tools that actually help."},{"id":"a64c8330-e22b-45d2-a4ba-ae0e6a98e048","type":"toc"},{"id":"5c8a7b6c-2065-4e01-88b6-f167e8ef990f","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"1. What is project planning","anchorId":"que-es-planificacion"},{"id":"e23400fc-11bc-4da5-ae12-a79ff6b4ac6f","type":"paragraph","html":"Project planning is the part of project management where you define what needs to be done, in what order, with which resources, and within what timeframes. It is not just a task list: it is deciding the phases of a project, assigning responsibilities, estimating time and costs, and setting a clear framework for monitoring and evaluation. The scar appears when nobody really “agrees” on it and the project is redefined at the first crisis."},{"id":"3361b1cc-14be-4734-bcaf-3d29b8d5c949","type":"paragraph","html":"In practice, planning is usually organized into phases. Although each methodology names them differently (classic project management, Scrum, etc.), there is usually a start (scope and objectives), a planning phase (schedule, budget, resources), execution, and closure. What matters here is that in the planning phase you build the schedule, set the project budget, and decide how resources will cover the work."},{"id":"7ec4432f-2a37-4ed2-bb9c-783b2c4c5a42","type":"paragraph","html":"Without that foundation, the project becomes a chain of emergencies: you do not know whether you are on track until invoicing arrives or the client complains. That is why it makes sense to treat schedule, budget, and resources as a single system, not as three separate documents."},{"id":"5c4adf2e-4676-4431-a08a-9d943014cf23","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"The phases of a project (summary)"},{"id":"66c65672-0016-4a7f-8ca6-17faf1a923cc","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Start"},{"id":"4a6974a9-1ef7-4ef2-8170-109741f95972","type":"paragraph","html":"Scope and objectives"},{"id":"3097cc6e-bc2c-4935-9f64-184a8f364f37","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Planning"},{"id":"eaedfec4-2383-4eee-b88f-599d2f5d23c4","type":"paragraph","html":"Schedule, budget, resources"},{"id":"43a5726f-e059-46d6-9585-e227db9aad40","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Execution"},{"id":"786d7a98-915d-47b6-833c-47efc6a357ac","type":"paragraph","html":"Monitoring and adjustments"},{"id":"fa42d8da-5e76-49e8-be7b-e2d72df897b9","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Closure"},{"id":"45f41163-d067-418e-82a7-f53fee5c1ff1","type":"paragraph","html":"Evaluation and lessons learned"},{"id":"bb057097-1f30-4dd4-ac6c-255db02cee94","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"2. The schedule and the Gantt chart","anchorId":"cronograma-gantt"},{"id":"f55df96c-ec38-44c6-bbce-98f45b4e59c0","type":"paragraph","html":"A project schedule is the timeline of milestones and tasks: what is done and when. The most visual way to represent it is the Gantt chart: bars over a time scale that show the duration of each activity and, in many tools, the dependencies between them. It lets you see at a glance whether dates fit together and which tasks are critical. The scar is that the Gantt “fits” on screen… but when emergencies repeat, the same resource appears in three places at once."},{"id":"684995da-0389-421d-9685-4b25e307fbd9","type":"paragraph","html":"A well‑used Gantt chart helps you answer questions such as: when does each phase start and end? Which tasks block others? Are there obvious gaps or overlaps? Tools like online timelines or project‑management software usually include a Gantt view; you can also build a Gantt chart in Excel with a template or use a dedicated tool. The key is that the schedule is credible: it reflects real dependencies and, as far as possible, is aligned with the capacity of the people who will do the work."},{"id":"cbf62c1e-adfe-4f07-bf3c-fcb15bdd6a8e","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Task‑only schedule vs. schedule with resources"},{"id":"f095a26c-f9af-40cd-a279-ffaa845f5b83","type":"paragraph","html":"A classic Gantt shows deadlines; it usually does not show who does what or how many hours each person has."},{"id":"e26da8ce-ef96-4f2b-9f15-a595496a7dc3","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Only tasks and deadlines"},{"id":"7fcbd2db-0fbe-4765-9ff5-bd13240e3397","type":"paragraph","html":"You see dates and dependencies. You do not see whether the same person is on three projects in the same week."},{"id":"8d11469e-2ff1-4ebc-aee3-d7101cebee89","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Tasks + resources and hours"},{"id":"7ee381cd-7bbe-41ec-bfc0-5a26b0dac790","type":"paragraph","html":"A schedule aligned with capacity: who does what and with how many hours. It prevents hidden overloads."},{"id":"7fca7f8b-e142-4549-a313-3ebf6b287e2b","type":"callout","tone":"warning","html":"<strong>A common limitation of Gantt charts</strong> You can have a perfect schedule on paper and, in reality, three projects all asking for the same resource in the same week. That is why the logical next step is to connect the schedule with resources: who does what and with how many hours."},{"id":"3b4458b4-9f17-473e-86ee-b576ddbc2ecd","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"3. Project budget","anchorId":"presupuesto-triangulo"},{"id":"ec806a29-f877-4ebf-8277-2a3fba7fb3c7","type":"paragraph","html":"A project budget sets how much you are going to spend (or invest in hours and costs) to deliver the agreed scope. In many agencies and service teams, project budgets are built from hours: estimated hours by role or person, multiplied by a cost or selling rate. A project budget matrix can be broken down by phase, by work package, or by month, depending on how you bill or track performance. The scar is often that January when “X hours” are approved, and at the first scope change that number stops protecting you."},{"id":"5942c7c4-d301-424d-8367-14711c7094cb","type":"paragraph","html":"The relationship with the schedule is direct: if the schedule lengthens, actual hours tend to spike and the budget drifts. The classic project‑management triangle (scope, time, cost) is still alive: change one, and you typically affect the others."},{"id":"ea1f09b2-9c33-4998-bb13-aac56a51ca90","type":"paragraph","html":"That is why it makes sense for the budget not to be a standalone number, but hours and costs assigned to the same phases and tasks you already have in the schedule. Then, when you do tracking, you can compare budgeted hours with actual hours and see whether the project is still within margin."},{"id":"bdc944c6-8b27-4e6a-9963-47198fb9bb63","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"The scope–time–cost triangle"},{"id":"7a3ef1a3-dd77-47f7-83bf-baf3163f2719","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Scope"},{"id":"4152ad13-75e3-46f0-86ae-c2b14c0e32ae","type":"paragraph","html":"What is delivered (deliverables, requirements)"},{"id":"319fdf1b-71b9-41f7-90cd-bf474fc021cb","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Time"},{"id":"f760e793-02e7-4f35-b9a9-1afc8cff4e6f","type":"paragraph","html":"Deadlines and schedule"},{"id":"5e852675-d863-45be-9a22-c83daa8aa220","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Cost"},{"id":"4cd80ae8-32dd-4ce8-8316-888b5d54f65e","type":"paragraph","html":"Budget (hours × rate, other costs)"},{"id":"8294683b-baa7-4dde-8e10-1b6301a0588f","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Changing one usually impacts the other two. That is why the budget should be tied to the same phases and tasks as the schedule.</em>"},{"id":"17f43a8b-db85-418c-8739-a296d74df122","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"4. Resources and capacity","anchorId":"recursos-capacidad"},{"id":"7903ccfb-df11-4ef3-b211-81622462f12f","type":"paragraph","html":"The resources to deliver a project are, in most cases, people: their time and their capacity. Team capacity is the number of hours available in a period (day, week, month) after subtracting holidays, sick leave, and other absences. If you are not clear on how many hours each person has per week, it is very easy to assign more work than they can do or, conversely, leave capacity unused. What hurts is planning with “gross capacity” and discovering two weeks later that the real net capacity was much lower."},{"id":"ad4cd532-53d3-43ae-9f71-2871c39bed8f","type":"paragraph","html":"Hour allocation is the bridge between schedule and budget: who spends how many hours on which project each week. When that allocation is made explicitly (for example with a weekly or monthly hour‑based planner), you can see overloads and under‑utilization before they become delays or eaten‑up margins."},{"id":"408db063-c594-42e4-adca-47dd1a60f2f3","type":"paragraph","html":"This way of working is very close to timeboxing: assigning specific time blocks to projects or tasks instead of just listing tasks without time. We go deeper into the technique in the guide on what timeboxing is."},{"id":"a6e4283b-d24f-4bf9-92e9-32ea5c481c70","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"No visibility on capacity"},{"id":"55b479d6-d825-4bf4-a3b4-3084d9758fcf","type":"paragraph","html":"You assign tasks without knowing how many hours each person has. The result: overload, delays, and margins disappearing with nobody noticing in time."},{"id":"624b58bf-72a2-4a36-8aea-31669fc53ec4","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Hour‑based planning"},{"id":"028ada81-d238-4f86-8c89-4beb0e86c30c","type":"paragraph","html":"You see who has how many free hours and how many assigned hours per project. You spot overloads before they happen and adjust schedule or scope."},{"id":"5390fb20-a5aa-4f40-9c03-db40b9252de7","type":"paragraph","html":"what timeboxing is"},{"id":"afd8fc97-27fa-44d3-ba49-d4abb8033b39","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>In short: the schedule tells you when; the budget, how much; resources and capacity, who and with how many hours. Connecting all three prevents projects from living only in the task board and profitability being discovered when it is already too late.</strong>"},{"id":"cff8f654-54eb-4cdb-8f7a-b5696cd4ef7b","type":"callout","tone":"highlight","html":"<strong>💡 Taimbox capsule: Schedule and capacity in one place</strong> In Taimbox, the planner shows week by week who does what and with how many hours. That way you connect schedule, project budgets, and resources without having to juggle three tools."},{"id":"4e7c1f80-ca1f-4870-a3f5-215a46406753","type":"cta","text":"See the resource planner","href":"/planificador-recursos","variant":"primary"},{"id":"37216642-791a-4634-9a43-28038a898363","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"5. Monitoring, KPIs, and project dashboard","anchorId":"seguimiento-kpis"},{"id":"687d342a-9677-45b3-9563-c3b0882059fc","type":"paragraph","html":"Monitoring and evaluating projects means comparing plan and reality: progress, hours burned, costs, and, where relevant, client satisfaction. This is what indicators are for: a project KPI might be progress versus plan, actual hours versus budgeted hours, or the project’s current margin. The scar is when the dashboard “proves you right” too late: the client is already upset and you have already burned through the buffer."},{"id":"629958c8-098f-4991-9087-66c27e475a44","type":"paragraph","html":"A worthwhile project dashboard usually shows at least: the status of each project (on track, at risk, delayed), assigned hours vs. actual hours (or vs. budget), and workload per person or team. That way you see whether a project is eating more hours than planned and whether someone is over‑assigned."},{"id":"60b1fed6-5a4f-4ff9-b8dd-4a31e054c7be","type":"paragraph","html":"In a small or mid‑sized agency, having a single place where you can cross schedule, budget, and actual hours often makes the difference between reacting in time and finding out only once the client is already upset."},{"id":"e54e4fa6-fa8d-4057-b2db-4d0bb1d48b33","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Progress vs. plan"},{"id":"382a9b4c-910c-4349-9869-e1493971a7e3","type":"paragraph","html":"Are we where we should be? Percentage of tasks or milestones completed versus the schedule."},{"id":"897c0439-e725-435b-8c4e-f39e19fdb380","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Actual vs. budgeted hours"},{"id":"2e175593-e92e-47cf-ad8b-22e5abed05db","type":"paragraph","html":"Are we overshooting hours? If actual hours exceed planned hours, margin falls."},{"id":"72c6550b-11a8-480e-8fbe-873e54aeebde","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Project margin"},{"id":"d2534f88-014e-4b8d-8ad8-2e267d3e3517","type":"paragraph","html":"Revenue minus costs (hours × rate, etc.). The indicator that connects time and profitability."},{"id":"cc7163a7-054a-43b7-977e-e879fde4e0db","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"6. Project‑management tools","anchorId":"herramientas"},{"id":"c383cad4-a630-44c9-95c9-ca94570833c0","type":"paragraph","html":"Project‑management tools solve different needs. Kanban‑style boards (Trello, Asana, ClickUp, Notion for projects) are very useful for task status and workflow; many also include a schedule or Gantt‑chart view. The scar is having “three truths”: one for tasks, one for hours, and one for margin, and ending up deciding by gut feel in every crisis."},{"id":"30a29909-bb5b-4fdd-b813-3cf0a1247dd4","type":"paragraph","html":"To connect time, capacity, and profitability you need tools that work explicitly with hours. In Taimbox we focus on that layer: hour‑based resource planning, a schedule of who does what each week, and profitability reports by project and client."},{"id":"a1eb4844-9532-492e-bd77-01b2725b1392","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"What does each type of tool solve?"},{"id":"59afe2a0-1cd5-447d-bd70-5d0c2436a8cf","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Boards and Gantt charts"},{"id":"7da7d2f1-f078-410c-96f3-49a01bb1ef48","type":"paragraph","html":"Task status, workflow, dependencies, and deadlines. They usually do not show capacity or hours per person or margin by project."},{"id":"10885b02-bf4c-4794-887e-ea4463b7edec","type":"heading","level":4,"text":"Hour‑ and resource‑based planning"},{"id":"057c7f2c-ec0f-4f61-8d5a-8ab76cd90523","type":"paragraph","html":"Who does what and with how many hours. Project budgets tied to those hours and margin reports (planned vs. actual)."},{"id":"0681421c-eeb1-415b-a4bf-854cfada58f4","type":"callout","tone":"highlight","html":"<strong>📊 Taimbox capsule: Planner + profitability reports</strong> Plan by hours in the planner, track progress in the dashboard, and review margin by project and client in the profitability reports. All in a single platform."},{"id":"618d23f5-96d7-4fa4-a055-cfb64e18bb89","type":"cta","text":"Planner","href":"/planificador-recursos","variant":"primary"},{"id":"b9a6f7e7-3c6e-42bd-a857-237609dafa20","type":"cta","text":"Profitability reports","href":"/reportes-rentabilidad","variant":"secondary"},{"id":"ca8c6295-7656-4c67-ba40-6de10a1aa27b","type":"paragraph","html":"Details on plans and pricing are on the pricing page"},{"id":"5a932df4-7baa-4c1e-8fde-8cc253b2ef07","type":"paragraph","html":"Solid project planning means aligning schedule, budget, and resources: what is done and when, how much it costs, and who does it with how many hours. The Gantt chart and schedule are the visual foundation; project budgets and hour allocation are what keep things from remaining only intentions. Tracking with KPIs and a simple dashboard lets you correct course before the project goes completely off the rails."},{"id":"4c89b160-948a-4ed5-9282-2d4bd753e64e","type":"paragraph","html":"If your agency or team already uses task boards but you are missing that link between time, capacity, and profitability, trying an hour‑based planner may be the logical next step."},{"id":"f52d50c9-b8da-4256-b23c-16c99666e91f","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Frequently asked questions about project planning","anchorId":"preguntas-frecuentes"},{"id":"4ab4a179-9878-40ba-8bc9-c513557ed9a9","type":"faq","items":[{"q":"Is a Gantt chart enough to manage a project?","a":"For deadlines and dependencies, yes. To know whether you will hit the budget and whether your team has real capacity, no: you need to cross the schedule with hours per person and the project budget."},{"q":"Which project KPI makes the most sense in an agency?","a":"Actual vs. budgeted hours and margin by project (or by client). These are the ones that connect time and profitability. Progress versus schedule helps, but without hours and margin you cannot see whether the project is profitable."},{"q":"Can I use a Kanban board and an hour‑based planner at the same time?","a":"Yes. Many teams use Trello, Asana, or similar for day‑to‑day task management and an hour‑based planning tool (such as Taimbox) for capacity, budget, and margin. They complement each other: the board for workflow, the planner for time and money."}]},{"id":"06eeeb8e-7288-4b10-80d6-4c80ae10adfc","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Plan by hours and regain control of margin","anchorId":"cta-final"},{"id":"d55d7875-357c-4c17-81b8-94622dc5f665","type":"paragraph","html":"Schedule, budget, and resources in one place; you can explore Taimbox with no commitment."},{"id":"987855db-44bf-4dc7-bfe6-3ffff4d33343","type":"cta","text":"See the resource planner","href":"/planificador-recursos","variant":"primary"},{"id":"5270fbba-9ee8-4692-9104-69571409b087","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Written by the Taimbox team — Resource management and profitability for agencies.</em>"},{"id":"d3e38c32-7819-42db-bf86-7d3e6f78bc21","type":"relatedPost","slug":"que-es-timeboxing"}]'::jsonb,
  json_ld_es = '{"@context":"https://schema.org","@graph":[{"@type":"Article","headline":"Planificación de proyectos: cronograma, presupuesto y recursos (guía práctica)","description":"Guía práctica para unir cronograma, presupuesto y capacidad del equipo. Incluye diagrama de Gantt, fases del proyecto, KPIs y herramientas de gestión de proyectos.","author":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"publisher":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"datePublished":"2026-03-18","inLanguage":"es","mainEntityOfPage":{"@type":"WebPage","@id":"https://taimbox.com/blog/planificacion-proyectos-cronograma-recursos"}}]}'::jsonb,
  json_ld_en = '{"@context":"https://schema.org","@graph":[{"@type":"Article","headline":"Project Planning: Schedule, Budget, and Resources (Practical Guide)","description":"Practical guide to combine schedule, budget, and team capacity. Includes Gantt charts, project phases, KPIs, and PM tools.","author":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"publisher":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"datePublished":"2026-03-18","inLanguage":"en","mainEntityOfPage":{"@type":"WebPage","@id":"https://taimbox.com/en/blog/project-planning-schedule-resources"}}]}'::jsonb
WHERE slug = 'planificacion-proyectos-cronograma-recursos';

-- kpis-agencias-marketing-2026
UPDATE public.blog_posts SET
  blocks_es = '[{"id":"3c60c67d-88d9-42e0-8743-4c0eff3e3422","type":"paragraph","html":"Medir la productividad en una fábrica es sencillo: cuentas unidades producidas. En una agencia creativa o de marketing, es un campo de minas. ¿Estar ocupado es ser productivo? No necesariamente. Si tu equipo está al límite de capacidad pero los proyectos no salen o el margen se esfuma, el problema suele ser de visibilidad, no de esfuerzo."},{"id":"211579e9-2ff7-4726-b08f-4382afee3ba2","type":"paragraph","html":"En 2026, además, la pregunta ya no es solo qué KPI mirar: es cuánto tiempo te va a costar medirlo bien cada semana. El coste oculto no es la fórmula; es la fricción: perseguir datos, reconciliar hojas y convencer a todo el mundo de que rellene la misma plantilla."},{"id":"5e587c56-5565-43cb-9ab6-e1f3eac4ee48","type":"callout","tone":"info","html":"Cronograma, Gantt y recursos los tratamos a fondo enPlanificación de proyectos: cronograma, presupuesto y recursos. En este texto el foco es qué medir, con qué frecuencia y qué hacer cuando el número sale mal."},{"id":"d2e7e03f-5eee-44b7-82be-0fd1ab85562e","type":"toc"},{"id":"dae9e757-5319-44de-927a-4e9cec35f22a","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Tabla rápida: qué mide cada KPI y qué decisión habilita","anchorId":"tabla-kpis"},{"id":"b5897ad2-f130-47e0-9052-c8b6101f0310","type":"paragraph","html":"Tabla rápida: qué mide cada KPI y qué decisión habilitaTercera columna a propósitoejecutiva: si el KPI no te ayuda a decidir algo incómodo (contratar, subir precio, cortar scope), no es un KPI; es un adorno. En la práctica, lo notas cuando el comité mira el número y la conversación se queda en “vale… ¿y ahora qué?”."},{"id":"cebc5b77-95ce-40fd-8225-d8e26b7c5b6f","type":"table","headers":["KPI","Qué mide","Decisión que habilita"],"rows":[["Utilización","Horas de trabajo útil (cliente/producción) frente a capacidad neta.","Decidir si contratar, frenar ventas o mover horas de interno a cliente."],["Rentabilidad + pacing","Margen por proyecto y ritmo de consumo de horas vs. el mes.","Decidir si subir fee, recortar alcance o replanificar antes de facturar."],["Estimado vs real","Precisión de presupuestos y plannings.","Decidir buffers y plantillas de presupuesto por tipo de entregable."],["Capacidad por área","Dónde está el cuello de botella (Paid, Diseño, etc.).","Decidir si externalizar, reasignar entre departamentos o negociar plazos."],["OKRs / objetivos","Si el esfuerzo se traduce en resultados de negocio.","Decidir si los KR miden actividad o impacto; alinear estrategia y margen."]]},{"id":"c9476764-169b-4bee-b987-d093bb0d3728","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"1. Tasa de utilización (carga útil vs capacidad)","anchorId":"kpi-utilizacion"},{"id":"979010fd-9b79-4170-b70c-5ac6b189a446","type":"paragraph","html":"Es el KPI operativo por excelencia: qué parte del tiempo disponible del equipo va a trabajo que alimenta ingresos o producción frente a capacidad real (descontando ausencias). Fórmula típica:<strong>(horas en trabajo de cliente o producción / horas disponibles netas) × 100</strong>. Define en el equipo qué contáis como «disponible» y qué horas son de cliente vs internas para que el número sea comparable mes a mes."},{"id":"739a15aa-525a-4656-a03f-d9e03c9268c1","type":"paragraph","html":"Un rango orientativo en muchas agencias de servicios ronda el 70–85%; el mix de negocio (retainers, proyectos puntuales, I+D interna) cambia el objetivo. No es una verdad absoluta. Se ve clarísimo cuando “estamos a tope” en el standup… pero en dos días el proyecto ya va tarde y el margen empieza a temblar."},{"id":"37ac612c-f12c-4b08-80a5-dcae7998e957","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>Si lo haces a mano:</strong> puedes obtener el mismo número con papel y boli o una hoja de cálculo: horas por persona y semana, capacidad neta (restando ausencias) y qué parte va a cliente o producción frente al total. Es farragoso, pero el KPI es el mismo; el coste es el tiempo de actualizarlo cada semana. Una estructura de partida —inventario de horas, cuadrante y % de carga— está en laplantilla de planificación de recursos para agencias (Excel o Sheets, con descarga)."},{"id":"45a81733-9d3f-4bbd-90b4-e2b5ef9eb3bc","type":"paragraph","html":"En<strong>Taimbox</strong> ves la carga por persona y semana frente a la capacidad en el tablero de capacidad del equipo y en las vistas de planificación, sin depender de una hoja paralela que se quede obsoleta."},{"id":"3b4bd5f2-2acb-48e9-ac4a-1cf1135c0fdb","type":"callout","tone":"warning","html":"<strong>Si el número está alto o bajo</strong><br/><br/><strong>Por encima de ~90%:</strong>  no celebres el «lleno». Es señal de riesgo de quemazo y errores. Sube tarifas, contrata o reduce ventas a corto plazo; el sobreesfuerzo sostenido precede a la fuga de talento.<br/><br/><strong>Muy por debajo del rango esperado:</strong>  revisa pipeline y precios, y si demasiadas horas viven en interno o administración que podrían asignarse a cliente con mejor comercialización."},{"id":"dd6a8038-af9d-486f-9bca-074d22c14eff","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"2. Rentabilidad por proyecto y pacing (ritmo)","anchorId":"kpi-rentabilidad"},{"id":"203f3718-c4ba-453d-9f75-a2c97553547a","type":"paragraph","html":"No todos los fees mensuales son iguales: algunos se ven jugosos hasta que sumas revisiones infinitas. La rentabilidad por proyecto relaciona<strong>ingreso</strong> (fee, devengo) con<strong>coste de horas</strong> y te dice si ese cliente es sostenible."},{"id":"ec7a2303-8f4b-447e-93f5-62b5c8c25a3c","type":"paragraph","html":"En 2026 las agencias no pueden esperar al cierre de mes para saber si un proyecto se comió el margen. Hace falta pacing: comparar el consumo de horas con el tiempo transcurrido del mes (¿vas por delante o por detrás del ritmo?). Si a mitad de mes ya vas desproporcionado, la conversación con el cliente va con tiempo. La cicatriz típica: “vamos bien” hasta el día 12, y de repente todo el mundo empieza a preguntarte por el mismo proyecto… con el Excel ya en versiones y el cliente ya en modo urgencia."},{"id":"66f6fea6-5e8d-477f-90f5-240ed4793f73","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>Si lo haces en Excel:</strong> basta una fila por proyecto con fee del mes, horas consumidas, horas presupuestadas y una columna con el porcentaje de mes transcurrido; si las horas consumidas crecen más rápido que el calendario, el pacing va mal. El truco es mantener los datos al día sin pelearse con cinco versiones de la misma hoja."},{"id":"ce59b0e9-f0c3-4f4a-8869-8a84a678f18b","type":"paragraph","html":"En<strong>Taimbox</strong>, la<strong>salud financiera</strong> y elreportes de rentabilidad conectan presupuesto en horas, fee y ritmo de consumo para que no te enteres tarde."},{"id":"6a55b427-929a-4365-80fe-6d00e6bfe19a","type":"callout","tone":"info","html":"<strong>Ejemplo con números (mitad de mes)</strong> Tienes un fee de<strong>60 h</strong> para el mes. A día<strong>15</strong> suele haber pasado<strong>~50 %</strong> del calendario: a ese ritmo \"equilibrado\" llevarías unas<strong>30 h</strong> consumidas (la mitad del cupo). Si a esa fecha el equipo lleva 40 h imputadas, vas 10 h por encima del ritmo esperado; en una sola métrica, el pacing ronda el 133 % frente al tiempo transcurrido (40 frente a 30: has usado 40/60 del fee cuando el reloj solo marca el 50 % del mes)."},{"id":"3ca263bd-8cf9-4a1e-b3b3-a62af555428f","type":"callout","tone":"warning","html":"<strong>Si el número está alto o bajo</strong><br/><br/><strong>Pacing en rojo a mitad de mes:</strong>  conversación de alcance, pausa en scope o repriorizar equipo<br/><br/><strong> Margen alto pero caos operativo:</strong>  atesora el margen pero documenta el proceso; puede no repetirse si el equipo no aguanta el ritmo."},{"id":"8efec84c-a977-4fb1-add4-61995044e2fd","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"3. Desviación entre estimación y realidad","anchorId":"kpi-estimacion"},{"id":"8f6b96f1-4700-47e8-ab17-3b58c5499ef6","type":"paragraph","html":"Fórmula útil:<strong>(horas reales − horas estimadas) / horas estimadas</strong> por tipo de trabajo o proyecto. Sirve para<strong>aprender a presupuestar</strong>, no para castigar al project manager en público: si el diseño siempre se sale un 20%, el siguiente presupuesto lleva ese buffer explícito. En la vida real, te lo pregunta el director cuando ya estás en la fase de “otra ronda más” y aún no sabes si la desviación era un bache o el patrón."},{"id":"8f72c3fa-afc3-468f-881b-11c92220cfc0","type":"paragraph","html":"Si lo haces a mano: una tabla en Excel (o en tu ERP) con columnas de estimado y real por proyecto o tipo de entregable; un filtro por disciplina te muestra si la desviación es sistemática. Las retrospectivas al cerrar proyecto son el momento de actualizar los ratios para el siguiente presupuesto."},{"id":"e6bdefaa-9bb8-40d9-9c08-1183ac0301d4","type":"callout","tone":"warning","html":"<strong>Si el número está alto o bajo</strong><br/><br/><strong>Desviación sistemática (ej. +20%) en un tipo de entregable:</strong>  añade buffer en la plantilla de presupuesto y un mini checklist de alcance en la propuesta.<br/><br/><strong> Si siempre aciertas por suerte:</strong>  revisa si estás sobreasignando horas internas no registradas."},{"id":"dae000a2-6e73-4bcb-b3ae-081abb160dfd","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"4. Capacidad por departamento o skill","anchorId":"kpi-departamento"},{"id":"f5fe2094-20cc-4411-aa61-6acdb9847d99","type":"paragraph","html":"A veces la agencia «está a tope» pero solo un área (Paid, producción, diseño) arrastra el cuello de botella. Sin esta vista, mezclas sensación global con datos y tomas decisiones tarde. Se nota cuando el resto del equipo va “verde” en la semana… y diseño/producción se come la cola sin que nadie lo vea hasta que se entregan tarde."},{"id":"802a4858-de51-46ef-815b-fe47fee39cbb","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>Si lo haces a mano:</strong> una matriz simple (incluso en Excel) con departamentos en filas y horas cargadas o % de capacidad por semana; o una reunión breve semanal donde cada lead declare estado (verde/ámbar/rojo) en su equipo. Sin granularidad por área, solo ves el promedio y no sabes dónde meter refuerzo."},{"id":"8687ee90-b716-4f22-bd0a-726a3de518ff","type":"callout","tone":"warning","html":"<strong>Si el número está alto o bajo</strong><br/><br/><strong>Un solo departamento en rojo:</strong>  reasignar entre áreas, externalizar una pieza o negociar plazos con el cliente.<br/><br/><strong> Todos en verde pero facturación floja:</strong>  el problema es de pipeline o precio, no de capacidad horaria."},{"id":"ad5583cf-77bb-4236-a241-3cadd1f258d7","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"5. Alineación con OKRs y objetivos trimestrales","anchorId":"kpi-okrs"},{"id":"5c02603f-8504-471f-ae88-77ffb3772f5b","type":"paragraph","html":"La productividad no es solo «picar horas»: es avanzar hacia objetivos que importan al negocio. Este KPI mide<strong>eficacia</strong> (¿vamos donde dijimos?), no solo eficiencia. Si la utilización es alta pero los resultados estratégicos no llegan, algo desalinea prioridades. Lo ves cuando los OKRs van “cumplidos” por entregables… pero el margen y la retención siguen igual, y te toca explicar por qué en dirección."},{"id":"a8ea2224-472a-4a67-b3f7-2f11eb7373ec","type":"paragraph","html":"Si lo haces a mano: una tabla con key results, responsable y % de avance (Notion, Google Sheets o Excel) más una revisión trimestral sincera. Lo importante es que los KR no midan solo actividad: si el margen sube pero el resultado de negocio no, el indicador estratégico está mal elegido."},{"id":"313d67c0-3e4f-4bee-90c1-edc23a64a4e3","type":"callout","tone":"warning","html":"<strong>Si el número está alto o bajo</strong><br/><br/><strong>OKRs «verdes» pero margen malo:</strong>  revisa si los key results miden actividad (reuniones, entregas) en lugar de resultado de negocio.<br/><br/><strong> Buen margen pero OKRs en rojo:</strong>  riesgo de optimizar el corto plazo y descuidar posición estratégica (marca, producto, retención)."},{"id":"c6f67a28-d3aa-4af5-a8df-5e92df7d5e96","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Excel vs una herramienta integrada: fricción y tiempo","anchorId":"excel-vs-taimbox"},{"id":"ae8e8d68-2174-42f3-bd33-75519b080404","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>Sí, puedes cerrar esta pestaña y seguir con Excel.</strong> Todo lo anterior es aplicable con método, reuniones y plantillas: el valor educativo no depende de una herramienta concreta. Si ya tienes tablas que cuadran y un ritual semanal que las alimenta, no necesitas cambiar nada por leer este artículo."},{"id":"4443487a-d089-42fe-b20b-a3e15faf702c","type":"paragraph","html":"Donde muchos equipos se atascan no es en la fórmula, sino en el coste de mantenerla:<strong>arqueología de datos</strong> — perseguir a la gente para que rellene horas, cuadrar versiones y reconciliar el fee del mes con las horas consumidas cuando el ritmo del proyecto ya se desvió hace diez días. El problema no es solo que Excel sea estático; es que el día a día de una agencia es líquido. En algún punto, esa liquidez te explota en la cara: el lunes ya tienes “versión 4”, el martes hay cambios y el jueves nadie quiere tocar el archivo."},{"id":"c63ca662-c0c5-4003-a19b-ad9ee9b79dd8","type":"paragraph","html":"En 2026 el sector empuja hacia herramientas que reducen trabajo manual en reporting; lo que importa para tu agencia es si la métrica nace de cómo trabajáis (planificación y seguimiento de horas en flujo), no de un lunes de «montar el cuadro de mando»."},{"id":"d9251e8a-baef-42e6-9c42-ac52e1c38899","type":"paragraph","html":"Ahí es donde una<strong>plataforma integrada</strong> entra en juego: no sustituye el criterio humano, pero concentra planificación y lectura de carga y margen para que dediques las reuniones a decidir, no a discutir si el número es el de la versión 3 o la 4 del Excel. En<strong>Taimbox</strong>, las métricas que antes montabas a mano se derivan de la planificación y del seguimiento de horas en el mismo flujo, con mucha menos fricción que reconciliar hojas cada lunes."},{"id":"58b1bce6-e080-43e2-bb51-b2b02c726b14","type":"callout","tone":"highlight","html":"El valor no es solo el dato: es la<strong>fricción casi cero</strong> cuando las métricas se derivan de la planificación y del registro de horas en el mismo sitio."},{"id":"85014645-6ee9-4f0e-941c-fca81b0dfea1","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Por si quieres verlo en la herramienta","anchorId":"links"},{"id":"17cfe765-6c29-4639-a37c-870f06677994","type":"paragraph","html":"Laguía de funcionalidades recorre planificador, informes y equipos con vistas parecidas a lo que hemos contado arriba (capacidad, rentabilidad, departamentos). Si eres de los que prefieren “verlo una vez” antes de montar otro Excel desde cero, aquí es donde encaja."},{"id":"a129e5d8-dee9-4f58-bb2b-b669c775a6f3","type":"cta","text":"Planificador","href":"/planificador-recursos","variant":"primary"},{"id":"45bf0f10-67c3-4784-90d0-9792144c5b47","type":"cta","text":"Reportes de rentabilidad","href":"/reportes-rentabilidad","variant":"secondary"},{"id":"cbe97a00-2ab8-4631-9626-caaa9b06be5e","type":"cta","text":"Integraciones","href":"/integraciones","variant":"secondary"},{"id":"b22b49f0-dcf3-4f97-a434-9d2f7acbe347","type":"paragraph","html":"Medir productividad no es vigilar al equipo: es darles visibilidad para que el trabajo rentable se vea y la agencia sea sostenible. Cuando el trabajo se estira sin freno, suele aparecer en la misma conversación laLey de Parkinson y eltimeboxing: límites de tiempo y plazos como contrapeso cultural."},{"id":"fb4cdfc2-624b-4454-8b61-9049cfad9fd7","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Rentabilidad con cifras claras","anchorId":"cta-final"},{"id":"f8404006-9d6e-4980-a3e2-f2250008d09c","type":"paragraph","html":"Capacidad y ritmo de proyectos en un solo flujo en<strong>Taimbox</strong>, para quien ya haya cerrado Excel los lunes. Sin compromiso al empezar."},{"id":"9ca9c890-205f-4775-9865-65ea43659ba0","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>La cicatriz final suele ser la misma: el día que preguntas “¿por qué el margen no aparece?”, te responden con un “porque el mes se nos fue”, y tú quieres que el número te diga dónde se fugó.</em>"},{"id":"2e468550-b2cd-4cc6-9f4c-f37886002290","type":"cta","text":"Ver rentabilidad y forecast","href":"/reportes-rentabilidad","variant":"primary"},{"id":"c4808ddb-7cba-4b7a-85c1-c1c32febc4e2","type":"cta","text":"Planificador de recursos","href":"/planificador-recursos","variant":"secondary"},{"id":"60466cba-a85d-4f15-a765-0b4372fe7ba4","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Escrito por el equipo de Taimbox — Gestión de recursos y rentabilidad para agencias.</em>"},{"id":"a5c5f507-0617-40b5-85ad-9e12d08bce81","type":"relatedPost","slug":"planificacion-proyectos-cronograma-recursos"}]'::jsonb,
  blocks_en = '[{"id":"99dad54a-727b-46fe-946f-7210436ddbad","type":"paragraph","html":"Measuring productivity in a factory is simple: you count units produced. In a creative or marketing agency, it is a minefield. Is being busy the same as being productive? Not necessarily. If your team is at full capacity but projects do not ship or margin disappears, the problem is usually visibility, not effort."},{"id":"c3a1c082-71c3-494c-b871-a81c41f82e6e","type":"paragraph","html":"In 2026, the question is no longer just which KPI to look at: it is how much time it will cost you to measure it properly every week. The hidden cost is not the formula; it is the friction: chasing data, reconciling spreadsheets, and convincing everyone to fill in the same template."},{"id":"43023c4d-acbb-466b-abf2-44acf414f282","type":"callout","tone":"info","html":"We go deep into timelines, Gantt charts, and resources inProject planning: schedule, budget, and resources. In this article the focus is what to measure, how often, and what to do when the number looks bad."},{"id":"31cd3a08-a67c-473f-a132-d5e91f5042f0","type":"toc"},{"id":"0d88fba2-b8de-4132-aec6-8ab58a121a58","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Quick table: what each KPI measures and what decision it enables","anchorId":"tabla-kpis"},{"id":"b1da7312-5420-44d2-9c08-3aba136f4322","type":"paragraph","html":"Quick table: what each KPI measures and what decision it enablesThird column is deliberatelyexecutive: if the KPI does not help you take an uncomfortable decision (hire, raise prices, cut scope), it is not a KPI; it is decoration. In practice, you notice it when the leadership team looks at the number and the conversation stalls at “okay… so now what?”."},{"id":"879b68d2-accf-4e74-8b7c-79858d7abd06","type":"table","headers":["KPI","What it measures","Decision it enables"],"rows":[["Utilisation","Hours of productive work (client/production) versus net capacity.","Decide whether to hire, slow down sales, or move hours from internal work to client work."],["Profitability + pacing","Margin per project and pace of hour consumption versus the month.","Decide whether to raise the fee, cut scope, or re‑plan before invoicing."],["Estimated vs actual","Accuracy of budgets and plans.","Decide buffers and budget templates by type of deliverable."],["Capacity by area","Where the bottleneck really is (Paid, Design, etc.).","Decide whether to outsource, reassign between departments, or renegotiate deadlines."],["OKRs / goals","Whether effort turns into business outcomes.","Decide whether key results are measuring activity or impact; align strategy and margin."]]},{"id":"a386dbd9-fbb8-4b5b-88b5-be88f4d044c5","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"1. Utilisation rate (productive load vs. capacity)","anchorId":"kpi-utilizacion"},{"id":"5a6c1e4e-5835-47e2-a422-fa568a1184f8","type":"paragraph","html":"This is the operational KPI par excellence: what share of the team’s available time goes to work that feeds revenue or production versus real capacity (after subtracting absences). Typical formula:<strong>(client or production hours / net available hours) × 100</strong>. Agree as a team what counts as “available” and which hours are client vs. internal so the number is comparable month to month."},{"id":"24437ad8-3195-4b23-8f6a-208144e3fb0a","type":"paragraph","html":"A rough benchmark in many service agencies is 70–85%; your business mix (retainers, one‑off projects, internal R&D) changes the target. It is not an absolute truth. You feel it when “we are slammed” in the stand‑up… but two days later the project is already late and margin starts to shake."},{"id":"6b8dcf25-05e6-4cff-8973-985941c13149","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>If you do it manually:</strong> you can get the same number with pen and paper or a spreadsheet: hours per person and week, net capacity (after absences), and what share goes to client or production work versus total. It is tedious, but the KPI is the same; the cost is the time it takes to update it every week. A starting structure —inventory of hours, grid, and load %— lives in theresource planning template for agencies (Excel or Sheets, ready to download)."},{"id":"772af302-ab8e-4f7a-9f1c-111c60d436c4","type":"paragraph","html":"In<strong>Taimbox</strong> you see per‑person weekly load versus capacity in the team‑capacity board and planning views, without relying on a parallel spreadsheet that goes stale."},{"id":"52fc3db5-f6ea-423c-8bc8-8f814d519aa1","type":"callout","tone":"warning","html":"<strong>If the number is high or low</strong><br/><br/><strong>Above ~90%:</strong>  do not celebrate being “full”. It is a risk signal for burnout and errors. Raise prices, hire, or slow down sales in the short term; sustained overwork precedes talent churn.<br/><br/><strong>Well below the expected range:</strong>  review pipeline and pricing, and whether too many hours live in internal work or admin that could be turned into client work with better packaging."},{"id":"84b4a945-4ee8-4319-9619-ee807949def3","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"2. Profitability per project and pacing (rhythm)","anchorId":"kpi-rentabilidad"},{"id":"29b780eb-84c2-4d02-9ebf-e67a6250f4f3","type":"paragraph","html":"Not all monthly retainers are created equal: some look juicy until you add up endless revisions. Profitability per project relates<strong>revenue</strong> (fee, accrual) with<strong>hour cost</strong> and tells you whether that client is sustainable."},{"id":"3b3336b0-6416-44a5-b471-4ecce238f07f","type":"paragraph","html":"In 2026, agencies cannot wait until month‑end close to find out whether a project has eaten the margin. You need pacing: comparing hour consumption with time elapsed in the month (are you ahead of or behind the ideal pace?). If you are already off‑track halfway through the month, the conversation with the client still has time. The typical scar: “we’re fine” until day 12, and suddenly everyone is asking about the same project… with the spreadsheet already in multiple versions and the client in emergency mode."},{"id":"2a4afb11-ffb1-4f6c-bf65-468c9511c6b0","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>If you do it in Excel:</strong> a single row per project with monthly fee, hours consumed, budgeted hours, and a column with the percentage of month elapsed is enough; if hours grow faster than the calendar, pacing is off. The trick is keeping data up to date without fighting five versions of the same sheet."},{"id":"6f0d2927-207c-431d-a85f-edfe2c74644d","type":"paragraph","html":"In<strong>Taimbox</strong>,<strong>financial health</strong> and theprofitability reports connect budgeted hours, fee, and consumption pace so you do not find out too late."},{"id":"f3b716e9-6557-4841-8c31-5a75135115a9","type":"callout","tone":"info","html":"<strong>Example with numbers (mid‑month)</strong> You have a fee of<strong>60 h</strong> for the month. On day<strong>15</strong> roughly<strong>~50%</strong> of the calendar has passed: at that “balanced” pace you would have around<strong>30 h</strong> burned (half the allowance). If by that date the team has logged 40 h, you are 10 h above the expected pace; in a single metric, pacing is around 133% versus time elapsed (40 vs. 30: you have used 40/60 of the fee when the clock only marks 50% of the month)."},{"id":"671a041d-8a13-46ff-9961-d5a6b61312d5","type":"callout","tone":"warning","html":"<strong>If the number is high or low</strong><br/><br/><strong>Pacing in the red halfway through the month:</strong>  talk scope, pause work, or reprioritise the team<br/><br/><strong> High margin but operational chaos:</strong>  enjoy the margin but document the process; it may not repeat if the team cannot sustain the rhythm."},{"id":"21bb4757-25da-4c88-abf1-f805d5dfa755","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"3. Deviation between estimate and reality","anchorId":"kpi-estimacion"},{"id":"3a3e0b3f-c6c6-455a-a166-a82fea3c5feb","type":"paragraph","html":"A useful formula:<strong>(actual hours − estimated hours) / estimated hours</strong> by type of work or project. It is there to help you<strong>learn to budget</strong>, not to publicly punish the project manager: if design always runs 20% over, the next budget carries that buffer explicitly. In real life, the director asks about it when you are already in the “one more round” phase and you still do not know whether the deviation was a one‑off or the pattern."},{"id":"263b8ec6-75d2-4ca9-9fe3-643e7f6d235c","type":"paragraph","html":"If you do it manually: a table in Excel (or your ERP) with estimated and actual by project or deliverable type; a discipline‑level filter shows whether the deviation is systematic. Project retrospectives at closing time are when you update the ratios for the next budget."},{"id":"4b7d6d2e-5ccd-4612-92e1-262a49f16926","type":"callout","tone":"warning","html":"<strong>If the number is high or low</strong><br/><br/><strong>Systematic deviation (e.g. +20%) for a type of deliverable:</strong>  add buffer in the budget template and a short scope checklist in the proposal.<br/><br/><strong> If you always “nail it” by luck:</strong>  check whether you are over‑assigning unlogged internal hours."},{"id":"d759500d-a919-468a-9621-844d97ec9070","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"4. Capacity by department or skill","anchorId":"kpi-departamento"},{"id":"b0a3e337-4aaa-4d6a-958a-4c6dac8063f9","type":"paragraph","html":"Sometimes the agency is “at full capacity”, but only one area (Paid, production, design) is dragging the bottleneck. Without this view, you mix gut feeling with data and decide too late. You see it when the rest of the team is “green” for the week… and design/production is drowning in a queue nobody sees until deliveries are late."},{"id":"e1b10e53-a8a1-4ccc-b0d6-c55728fdc59c","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>If you do it manually:</strong> a simple matrix (even in Excel) with departments in rows and hours loaded or % capacity per week; or a short weekly meeting where each lead states their team’s status (green/amber/red). Without per‑area granularity, you only see the average and have no idea where to add support."},{"id":"3016cd1e-fcc8-435b-a2a2-5345a3b6ccc7","type":"callout","tone":"warning","html":"<strong>If the number is high or low</strong><br/><br/><strong>A single department in the red:</strong>  reassign between areas, outsource a piece, or renegotiate deadlines with the client.<br/><br/><strong> Everyone in the green but weak revenue:</strong>  the problem is pipeline or pricing, not hours capacity."},{"id":"fa2366bd-15de-46e6-8c2f-0fd7920ac5d0","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"5. Alignment with OKRs and quarterly goals","anchorId":"kpi-okrs"},{"id":"70a03220-aef6-44cd-8867-f53ad428da56","type":"paragraph","html":"Productivity is not just “logging hours”: it is moving towards goals that matter for the business. This KPI measures<strong>effectiveness</strong> (are we going where we said we would?), not just efficiency. If utilisation is high but strategic results do not show up, something is mis‑aligning priorities. You notice it when OKRs look “green” on deliverables… but margin and retention stay flat and you have to explain why to leadership."},{"id":"d50fa795-fab8-4f5a-a95f-f33c99f61fc7","type":"paragraph","html":"If you do it manually: a table with key results, owner, and % progress (Notion, Google Sheets, or Excel) plus an honest quarterly review. The key is that KRs do not just measure activity: if margin goes up but business outcomes do not, the strategic indicator is poorly chosen."},{"id":"3d1db472-c1f0-49ff-933f-3df5432098e5","type":"callout","tone":"warning","html":"<strong>If the number is high or low</strong><br/><br/><strong>OKRs “green” but poor margin:</strong>  review whether key results measure activity (meetings, deliverables) instead of business outcome.<br/><br/><strong> Strong margin but OKRs in the red:</strong>  you may be over‑optimising the short term and neglecting strategic position (brand, product, retention)."},{"id":"dd7bb009-e944-4fac-91d4-8e4a6237fe8e","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Excel vs. an integrated tool: friction and time","anchorId":"excel-vs-taimbox"},{"id":"7298f5b2-3fe6-465a-be64-dd994edefe4a","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>Yes, you can close this tab and stick with Excel.</strong> Everything above applies with method, meetings, and templates: the educational value does not depend on a specific tool. If you already have sheets that reconcile and a weekly ritual that feeds them, you do not need to change anything just because you read this article."},{"id":"989cc585-892c-4682-a331-64b89a0a5b5c","type":"paragraph","html":"Where most teams get stuck is not the formula; it is the cost of maintaining it:<strong>data archaeology</strong> — chasing people to log hours, reconciling versions, and tying the monthly fee to hours consumed when the project’s pace drifted ten days ago. The problem is not only that Excel is static; it is that an agency’s day‑to‑day is liquid. At some point that liquidity blows up in your face: by Monday you already have “version 4”, Tuesday brings changes, and by Thursday nobody wants to touch the file."},{"id":"399735b9-8452-4f8e-8e33-debd81a27435","type":"paragraph","html":"In 2026 the industry is moving towards tools that reduce manual reporting work; what matters for your agency is whether the metric is born from how you work (planning and hour tracking in flow), not from a Monday spent “building the dashboard”."},{"id":"3d76feee-fa18-4294-b667-618080c50124","type":"paragraph","html":"That is where an<strong>integrated platform</strong> comes in: it does not replace human judgement, but it concentrates planning and the reading of load and margin so you spend meetings deciding, not arguing over whether the number is from Excel version 3 or 4. In<strong>Taimbox</strong>, the metrics you used to build by hand are derived from planning and time tracking in the same flow, with far less friction than reconciling sheets every Monday."},{"id":"c15b3f5d-a818-416e-9361-89e5c97649e2","type":"callout","tone":"highlight","html":"The value is not just the data: it is the<strong>near‑zero friction</strong> when metrics are derived from planning and time tracking in the same place."},{"id":"c4d5ba7f-3d86-4a16-a086-820e74cafad7","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"If you want to see it in the product","anchorId":"links"},{"id":"e24d353c-d195-4729-b633-a56f71df1873","type":"paragraph","html":"Thefeature guide walks through planner, reports, and team views similar to what we have described above (capacity, profitability, departments). If you are the type who prefers “seeing it once” before building yet another spreadsheet from scratch, this is where it fits."},{"id":"f991b9f4-90ed-4690-9d0c-276ba697c35e","type":"cta","text":"Planner","href":"/planificador-recursos","variant":"primary"},{"id":"22a1e169-0192-48ee-a7b5-32a0fe47b770","type":"cta","text":"Profitability reports","href":"/reportes-rentabilidad","variant":"secondary"},{"id":"fe37bef3-448a-4918-b7c5-868e523ce306","type":"cta","text":"Integrations","href":"/integraciones","variant":"secondary"},{"id":"afb678ef-7715-4370-8a21-4d0e2e14debe","type":"paragraph","html":"Measuring productivity is not about policing the team: it is about giving them visibility so profitable work is visible and the agency is sustainable. When work stretches without limits, the same conversation tends to bring upParkinson’s Law andtimeboxing: time limits and deadlines as a cultural counterweight."},{"id":"8eed4623-ed3e-4fea-84b3-53d554f4b7cf","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Profitability with clear numbers","anchorId":"cta-final"},{"id":"67f9095c-a168-4fd5-ad84-ae2cdb3a232d","type":"paragraph","html":"Capacity and project pace in a single flow in<strong>Taimbox</strong>, for those who have already closed Excel on Mondays. No commitment to get started."},{"id":"85c7dc54-8650-4075-87b7-c1af73e8aaa7","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>The final scar is usually the same: the day you ask “why isn’t the margin showing up?”, the answer is “because the month ran away from us”, and you want the number to tell you where it leaked.</em>"},{"id":"c7044c55-9ec7-49cf-82b1-1df5295f5443","type":"cta","text":"See profitability and forecast","href":"/reportes-rentabilidad","variant":"primary"},{"id":"ce7b81e5-314c-4817-a937-960b67484c19","type":"cta","text":"Resource planner","href":"/planificador-recursos","variant":"secondary"},{"id":"c6df4876-b2f6-48e6-bf68-ae115a5badce","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Written by the Taimbox team — Resource management and profitability for agencies.</em>"},{"id":"72a766c9-cd77-41ed-8927-0354ef62cc3d","type":"relatedPost","slug":"planificacion-proyectos-cronograma-recursos"}]'::jsonb,
  json_ld_es = '{"@context":"https://schema.org","@graph":[{"@type":"Article","headline":"Los 15 KPIs esenciales para agencias de marketing en 2026","description":"Guía completa de métricas financieras y operativas para medir la salud de tu agencia de marketing y tomar decisiones basadas en datos.","author":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"publisher":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"datePublished":"2026-03-23","inLanguage":"es","mainEntityOfPage":{"@type":"WebPage","@id":"https://taimbox.com/blog/kpis-agencias-marketing-2026"}}]}'::jsonb,
  json_ld_en = '{"@context":"https://schema.org","@graph":[{"@type":"Article","headline":"The 15 essential KPIs for marketing agencies in 2026","description":"Complete guide to financial and operational metrics to measure the health of your marketing agency and make data-driven decisions.","author":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"publisher":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"datePublished":"2026-03-23","inLanguage":"en","mainEntityOfPage":{"@type":"WebPage","@id":"https://taimbox.com/en/blog/marketing-agency-kpis-2026"}}]}'::jsonb
WHERE slug = 'kpis-agencias-marketing-2026';

-- plantilla-planificacion-recursos-agencia
UPDATE public.blog_posts SET
  blocks_es = '[{"id":"062b1ed0-2f34-4ffc-9d1a-29387239e3f1","type":"paragraph","html":"Todas las agencias empiezan igual: un Excel con nombres en columna, proyectos en fila y una fórmula que suma horas. Funciona mientras el equipo cabe en una pantalla. Cuando no cabe, el problema no es la hoja en sí: es el tiempo que consume mantenerla viva y la facilidad con la que oculta sobrecargas."},{"id":"6bf36e52-8255-4740-b1ae-4d5e609b6a1e","type":"paragraph","html":"Este artículo no es un «Excel vs software»: es una guía para montar la plantilla más útil posible, entender cuándo flaquea y saber qué criterio mantener si decides dar el salto a una herramienta integrada. Al final hay una plantilla .xlsx con cinco hojas listas para usar: instrucciones, equipo, proyectos, asignación semanal e insights con formato condicional y KPIs."},{"id":"ddc7749c-9ff2-4c5c-bc12-c1f49a545aa8","type":"paragraph","html":"Si estabas comparando plantillas gratuitas de planificación de recursos, esta está pensada para uso real en agencia: no solo reparte horas, también cruza capacidad neta, pacing, coste y margen."},{"id":"e16be1c7-84db-429a-923e-ed366fed4f06","type":"paragraph","html":"Si buscas las métricas que acompañan a esta plantilla, el tema se amplía en <strong>KPIs para agencias de marketing: 5 métricas que sí importan en 2026</strong>. Aquí el foco está en la estructura de la hoja, las fórmulas y el momento en que deja de compensar."},{"id":"6998a32e-bf7b-4b5c-aacb-e55e70464fe8","type":"cta","text":"Descargar plantilla .xlsx","href":"/planificador-recursos","variant":"primary"},{"id":"2fcb2a98-fcfb-4273-ad44-9a14ad5908c6","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>5 hojas, fórmulas nativas, formato condicional, desplegables y protección de celdas. Funciona en Excel y Google Sheets.</em>"},{"id":"b44ed4ea-850d-4d7f-84e2-774bbc07ab5b","type":"toc"},{"id":"1fcd9f4c-11a5-4ad8-9965-3a877ffe4e9a","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"1. Por qué el Excel es el «primer amor» de toda agencia","anchorId":"intro"},{"id":"62cbf73c-2017-454a-ad79-c39f51c8cc3d","type":"paragraph","html":"Coste cero, flexibilidad total y curva de aprendizaje que el equipo ya domina. Para cinco personas y cuatro clientes, una hoja bien pensada basta para ver quién está cargado y dónde hay margen. Nadie necesita justificar una licencia ni configurar permisos: abres, escribes y compartes. La cicatriz es cuando el martes llega “versión 4” por email y nadie sabe cuál es la que refleja la realidad."},{"id":"b2928f71-4f61-4ec4-b2da-238549792a63","type":"paragraph","html":"El romance dura mientras el mantenimiento es anecdótico. Con ocho o diez personas, varios proyectos simultáneos y un par de incorporaciones recientes, el escenario cambia: alguien tiene que ser el guardián de la hoja. Actualizar quién trabaja en qué, perseguir a quien no rellena sus horas y detectar que una fórmula se descuadró hace tres semanas."},{"id":"245868f1-272d-4cdb-acfe-d84f25a7fbf7","type":"paragraph","html":"Ese rol de guardián suele recaer en el Traffic Manager o el PM. Y ahí aparece un coste invisible: las horas que dedica a la hoja no van a gestión de cuenta ni a producción. La herramienta gratuita tiene un peaje en tiempo de gente que factura."},{"id":"85aa76d3-b71b-458e-9a0e-f295fb485a97","type":"callout","tone":"info","html":"Según estudios de productividad en agencias de servicios, los mandos intermedios gastan entre 3 y 6 horas semanales en tareas de reporting manual (preparar datos, reconciliar versiones, actualizar cuadros). Tiempo que no se factura ni se ve como «coste» hasta que se mide."},{"id":"61628fde-8633-46c8-91b0-42ec6dbe406e","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"2. Capacidad bruta vs capacidad neta: la primera fórmula que importa","anchorId":"capacity"},{"id":"4fa752bc-6623-4f02-aed3-3a951e2b1dd6","type":"paragraph","html":"Capacidad bruta es el contrato: normalmente 40 h/semana. Capacidad neta es lo que queda para trabajo de producción o cliente después de descontar reuniones recurrentes, formación, administración interna y ausencias puntuales (vacaciones, festivos, bajas). La cicatriz aparece cuando comparas “bruta vs asignada” y el equipo está agotado, pero el número sigue pareciendo verde."},{"id":"9682b8a1-0e7d-4dc8-824d-fc1330c8ce22","type":"paragraph","html":"La diferencia importa porque, si comparas horas asignadas contra la bruta, la utilización siempre parece baja y «hay margen» que en realidad no existe. Es el error más común en plantillas de agencia y el que más sobrecargas oculta."},{"id":"f74caa4b-1153-4477-a40e-e9748438026c","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Ejemplo con números"},{"id":"27dccb3c-e000-4dfc-b2cd-8786d396ad59","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Ana tiene 32 h reales para trabajo de cliente, no 40. Si le asignas 35 h en proyectos, no está «al 87 %»: está al 109 % de su capacidad real, y eso se traduce en horas extra invisibles.</em>"},{"id":"8a967940-d24c-4698-b2cb-f06c791f8997","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Fórmula en la plantilla (hoja «Equipo», columna G)"},{"id":"d75956e2-d471-4716-9980-f46d18686258","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Es decir: Jornada − Reuniones − Admin − Ausencias. Cuatro columnas de descuento; la neta se calcula sola al rellenar las otras.</em>"},{"id":"1f41b6a7-ae89-472b-94e6-3cea6e0788a8","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"3. Anatomía de la plantilla: cuatro hojas y cómo se conectan","anchorId":"anatomy"},{"id":"7e1647ca-5a84-439a-8bbc-54f7aa2f7193","type":"paragraph","html":"La estructura profesional se apoya en cuatro hojas encadenadas (más una de instrucciones): inventario de equipo, catálogo de proyectos, cuadrante de asignación semanal y dashboard de insights. Cada una alimenta a la siguiente; si alguna falla, el resultado final pierde sentido. Lo notas cuando una hoja “no se ha tocado” y aun así cambian los KPIs… porque la fórmula estaba apuntando a otro rango."},{"id":"dd49d2bf-6bf0-49bc-a37a-686be46869f6","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Hoja «Equipo» — Inventario de capacidad"},{"id":"0a6fa4dc-eeb3-4340-9dee-390ad9e0672d","type":"paragraph","html":"Aquí defines quiénes sois y cuántas horas reales tiene cada uno. Ocho columnas: persona, rol, jornada, reuniones, admin/formación, ausencias semanales, capacidad neta (fórmula automática) y coste hora interno. La fila de totales suma jornada, reuniones, admin, ausencias y capacidad neta de todo el equipo."},{"id":"6eb7ecd0-a453-46dd-82c2-f3762afb621a","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Clave: actualizar la columna «Ausencias semana» cuando alguien tenga festivos, vacaciones o baja. Si no se toca, el % de utilización en Insights empieza a mentir en silencio.</em>"},{"id":"2bbdeadb-e737-4217-97d9-3efceae41756","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Hoja «Proyectos» — Fee, presupuesto y margen"},{"id":"6ceabf22-5233-42f2-b990-07f56f7f6128","type":"paragraph","html":"Cada proyecto (o servicio-cliente) ocupa una fila. Tú rellenas nombre, tipo (Retainer / Proyecto / Interno con desplegable), fee mensual y horas presupuestadas al mes. Las columnas de cálculo hacen el resto:"},{"id":"aca6b728-6ba9-4c23-a207-f848753efd38","type":"list","ordered":false,"items":["Horas asignadas semana: suma automática desde la hoja de Asignación (SUMIF).","Pacing (%): horas asignadas esta semana vs media semanal presupuestada (horas mes ÷ 4). Si supera el 100 % vas «por delante» del presupuesto.","Coste semana estimado: cruza horas asignadas con el coste hora de cada persona (SUMPRODUCT × VLOOKUP).","Margen mensual estimado: fee − (coste semana × 4). Si sale negativo, la celda se pinta en rojo."]},{"id":"5df151e1-f82f-4957-b3c9-0fb4e93d9a5f","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Clave: el margen es una estimación basada en la asignación actual; no sustituye al cierre contable real, pero anticipa tendencias antes de que sea tarde.</em>"},{"id":"e2973986-11b5-4719-b7e3-11cf50bd8446","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Hoja «Asignación» — El cuadrante semanal"},{"id":"e00427cb-6785-44c2-be67-18cc6ef7e623","type":"paragraph","html":"El cruce personas × proyectos × semana. Cada fila es un bloque de asignación: quién, en qué proyecto, qué semana, cuántas horas y una nota libre. Las columnas Persona y Proyecto tienen desplegables enlazados a las hojas Equipo y Proyectos, lo que evita errores de escritura que rompen las fórmulas SUMIF."},{"id":"b9d13b0c-cc9d-408e-a1ef-5c936f91a213","type":"paragraph","html":"La plantilla incluye dos semanas de datos de ejemplo (S12 y S13) con 8 personas y 6 proyectos repartidos de forma realista, más 20 filas vacías con los desplegables ya configurados para que empieces a rellenar directamente."},{"id":"c0ca297c-d434-44e5-85af-9ee6e5ece05c","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Clave: el nivel de granularidad. Semanas suele ser el término medio ideal en agencias; por día es demasiado fino para mantener en Excel y por mes es demasiado grueso para detectar picos.</em>"},{"id":"4a997d7b-ef2d-477c-9a03-7ab97fd2ee1d","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Hoja «Insights» — Dashboard de alertas y KPIs"},{"id":"57636e27-3814-4e4c-97a8-dce8c34638c5","type":"paragraph","html":"Todo automático: departamento, capacidad neta, horas asignadas, horas libres, utilización (%), estado, coste semanal y número de proyectos por persona. La columna de utilización tiene formato condicional real con tres niveles de color:"},{"id":"75207ade-bd0f-4bf0-95a8-425d7615396f","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Clave: mirar esta hoja al principio de cada semana, no al final del mes. La alerta temprana es lo que diferencia una plantilla decorativa de una operativa.</em>"},{"id":"fe8700bf-4ccf-48a4-823b-6e25446ced9b","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Mockup: cuadrante semanal (ejemplo visual)</em>"},{"id":"2d61bd5f-757c-4744-9642-ef7b57c627be","type":"table","headers":["Persona","Cap. neta (h)","H. asignadas","H. libres","Utilización","Estado"],"rows":[["Ana L.","⚠️ RIESGO"],["Luis G.","⚠️ RIESGO"],["María P.","⛔ SOBRECARGA"],["Jorge N.","⚠️ RIESGO"]]},{"id":"3b2f5ee3-05ff-4e0a-a3f4-8599a51469bf","type":"cta","text":"Descargar plantilla con las cuatro hojas","href":"/planificador-recursos","variant":"primary"},{"id":"8e59f3d4-56b1-41a3-aba1-cf6245b3756c","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"4. Fórmula de utilización y formato condicional","anchorId":"utilization"},{"id":"6be25aef-5945-45a9-b0e9-471cf2c82a3b","type":"paragraph","html":"La métrica central de la plantilla es la tasa de utilización: qué proporción de la capacidad neta de una persona está asignada a proyectos. La fórmula es directa:"},{"id":"c6ee83b9-d382-4f64-a791-bc92176ebf8d","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Ejemplo con números (semana 12)"},{"id":"b9aaa268-ec2c-4c32-be83-868255117770","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Fórmula maestra (hoja «Insights», columna F)"},{"id":"b37f8bcf-638a-4983-8fb3-77a9bcdbc03f","type":"paragraph","html":"Donde D2 son las horas asignadas (calculadas con SUMIF desde Asignación) y C2 es la capacidad neta (traída de Equipo). El IFERROR evita el error #DIV/0! si la neta es cero."},{"id":"fd826380-acb3-4c66-a59d-dd96952f0d32","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Formato condicional (tres niveles de color)"},{"id":"cda847c6-53a0-4cdc-ab86-0118cf505973","type":"paragraph","html":"La plantilla aplica formato condicional nativo en la columna de utilización. Excel y Google Sheets lo interpretan directamente al abrir el archivo:"},{"id":"d7894ebf-112e-49e3-8a1a-938d2a0f936f","type":"list","ordered":false,"items":["Verde (70–90%): zona óptima, hay colchón para imprevistos.","Ámbar (> 90%): zona de riesgo, cualquier imprevisto desborda.","Rojo (≥ 100%): sobrecarga declarada, la persona ya no tiene horas."]},{"id":"a1d74cbc-f5fd-4720-8287-4229e49e2088","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Columna «Estado» (cuatro niveles con fórmula IF anidada)"},{"id":"3946250e-b2e1-4573-9511-8cb87d10db75","type":"paragraph","html":"Cuatro estados que se leen de un vistazo. «Baja carga» no significa que la persona no trabaje; puede estar en formación o tener ausencias esa semana. El valor está en el patrón a lo largo de varias semanas."},{"id":"dcd9b0ef-9a57-4350-b5a4-7f522a422d90","type":"paragraph","html":"María tiene 29 h netas (40 − 8 reuniones − 3 admin). Esta semana tiene asignadas 29 h en cuatro proyectos. Utilización: 29 / 29 = 100 %. Estado: ⛔ SOBRECARGA. No tiene ni una hora libre para un imprevisto. Si un cliente pide algo urgente, alguien va a hacer horas extra o un entregable se va a retrasar."},{"id":"08b37d36-46a9-4ef6-8c77-8f160212981c","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"5. Pacing por proyecto y margen estimado","anchorId":"pacing"},{"id":"ad9cf19f-eb32-4e7c-b040-ac11ab80cbf9","type":"paragraph","html":"La hoja Proyectos añade dos métricas que un cuadrante sencillo no suele incluir: el pacing (ritmo de consumo de horas) y el margen mensual estimado. La cicatriz es cuando el Excel te marca un buen pacing… y aun así el fee se va en horas antes de que cierre el mes."},{"id":"8cb04785-124f-4d5b-8c45-6676a4ee74e6","type":"paragraph","html":"El pacing compara las horas asignadas esta semana con lo que «debería» asignarse si repartes el presupuesto mensual de forma lineal (horas presupuestadas ÷ 4 semanas). Un pacing del 120 % significa que estás consumiendo horas un 20 % más rápido de lo presupuestado; si se mantiene, el fee se agotará antes de fin de mes."},{"id":"e7b3803f-df9b-49ba-902e-8f30b98eb08a","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Ejemplo: proyecto «Marca Beta — Web»"},{"id":"1c2ebb6b-029a-4a94-a070-32bfc1b6cdd3","type":"table","headers":["Métrica","Valor"],"rows":[["Fee mensual","8.000 €"],["Horas presupuestadas / mes","100 h"],["Media semanal presupuestada","25 h (100 ÷ 4)"],["Horas asignadas esta semana","30 h"],["Pacing","120%"],["Margen mensual estimado","8.000 − (coste sem. × 4)"]]},{"id":"a9bb2e5b-3b25-4131-82cf-b16ce22af012","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Si el pacing supera el 100 % dos semanas seguidas, es una señal clara de que el alcance se ha expandido o la estimación se quedó corta. El formato condicional pinta la celda en ámbar (>100 %) o rojo (>120 %) para que salte a la vista.</em>"},{"id":"aad7c0a6-b1f0-431a-8f6b-02d53519782c","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"6. El «impuesto Excel»: cuánto cuesta mantener la hoja","anchorId":"excelTax"},{"id":"ce5a12dd-8d58-4d00-a8d0-898564ef4820","type":"paragraph","html":"Si un PM con coste hora de 40 € dedica 4 horas semanales a actualizar el Excel (perseguir datos, corregir fórmulas, reconciliar versiones, preparar el resumen para la reunión de carga), el coste directo es. La cicatriz: cuando el reporte consume más tiempo del que te ayuda a tomar decisiones."},{"id":"ab47f3f4-fd3a-4a7d-989a-9b50bfebc2ea","type":"paragraph","html":"No es «gratis»: es un impuesto fijo sobre el margen que no aparece en ninguna línea de coste porque nadie lo factura. Y a eso se suma lo que el PM no hace mientras alimenta la hoja: gestión de cuenta, negociación de alcance, tiempo con el equipo creativo."},{"id":"71692b3f-2aba-4279-91be-ce1a0f127776","type":"paragraph","html":"La plantilla incluye este cálculo en el bloque de KPIs de la hoja Insights (4 × coste hora del PM × 52 semanas), para que el número esté visible cada vez que se abre el archivo."},{"id":"0011bf1e-c6fb-4fe3-8924-8ca92eefa57d","type":"callout","tone":"info","html":"<strong>4 h × 40 €/h × 4 semanas = 640 €/mes</strong>"},{"id":"8963ca06-2cc6-4662-b665-a2e17547a488","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Son 7.680 €/año en mantener un archivo estático. Si dos personas lo tocan, multiplica.</em>"},{"id":"18edf5f4-2562-4aac-a1e0-1fcf4347e067","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"7. Techo de cristal: tres puntos donde la hoja se rompe","anchorId":"ceiling"},{"id":"0647074d-d809-48ad-8c63-752a79b44ece","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"1. Arqueología de datos"},{"id":"c3208136-190e-4b73-a50c-2562705f2edf","type":"paragraph","html":"Perseguir a todo el equipo para que rellene sus horas, cuadrar versiones del archivo y descubrir que la hoja de la semana pasada no se actualizó. El dato existe, pero llegar a él cuesta más que el propio valor que aporta. La cicatriz es que el “dato clave” aparece justo después de la reunión donde ibais a decidir."},{"id":"8d0be74a-25de-4659-8219-c0e994876c6e","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"2. Desconexión con la realidad"},{"id":"bda911d3-f65a-4d68-8a24-fedd3e85cd57","type":"paragraph","html":"El Excel dice que las horas están asignadas, pero no sabe si las tareas se ejecutan ni si el margen del proyecto está bajando. Puedes tener «100 % de asignación» y descubrir al cerrar el mes que el fee se agotó en la segunda semana. No hay pacing en tiempo real: solo el que tú calcules."},{"id":"b494c880-32bc-4709-8d29-67c88e6f052f","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"3. Error de fórmula humano"},{"id":"9487743c-d329-4cf3-80af-11349c395c9c","type":"paragraph","html":"Una celda borrada por error, una fila que no se copió bien o un rango que se desplazó al insertar columnas. El resultado: un diseñador lleva tres semanas al 140 % de carga y nadie lo vio porque la fórmula apuntaba al rango equivocado. Cuando se detecta, el daño ya está hecho. La protección de celdas de la plantilla reduce este riesgo, pero no lo elimina del todo."},{"id":"3092751e-6b19-4b3c-a31d-5f802b55eaaa","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>Ninguno de estos problemas es del Excel como herramienta: es del flujo manual. Cualquier hoja, por bien pensada que esté, necesita que alguien la alimente puntualmente y que nadie la toque por error. En equipos pequeños el coste es asumible; al escalar, se vuelve un riesgo operativo.</strong>"},{"id":"e77f9a38-4578-4ea2-b5d2-73dbf1333dfa","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"8. Validación de datos y protección: cómo evitar que la hoja se rompa","anchorId":"validation"},{"id":"cdb6e093-c30e-4f84-999a-1b09f424dfc4","type":"paragraph","html":"El 80 % de los errores en una plantilla de recursos viene de dos sitios: alguien escribe un nombre con una tilde distinta y el SUMIF no cruza, o alguien borra una fórmula sin querer. La plantilla incluye dos mecanismos para minimizar ambos. Lo sientes cuando alguien “solo mira” una celda y, sin avisar, rompe el cálculo del margen."},{"id":"47cd03bc-49cf-4c56-9a11-6468e551c08f","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Desplegables (data validation)"},{"id":"f1c2412b-b36f-4c9f-80c7-7ba7dd626b33","type":"paragraph","html":"Las columnas «Persona» y «Proyecto» de la hoja Asignación tienen listas desplegables enlazadas a los nombres de Equipo y Proyectos. Al hacer clic en la celda aparece la flechita y se selecciona en lugar de escribir. Esto garantiza que el nombre coincida carácter por carácter con la hoja de origen, y que SUMIF, VLOOKUP y COUNTIF funcionen."},{"id":"011b4fc6-38d4-4a43-9492-49b34ea2af5c","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Si necesitas añadir una persona o proyecto nuevo, añádelo primero en la hoja correspondiente y luego actualiza la lista del desplegable (Datos → Validación de datos).</em>"},{"id":"5c68771a-f336-4380-ad4e-79b09f4a290d","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Protección de celdas"},{"id":"0471ad57-4709-4094-b33f-5589d0f51e1a","type":"paragraph","html":"Todas las celdas con fórmula (Capacidad neta, Utilización, Estado, Margen, KPIs…) están protegidas: si intentas escribir encima, Excel te avisa. Las celdas de entrada (nombre, horas, notas) quedan libres. La protección se puede desactivar sin contraseña (Revisar → Desproteger hoja) si necesitas ajustar algo, pero mientras esté activa evita el borrado accidental."},{"id":"13208d58-3b7a-498f-9bd2-b783663534e4","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>En Google Sheets, al importar el .xlsx la protección se convierte en «rangos protegidos» con el mismo efecto.</em>"},{"id":"313b0634-7732-44fd-a6b7-b0389d28cdfb","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"9. Cómo escalar la plantilla semana a semana","anchorId":"scale"},{"id":"d7998471-f91f-4b5b-92ec-73c7981ef064","type":"paragraph","html":"La plantilla viene con dos semanas de ejemplo (S12 y S13). Para añadir una nueva semana, el proceso es:"},{"id":"748ae812-8a19-4fcc-bfb0-265e643cf180","type":"list","ordered":true,"items":["Hoja Equipo: revisar la columna «Ausencias semana». Si alguien tiene vacaciones o un festivo, actualizar las horas. La capacidad neta se recalcula sola.","Hoja Asignación: añadir filas nuevas para la semana siguiente. Usa los desplegables de Persona y Proyecto. Puedes copiar las filas de la semana anterior y cambiar la columna «Semana» y las horas.","Hoja Insights: no tocar nada. Las fórmulas SUMIF suman todas las filas de Asignación independientemente de la semana, así que el dashboard se actualiza solo."]},{"id":"e06242e0-7222-4736-a846-91d3ac5cc379","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Truco: filtrar por semana"},{"id":"0992bc84-927a-43c2-97bf-ea92e99ef8b7","type":"paragraph","html":"Todas las hojas de datos tienen autofiltros activados. En Asignación puedes filtrar por la columna «Semana» para ver solo la semana actual. En Insights puedes filtrar por departamento para revisar la carga de un equipo concreto. Los totales de la plantilla suman el rango completo, pero el filtro visual te permite centrarte en lo que importa en cada reunión."},{"id":"81698f8f-bffa-4f1e-9578-120e04a20b81","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Limitación: como Insights suma todas las semanas, si dejas las filas antiguas de Asignación, las horas acumuladas crecen semana tras semana. Para un dashboard «solo esta semana», filtra o borra las filas de semanas anteriores. Es una de las fricciones del modelo manual que una herramienta integrada resuelve automáticamente.</em>"},{"id":"807d5f89-26a0-46eb-aa2e-c1f54d3b39f0","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"10. Google Sheets vs Excel: ¿cambia algo?","anchorId":"sheetsVsExcel"},{"id":"25cab794-c928-4b41-b965-205cbe8dcd75","type":"paragraph","html":"La plantilla funciona en los dos; las fórmulas son compatibles. La diferencia relevante es operativa:"},{"id":"156a5f92-9a8a-4bd0-abef-3776d937c50b","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>La conclusión: da igual el formato. El techo está en el modelo manual, no en si abres .xlsx o lo importas en Drive.</strong>"},{"id":"2105bef1-64f0-4aac-a12a-df6e59e01449","type":"list","ordered":false,"items":["Colaboración en tiempo real: Sheets permite que varias personas editen a la vez, lo que reduce el problema de «versión 3 o versión 4». Pero no elimina el riesgo de pisarse celdas ni de romper una fórmula sin querer.","Historial de cambios: Sheets guarda versiones automáticamente. Excel solo si usas OneDrive/SharePoint. En la práctica, ambos cubren el caso de «quién rompió la fila 12».","Desplegables y protección: al importar el .xlsx en Google Sheets, los desplegables se convierten en validación de datos nativa y la protección en rangos protegidos. No hay que reconfigurar nada.","Rendimiento: con muchas filas y fórmulas cruzadas, Excel local suele ir más fluido que Sheets en el navegador. Para plantillas de 5–30 personas, la diferencia es despreciable."]},{"id":"9353a379-bd82-4ccc-88dc-3716350ed329","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"11. Evolución: de rellenar celdas a planificación pasiva","anchorId":"evolution"},{"id":"334bf704-4e6b-4169-b045-ee8f95206b87","type":"paragraph","html":"La lógica que acabas de estructurar —capacidad neta, cuadrante de asignación, pacing, margen y utilización— es exactamente la misma que usa un sistema integrado. La diferencia es quién la mantiene: tú a mano o la herramienta de forma pasiva."},{"id":"9fe4e921-49da-483f-9fa9-6da885ed6843","type":"paragraph","html":"En Taimbox, mueves bloques en el planificador por horas. Los informes de utilización, carga por departamento y margen por proyecto se alimentan de ese movimiento sin que alguien reimporte números cada lunes. El criterio es el tuyo; la ejecución del dato deja de depender de copiar y pegar."},{"id":"92f4e8cf-061b-4004-9682-f7e798e16c1f","type":"paragraph","html":"No es «tirar el Excel» el primer día: es llevar la plantilla mental (y las fórmulas) a un sitio donde el dato no se descuadra. La evolución natural cuando el equipo ya no cabe en filas y columnas compartidas."},{"id":"23c4198b-1162-4600-be65-95627955d268","type":"callout","tone":"highlight","html":"Planificación pasiva: tú planificas; Taimbox calcula utilización, margen y capacidad en segundo plano. Las métricas que antes montabas a mano nacen de la forma en que trabajáis, sin reconciliar hojas.<br/><em>Los reportes de rentabilidad y el planificador de recursos detallan el enfoque en sus landings.</em>"},{"id":"880d30df-6581-4304-b218-1a550d715374","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Preguntas frecuentes","anchorId":"preguntas-frecuentes"},{"id":"3553c6b0-7774-49c0-829b-05bfa6bcd0cd","type":"faq","items":[{"q":"¿Necesito macros o VBA para que funcione la plantilla?","a":"No. Solo usa fórmulas estándar (SUMA, SI, SUMIF, VLOOKUP, SUMPRODUCT, COUNTIF) y formato condicional nativo. Funciona en Excel, LibreOffice y Google Sheets sin necesidad de habilitar macros."},{"q":"¿Cada cuánto hay que actualizar la plantilla?","a":"Lo ideal es revisarla al inicio de cada semana (o al final de la anterior): ajustar ausencias en Equipo y añadir las asignaciones de la nueva semana. La frecuencia semanal da tiempo a reaccionar antes de que una sobrecarga se convierta en crisis."},{"q":"¿A partir de cuántas personas deja de ser práctico el Excel?","a":"No hay un número mágico; depende más del ritmo de cambios (proyectos nuevos, rotaciones) que del tamaño. En la práctica, muchas agencias notan la fricción entre 8 y 15 personas con múltiples proyectos simultáneos: ahí el mantenimiento semanal empieza a no compensar."},{"q":"¿Puedo usar esta plantilla junto a un tablero Kanban (Trello, Asana…)?","a":"Sí: el Kanban gestiona el flujo de tareas; la plantilla de recursos gestiona horas y capacidad. Se complementan: el tablero dice «qué se está haciendo» y la plantilla dice «quién tiene horas libres para hacerlo»."},{"q":"¿Qué rango de utilización es «sano» en una agencia?","a":"Orientativo: 70–85 % sobre capacidad neta en muchas agencias de servicios. Por debajo puede indicar falta de pipeline; por encima del 90 % empieza el riesgo de quemazo y errores. El mix de negocio (retainers, proyectos puntuales, I+D interna) cambia el objetivo."},{"q":"¿El pacing tiene en cuenta que no todos los meses duran lo mismo?","a":"La fórmula divide las horas presupuestadas entre 4 semanas como aproximación. En meses de 5 semanas laborales, el pacing real será ligeramente inferior al mostrado. Para la mayoría de agencias la aproximación es suficiente; si necesitas precisión al día, un sistema integrado lo resuelve mejor."},{"q":"¿Cómo actualizo los desplegables si añado una persona o proyecto nuevo?","a":"En Excel: ve a la hoja Asignación, selecciona la columna con el desplegable, Datos → Validación de datos, y amplía la lista. En Google Sheets: clic en la celda, icono de desplegable, editar lista. Los nombres deben coincidir exactamente con las hojas Equipo o Proyectos."}]},{"id":"e72ef9f5-6cfe-4864-8799-e3eb7b80c4aa","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Resumen: lo que cambia con una plantilla bien hecha","anchorId":"resumen"},{"id":"c4154472-e92d-4c7c-a31e-815c813a1e90","type":"paragraph","html":"La diferencia entre una agencia que «cree que va bien» y una que sabe que va bien suele estar en unas pocas columnas de un Excel: capacidad neta, horas asignadas, utilización, pacing y margen. No es rocket science: es disciplina de datos, desplegables para no romper nada, protección para no borrar lo importante y revisión semanal."},{"id":"124de8ed-2653-4041-b020-96e497e64701","type":"paragraph","html":"Cuando esa disciplina ya no escala con la hoja, la misma lógica puede vivir en una herramienta que actualiza los números de forma pasiva. El criterio que acabas de aprender no caduca; el soporte donde lo aplicas, sí puede evolucionar."},{"id":"345e44e1-3162-4310-bfe7-84807b823e8e","type":"paragraph","html":"Los KPIs que acompañan a esta plantilla —utilización, pacing, estimado vs real— están desarrollados enKPIs para agencias de marketing. La gestión del tiempo que evita que las tareas se expandan sin control aparece enLey de Parkinsonytimeboxing. Y la visión global de cronograma + presupuesto + equipo se detalla enplanificación de proyectos."},{"id":"a0beb46d-a3e4-476e-b87a-85c7473ee0f7","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"La plantilla es el primer paso; el planificador es el siguiente","anchorId":"cta-final"},{"id":"cb80da0c-cac9-4889-aefa-c08a1a52ef61","type":"paragraph","html":"Capacidad, asignación, pacing y utilización sin mantener la hoja a mano. Taimbox se puede explorar sin compromiso."},{"id":"f2b59c79-5eca-4289-ade4-9189476e15b1","type":"cta","text":"Cómo Taimbox automatiza tu plantilla","href":"/planificador-recursos","variant":"primary"},{"id":"d7c37831-0f45-4419-a3c7-e5c91249eb84","type":"cta","text":"Descargar plantilla .xlsx","href":"/reportes-rentabilidad","variant":"secondary"},{"id":"4e616ddb-52e7-43fa-a275-4b2349f7062b","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Escrito por el equipo de Taimbox — Gestión de recursos y rentabilidad para agencias.</em>"},{"id":"ad1c82a2-b7ff-444b-847a-afe02deef710","type":"relatedPost","slug":"planificacion-proyectos-cronograma-recursos"}]'::jsonb,
  blocks_en = '[{"id":"8e40af80-6e94-4f18-8fbe-82d5a337a42d","type":"paragraph","html":"Every agency starts the same way: an Excel file with names in columns, projects in rows, and a formula summing hours. It works while the team still fits on one screen. Once it does not, the problem is not the sheet itself: it is the time it takes to keep it alive and how easily it hides overloads."},{"id":"5ac65b06-2fcd-4a9d-9189-af8ec8a4c091","type":"paragraph","html":"This article is not an “Excel vs. software” pitch: it is a guide to build the most useful template you can, understand where it starts to fail, and know which criteria to keep if you later move to an integrated tool. At the end you will find an .xlsx template with five sheets ready to use: instructions, team, projects, weekly allocation, and insights with conditional formatting and KPIs."},{"id":"da665958-c1ab-41af-b2e9-7798fed59a97","type":"paragraph","html":"If you have been comparing free resource‑planning templates, this one is designed for real agency use: it does not just distribute hours; it also crosses net capacity, pacing, cost, and margin."},{"id":"42a6af9e-ca9d-4c12-a2e9-2594992cf53a","type":"paragraph","html":"If you are looking for the metrics that go with this template, we go deeper in <strong>KPIs for marketing agencies: 5 metrics that really matter in 2026</strong>. Here the focus is on the sheet structure, the formulas, and the moment when it stops being worth the effort."},{"id":"64a399f3-2a45-4bf6-baec-125a8ec1d65b","type":"cta","text":".xlsx template download","href":"/planificador-recursos","variant":"primary"},{"id":"bd60634d-3c06-4d33-883e-c5f751a80900","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>5 sheets, native formulas, conditional formatting, dropdowns, and cell protection. Works in Excel and Google Sheets.</em>"},{"id":"43db3b76-4710-45dc-87a6-45739483e70c","type":"toc"},{"id":"a34cd3fb-c11b-4ed3-b550-51322ea497e8","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"1. Why Excel is every agency’s “first love”","anchorId":"intro"},{"id":"8a93bb04-c193-49a7-bad4-595bf9f53956","type":"paragraph","html":"Zero cost, total flexibility, and a learning curve the team already mastered. For five people and four clients, a well‑designed sheet is enough to see who is loaded and where there is slack. Nobody has to justify a licence or set up permissions: you open, type, and share. The scar is when “version 4” arrives by email on Tuesday and nobody knows which one reflects reality."},{"id":"a1f2e2f3-16bf-43f2-8ec2-a993c35933fc","type":"paragraph","html":"The romance lasts as long as maintenance is anecdotal. With eight or ten people, several simultaneous projects, and a couple of recent hires, the picture changes: someone has to become the sheet’s gatekeeper. Updating who is working on what, chasing those who do not log their hours, and spotting that a formula drifted three weeks ago."},{"id":"23b9b41e-1f19-454d-bb23-17280f7ad1f0","type":"paragraph","html":"That gatekeeper role usually lands on the traffic manager or PM. And there you get an invisible cost: the hours they spend on the sheet do not go to account management or production. The “free” tool charges a toll in billable people’s time."},{"id":"b6c7648f-1ca9-4136-a1f2-d766ba3b3d7c","type":"callout","tone":"info","html":"In productivity studies on service agencies, middle managers spend between 3 and 6 hours a week on manual reporting (preparing data, reconciling versions, updating dashboards). Time that is neither billed nor seen as a “cost” until you measure it."},{"id":"a4d81ffb-d24f-46b2-a4f9-d42cda76dcda","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"2. Gross vs. net capacity: the first formula that matters","anchorId":"capacity"},{"id":"43d54d93-01da-48bd-a60a-85f63393c2e6","type":"paragraph","html":"Gross capacity is the contract: usually 40 h/week. Net capacity is what is left for client or production work after subtracting recurring meetings, training, internal admin, and one‑off absences (vacations, holidays, sick leave). The scar appears when you compare “gross vs. assigned”, the team is exhausted, and the number still looks comfortably green."},{"id":"481d7b88-d8ab-419f-a045-e133d1486c40","type":"paragraph","html":"The difference matters because if you compare assigned hours against gross capacity, utilization always looks low and “there is room” that in reality does not exist. It is the most common error in agency templates and the one that hides the most overload."},{"id":"58905ae1-ba2f-4468-a28e-9f8c92bf1451","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Example with numbers"},{"id":"0177e63c-9ef0-4e58-83c0-52a343a5c69c","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Ana has 32 real hours for client work, not 40. If you assign her 35 project hours, she is not “at 87%”: she is at 109% of her real capacity, and that turns into invisible overtime.</em>"},{"id":"135ea36e-054c-4262-8a10-a871758e6ff4","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Template formula (\"Team\" sheet, column G)"},{"id":"928b9194-23d1-4e34-b9eb-1d2b5d5ad8a9","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>In other words: Working hours − Meetings − Admin − Absences. Four subtraction columns; net capacity updates automatically as you fill in the others.</em>"},{"id":"f2169ad1-a943-4973-8405-b3a189b3cb12","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"3. Template anatomy: four sheets and how they connect","anchorId":"anatomy"},{"id":"b2546810-06cb-4c7d-8d8b-b967bbce2420","type":"paragraph","html":"A professional structure rests on four linked sheets (plus one with instructions): team inventory, project catalog, weekly allocation grid, and insights dashboard. Each feeds the next; if one fails, the final picture stops making sense. You notice it when a sheet “has not been touched” and the KPIs still change… because a formula was pointing at the wrong range."},{"id":"5b65376a-7bb1-4e9e-aec8-7ef5a0941962","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"\"Team\" sheet — Capacity inventory"},{"id":"10c72b37-7ca8-4122-9855-8e48ab75ecce","type":"paragraph","html":"Here you define who you are and how many real hours each person has. Eight columns: person, role, working hours, meetings, admin/training, weekly absences, net capacity (automatic formula), and internal hourly cost. The totals row sums working hours, meetings, admin, absences, and net capacity for the whole team."},{"id":"b0f1aeeb-d7f7-4f56-96a9-3b7da9cdc215","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Key: keep the “Weekly absences” column up to date when someone has holidays or time off. If it is ignored, the utilization % in Insights starts lying quietly.</em>"},{"id":"7105278f-157c-4398-9904-97abc8f2c3ae","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"\"Projects\" sheet — Fee, budget, and margin"},{"id":"5e2060eb-6e9b-44d4-907e-d7657ed2fcf2","type":"paragraph","html":"Each project (or client‑service combo) takes one row. You fill in name, type (Retainer / Project / Internal via dropdown), monthly fee, and budgeted monthly hours. The calculation columns do the rest:"},{"id":"204fab3c-103a-4cc5-87a8-936fba9c5cd5","type":"list","ordered":false,"items":["Weekly hours assigned: automatic sum from the Allocation sheet (SUMIF).","Pacing (%): hours assigned this week vs. average weekly budget (monthly hours ÷ 4). If it goes over 100%, you are running ahead of budget.","Estimated weekly cost: crosses assigned hours with each person’s hourly cost (SUMPRODUCT × VLOOKUP).","Estimated monthly margin: fee − (weekly cost × 4). If it is negative, the cell turns red."]},{"id":"851a13ae-fd16-45e7-8542-6ffbdd59f276","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Key: margin is an estimate based on current allocation; it does not replace the actual accounting close, but it flags trend changes before it is too late.</em>"},{"id":"a2f4ce17-9959-4252-a127-10507ceacfc3","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"\"Allocation\" sheet — The weekly grid"},{"id":"4125d671-4d06-4be0-b782-6d17ced5de00","type":"paragraph","html":"The cross between people × projects × week. Each row is an allocation block: who, on which project, which week, how many hours, and a free‑text note. The Person and Project columns use dropdowns linked to the Team and Projects sheets, which prevents typos that would break SUMIF formulas."},{"id":"cb578a99-fd07-45d1-b6f8-2c58c1c8d7a5","type":"paragraph","html":"The template includes two weeks of sample data (W12 and W13) with 8 people and 6 projects distributed in a realistic way, plus 20 empty rows with dropdowns already configured so you can start filling them in right away."},{"id":"9b1a8885-227f-4123-9bfc-ae2d21dee3d6","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Key: the granularity level. Weeks tend to be the sweet spot in agencies; days are too fine‑grained to maintain in Excel and months are too coarse to spot spikes.</em>"},{"id":"0939c633-18f9-4eb0-83b6-544ed0ec6bd9","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"\"Insights\" sheet — Alerts and KPI dashboard"},{"id":"f5201a79-c139-410c-b50b-8a8cb696f53a","type":"paragraph","html":"Everything is automatic: department, net capacity, assigned hours, free hours, utilization (%), status, weekly cost, and number of projects per person. The utilization column uses real conditional formatting with three colour levels:"},{"id":"626c8e6c-2958-42ad-9f52-0d3a04dc7ad0","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Key: look at this sheet at the start of each week, not at the end of the month. Early alerts are what separate a decorative template from an operational one.</em>"},{"id":"10a77d4e-5b76-45ae-a55e-115249bf04e6","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Mock‑up: weekly grid (visual example)</em>"},{"id":"cb23e91f-7497-487c-8d3d-74d55c44b440","type":"table","headers":["Person","Net cap. (h)","Assigned h.","Free h.","Utilization","Status"],"rows":[["Ana L.","⚠️ AT RISK"],["Luis G.","⚠️ AT RISK"],["María P.","⛔ OVERLOADED"],["Jorge N.","⚠️ AT RISK"]]},{"id":"5468e8dc-ac8f-4fcf-a19f-85d1a90f43ca","type":"cta","text":"Download template with all four sheets","href":"/planificador-recursos","variant":"primary"},{"id":"18a19574-ae88-4b2f-9d6e-47d66e5e7009","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"4. Utilization formula and conditional formatting","anchorId":"utilization"},{"id":"a4f9cc82-e98d-41be-ab4a-66d130d4b666","type":"paragraph","html":"The central metric in the template is the utilization rate: what share of a person’s net capacity is assigned to projects. The formula is straightforward:"},{"id":"b4db7650-9157-4ea6-98e7-4ba584f1966c","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Worked example (week 12)"},{"id":"168a77de-d56e-4cf7-b3be-a0188624d80f","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Master formula (\"Insights\" sheet, column F)"},{"id":"fa6ca0f7-dce0-452a-ae4d-0b08674a7c59","type":"paragraph","html":"Where D2 is assigned hours (calculated with SUMIF from Allocation) and C2 is net capacity (brought in from Team). IFERROR avoids #DIV/0! when net capacity is zero."},{"id":"66caf71f-9ca3-4b45-bd62-6935d69048c9","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Conditional formatting (three colour levels)"},{"id":"08f27b39-ad77-4f2e-a729-17a26f46e01d","type":"paragraph","html":"The template applies native conditional formatting to the utilization column. Excel and Google Sheets both interpret it out of the box:"},{"id":"49268121-e988-41bc-8e8c-0b6a879bc813","type":"list","ordered":false,"items":["Green (70–90%): sweet spot, there is still buffer for surprises.","Amber (> 90%): risk zone, any surprise will overflow capacity.","Red (≥ 100%): declared overload, the person has no hours left."]},{"id":"83e5a06a-23a2-458c-b672-4a707479682b","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"\"Status\" column (four levels with nested IF formula)"},{"id":"e11d9bf5-3f32-4377-897b-e3f01fb279a4","type":"paragraph","html":"Four states you can read at a glance. “Under‑loaded” does not mean the person is not working; they might be in training or have absences that week. The value is in the pattern across several weeks."},{"id":"0c4c589a-c53c-469b-ac0b-6cee28b9ba92","type":"paragraph","html":"María has 29 net hours (40 − 8 meetings − 3 admin). This week she has 29 hours assigned across four projects. Utilization: 29 / 29 = 100%. Status: ⛔ OVERLOADED. She has no free hour for anything unexpected. If a client demands something urgent, someone will do unpaid overtime or a deliverable will slip."},{"id":"4d4a311f-80d3-4196-afd1-cce15d850529","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"5. Project pacing and estimated margin","anchorId":"pacing"},{"id":"20ca53ad-55ff-4258-9273-e277c6f14711","type":"paragraph","html":"The Projects sheet adds two metrics a simple grid usually lacks: pacing (the rate at which you are burning hours) and estimated monthly margin. The scar is when Excel tells you pacing is fine… and the fee is still gone in hours before the month is over."},{"id":"6503e455-e791-4b64-b261-b2f58a056fbc","type":"paragraph","html":"Pacing compares hours assigned this week with what “should” be assigned if you spread the monthly budget evenly (budgeted hours ÷ 4 weeks). A pacing of 120% means you are burning hours 20% faster than planned; if that continues, the fee will run out before month‑end."},{"id":"cdc60ef2-3b87-4ef4-aa8d-6c80ad29fbb4","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Example: “Brand Beta — Website” project"},{"id":"d3b94f51-3b74-49b8-a737-027e0931ac61","type":"table","headers":["Metric","Value"],"rows":[["Monthly fee","€8,000"],["Budgeted hours / month","100 h"],["Budgeted weekly average","25 h (100 ÷ 4)"],["Hours assigned this week","30 h"],["Pacing","120%"],["Estimated monthly margin","8,000 − (weekly cost × 4)"]]},{"id":"cb41124b-8afc-4445-9b80-58140eccf6ee","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>If pacing stays above 100% for two weeks in a row, it is a clear sign that scope has expanded or the estimate was too low. Conditional formatting paints the cell amber (>100%) or red (>120%) so it stands out.</em>"},{"id":"4ff6c4e1-c4d6-45fb-a84b-9b9dce246896","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"6. The \"Excel tax\": how much it costs to maintain the sheet","anchorId":"excelTax"},{"id":"23cdd2f4-4f90-40df-b3c1-7c6478c9e4ff","type":"paragraph","html":"If a PM with an hourly cost of €40 spends 4 hours a week updating the Excel (chasing data, fixing formulas, reconciling versions, preparing the summary for the workload meeting), the direct cost is. The scar: when reporting takes more time than the decisions it is supposed to support."},{"id":"7ee9ac8d-9db1-4ecf-a480-be73632f7af9","type":"paragraph","html":"It is not “free”: it is a fixed tax on margin that never shows up on any cost line because nobody bills it. On top of that you have what the PM is not doing while feeding the sheet: account management, scope negotiation, time with the creative team."},{"id":"be5cc334-b611-49a6-809c-4c76a1705b87","type":"paragraph","html":"The template includes this calculation in the Insights KPI block (4 × PM hourly cost × 52 weeks) so the number is visible every time the file is opened."},{"id":"07914d53-708e-4f3e-99ff-ee4bb8f49c57","type":"callout","tone":"info","html":"<strong>4 h × €40/h × 4 weeks = €640/month</strong>"},{"id":"1492e2f5-10fb-40dd-b5c9-911ad30d3e3b","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>That is €7,680/year to keep a static file alive. If two people touch it regularly, multiply.</em>"},{"id":"fe7d6e6e-a4f6-45fc-957b-ce30659fedfe","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"7. Glass ceiling: three points where the sheet breaks","anchorId":"ceiling"},{"id":"f28e642f-27f0-45e8-838e-898caab8fc02","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"1. Data archaeology"},{"id":"13288dc1-c127-4e6f-9b80-f0b619954c77","type":"paragraph","html":"Chasing the whole team to fill in hours, reconciling file versions, and discovering that last week’s sheet never got updated. The data exists, but getting to it costs more than the value it provides. The scar is when the “key number” shows up right after the meeting where you needed it most."},{"id":"ed857fcd-2682-4e15-902f-3a52b54f8ddb","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"2. Disconnect from reality"},{"id":"1317140a-af9a-428f-80f3-dabe2f984102","type":"paragraph","html":"Excel says hours are assigned, but it has no idea whether tasks are executed or whether project margin is sliding. You can have “100% allocation” and still discover at month‑end that the fee was burned by week two. There is no real‑time pacing, only whatever you manually calculate."},{"id":"dcd327ac-ade0-489c-9cba-e8b413eaa252","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"3. Human formula error"},{"id":"1a839570-b5c2-4890-a73b-55be28ced5b0","type":"paragraph","html":"A cell deleted by mistake, a row copied poorly, or a range shifted when inserting columns. The result: a designer has been at 140% load for three weeks and nobody saw it because the formula was pointing at the wrong range. By the time you catch it, the damage is done. Cell protection in the template reduces this risk but does not eliminate it entirely."},{"id":"b6d400a2-5848-4e82-a9e1-cec2bf96f7d5","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>None of these problems are Excel’s fault as a tool; they are symptoms of a manual flow. Any sheet, no matter how well‑designed, needs someone feeding it on time and nobody breaking it by mistake. In small teams the cost is manageable; as you scale, it becomes an operational risk.</strong>"},{"id":"fd1576e2-2e61-48df-8d9c-e85087ec6c09","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"8. Data validation and protection: how not to break the sheet","anchorId":"validation"},{"id":"f637295d-6c11-4bdc-840f-7a2f815d5e8e","type":"paragraph","html":"Roughly 80% of errors in a resource template come from two places: someone types a name with a different accent so SUMIF does not match, or someone deletes a formula by accident. The template includes two mechanisms to reduce both. You feel it when someone “just looks” at a cell and silently breaks the margin calculation."},{"id":"9fb263a5-504d-4fb1-ade6-45e6a348ee82","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Dropdowns (data validation)"},{"id":"19077ba2-fa58-45ee-91f2-b4c7d2897fde","type":"paragraph","html":"The \"Person\" and \"Project\" columns in the Allocation sheet use dropdown lists linked to the names in the Team and Projects sheets. When you click a cell, a little arrow appears and you pick from the list instead of typing. This guarantees the name matches the source sheet character for character so SUMIF, VLOOKUP, and COUNTIF all work."},{"id":"33e72e4f-1017-4e12-871b-e277ac5cc572","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>If you need to add a new person or project, add it to the relevant sheet first and then extend the dropdown list range (Data → Data validation).</em>"},{"id":"649fa0d0-ec63-4b7a-82cb-1c30341794cb","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Cell protection"},{"id":"c43af72d-b794-4146-a180-78144c86796f","type":"paragraph","html":"All formula cells (Net capacity, Utilization, Status, Margin, KPIs…) are protected: if you try to type over them, Excel warns you. Input cells (name, hours, notes) remain unlocked. You can turn protection off without a password (Review → Unprotect sheet) if you need to adjust something, but while it is on it prevents accidental deletion."},{"id":"f84d7cd7-c3f0-411b-b5ff-aaadf24bff81","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>In Google Sheets, when you import the .xlsx file, protection becomes native \"protected ranges\" with the same effect.</em>"},{"id":"788ce705-d4f3-4e1a-ad0e-53e4120972db","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"9. How to scale the template week by week","anchorId":"scale"},{"id":"a51a38e5-8ea8-4f02-a7f4-50726ead4390","type":"paragraph","html":"The template ships with two example weeks (W12 and W13). To add a new week, the process is:"},{"id":"57828fb0-dcda-4835-9ebf-fce697ced21c","type":"list","ordered":true,"items":["\"Team\" sheet: review the \"Weekly absences\" column. If someone has holidays or a bank holiday, update their hours. Net capacity recalculates automatically.","\"Allocation\" sheet: add new rows for the following week. Use the Person and Project dropdowns. You can copy rows from the previous week and change the \"Week\" column and hours.","\"Insights\" sheet: do not touch anything. SUMIF formulas add up all Allocation rows regardless of week, so the dashboard updates itself."]},{"id":"0f541f8b-b650-4301-ba6e-0fee3e8fc7a8","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Tip: filter by week"},{"id":"ce61e5cd-2cbd-4d9e-886a-d10c99916dd0","type":"paragraph","html":"All data sheets have filters enabled. In Allocation you can filter by the \"Week\" column to see only the current week. In Insights you can filter by department to review a specific team’s load. Template totals always sum the full range, but visual filters let you focus on what matters for each meeting."},{"id":"cc766e22-e0c3-44de-8a52-13f0749f7475","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Limitation: because Insights sums all weeks, if you leave old Allocation rows in place, accumulated hours will grow week after week. For a \"this week only\" dashboard, filter or delete old week rows. This is one of the frictions of a manual model that an integrated tool solves automatically.</em>"},{"id":"00739174-09d7-4f69-9ae1-615d5e2d0c22","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"10. Google Sheets vs. Excel: does anything change?","anchorId":"sheetsVsExcel"},{"id":"39ee90cd-fa37-4731-8fab-1d48193ab30d","type":"paragraph","html":"The template works in both; the formulas are compatible. The meaningful difference is operational:"},{"id":"4b2c44e6-edd3-4398-90be-6a82abdf6bd9","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>Bottom line: the file format does not matter. The ceiling is the manual model, not whether you open .xlsx locally or import it into Drive.</strong>"},{"id":"ecee9039-a571-4a65-a1f9-b8fc77a3247f","type":"list","ordered":false,"items":["Real‑time collaboration: Sheets lets several people edit at once, which reduces the “v3 or v4?” problem. It does not, however, remove the risk of overwriting cells or breaking a formula by mistake.","Change history: Sheets saves versions automatically. Excel does too if you use OneDrive/SharePoint. In practice both cover the “who broke row 12?” case.","Dropdowns and protection: when you import the .xlsx into Google Sheets, dropdowns become native data‑validation lists and protection becomes protected ranges. No need to reconfigure anything.","Performance: with many rows and cross formulas, local Excel is usually smoother than Sheets in the browser. For templates covering 5–30 people, the difference is negligible."]},{"id":"94b6f0a9-db2b-4e9e-8c49-f5b17f60e93e","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"11. Evolution: from filling cells to passive planning","anchorId":"evolution"},{"id":"b21c783d-e78e-4ae8-911f-a420b4a8f879","type":"paragraph","html":"The logic you have just structured — net capacity, allocation grid, pacing, margin, and utilization — is exactly the same logic an integrated system uses. The difference is who maintains it: you by hand, or the tool in the background."},{"id":"61d5d967-a3d1-4d77-8b8b-231a30797980","type":"paragraph","html":"In Taimbox, you drag blocks in the hourly planner. Utilization reports, department‑level workload, and project‑level margin all flow from that movement without someone re‑importing numbers every Monday. The criteria are yours; the data‑crunching stops depending on copy‑paste."},{"id":"66487326-0da2-4ae8-81e8-1c7f148e841b","type":"paragraph","html":"This is not about “throwing Excel away” on day one: it is about moving the mental template (and the formulas) into a place where the data does not drift. The natural evolution once the team no longer fits comfortably in shared rows and columns."},{"id":"8f4e482d-2b19-4dd6-b223-3e2e889d8237","type":"callout","tone":"highlight","html":"Passive planning: you plan; Taimbox calculates utilization, margin, and capacity in the background. The metrics you used to build manually now emerge from how you actually work, without reconciling sheets.<br/><em>The profitability reports and the resource planner each have their own landing pages that go into the details.</em>"},{"id":"80046976-aac1-4c17-a53b-2cac4946f17f","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Frequently asked questions","anchorId":"preguntas-frecuentes"},{"id":"2fe31962-9c6c-4aa9-9712-5960bb96bab6","type":"faq","items":[{"q":"Do I need macros or VBA for the template to work?","a":"No. It only uses standard formulas (SUM, IF, SUMIF, VLOOKUP, SUMPRODUCT, COUNTIF) and native conditional formatting. It works in Excel, LibreOffice, and Google Sheets without enabling macros."},{"q":"How often do I need to update the template?","a":"Ideally at the start of each week (or the end of the previous one): adjust absences in the Team sheet and add allocations for the new week. Weekly cadence gives you time to react before overload turns into a crisis."},{"q":"From how many people does Excel stop being practical?","a":"There is no magic number; it depends more on the pace of change (new projects, staff changes) than on headcount. In practice many agencies feel the friction between roughly 8 and 15 people with several parallel projects: from that point on, weekly maintenance stops paying off."},{"q":"Can I use this template alongside a Kanban board (Trello, Asana…)?","a":"Yes. The board manages the flow of tasks; the resource template manages hours and capacity. They complement each other: the board tells you what is being worked on and the template tells you who has hours left to do it."},{"q":"What utilization range is “healthy” in an agency?","a":"As a rough guide, 70–85% of net capacity in many service agencies. Below that, you may have pipeline issues; above 90% you start to see burnout and errors. The ideal point depends on your mix of work (retainers, one‑off projects, internal R&D)."},{"q":"Does pacing account for months having different lengths?","a":"The formula divides budgeted hours by 4 weeks as an approximation. In months with 5 working weeks, real pacing will be slightly lower than shown. For most agencies this is accurate enough; if you need day‑level precision, an integrated system is a better fit."},{"q":"How do I update dropdowns when I add a new person or project?","a":"In Excel: go to the Allocation sheet, select the column with the dropdown, Data → Data validation, and extend the list range. In Google Sheets: click the cell, dropdown icon, edit list. Names must match exactly those in the Team or Projects sheets."}]},{"id":"39ed93bb-a58c-4671-a160-dbdc94a2d847","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Summary: what changes with a well‑built template","anchorId":"resumen"},{"id":"abaffaf5-3d9c-4479-bf4d-8d48a5fbc041","type":"paragraph","html":"The difference between an agency that “thinks it is doing fine” and one that knows it is usually lives in a handful of Excel columns: net capacity, assigned hours, utilization, pacing, and margin. It is not rocket science: it is data discipline, dropdowns so nothing breaks, protection so you do not overwrite what matters, and weekly review."},{"id":"3985de53-ec8c-41ea-85b1-d7aeb0038747","type":"paragraph","html":"When that discipline no longer scales with a sheet, the same logic can live in a tool that updates numbers passively. The criteria you have just learned do not expire; the medium you apply them in can evolve."},{"id":"461f1ded-bb0d-4e90-82d8-e7dc5573ea85","type":"paragraph","html":"The KPIs that go with this template — utilization, pacing, estimated vs. actual — are covered in more depth inKPIs for marketing agencies. Time‑management that keeps tasks from expanding without control appears inParkinson’s Lawandtimeboxing. The global picture of schedule + budget + team comes together inproject planning."},{"id":"e6e44495-9215-4e4c-a961-2dd29ba19bdb","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"The template is the first step; the planner is the next one","anchorId":"cta-final"},{"id":"eefb2bcf-725f-4f1a-8e54-4b138c058c06","type":"paragraph","html":"Capacity, allocation, pacing, and utilization without maintaining the sheet by hand. You can explore Taimbox with no commitment."},{"id":"818dda02-5883-49aa-8684-c7ad40eb3c57","type":"cta","text":"How Taimbox automates your template","href":"/planificador-recursos","variant":"primary"},{"id":"f2cb4e88-e565-4dd2-b224-299d0588a129","type":"cta","text":"Download .xlsx template","href":"/reportes-rentabilidad","variant":"secondary"},{"id":"4bd5092f-9f4a-47e9-ae8c-f9cc1439e0e1","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Written by the Taimbox team — Resource management and profitability for agencies.</em>"},{"id":"90bdf810-7813-4d99-a207-b8eb36235d8e","type":"relatedPost","slug":"planificacion-proyectos-cronograma-recursos"}]'::jsonb,
  json_ld_es = '{"@context":"https://schema.org","@graph":[{"@type":"Article","headline":"Plantilla gratuita de planificación de recursos para agencias","description":"Descarga nuestra plantilla de Excel/Google Sheets para gestionar la capacidad de tu equipo, el pacing de proyectos y el margen de tu agencia.","author":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"publisher":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"datePublished":"2026-03-24","inLanguage":"es","mainEntityOfPage":{"@type":"WebPage","@id":"https://taimbox.com/blog/plantilla-planificacion-recursos-agencia"}},{"@type":"FAQPage","mainEntity":[{"@type":"Question","name":"¿Necesito macros o VBA para que funcione la plantilla?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"No. Solo usa fórmulas estándar (SUMA, SI, SUMIF, VLOOKUP, SUMPRODUCT, COUNTIF) y formato condicional nativo. Funciona en Excel, LibreOffice y Google Sheets sin necesidad de habilitar macros."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"¿Cada cuánto hay que actualizar la plantilla?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Lo ideal es revisarla al inicio de cada semana (o al final de la anterior): ajustar ausencias en Equipo y añadir las asignaciones de la nueva semana. La frecuencia semanal da tiempo a reaccionar antes de que una sobrecarga se convierta en crisis."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"¿A partir de cuántas personas deja de ser práctico el Excel?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"No hay un número mágico; depende más del ritmo de cambios (proyectos nuevos, rotaciones) que del tamaño. En la práctica, muchas agencias notan la fricción entre 8 y 15 personas con múltiples proyectos simultáneos: ahí el mantenimiento semanal empieza a no compensar."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"¿Puedo usar esta plantilla junto a un tablero Kanban (Trello, Asana…)?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Sí: el Kanban gestiona el flujo de tareas; la plantilla de recursos gestiona horas y capacidad. Se complementan: el tablero dice «qué se está haciendo» y la plantilla dice «quién tiene horas libres para hacerlo»."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"¿Qué rango de utilización es «sano» en una agencia?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Orientativo: 70–85 % sobre capacidad neta en muchas agencias de servicios. Por debajo puede indicar falta de pipeline; por encima del 90 % empieza el riesgo de quemazo y errores. El mix de negocio (retainers, proyectos puntuales, I+D interna) cambia el objetivo."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"¿El pacing tiene en cuenta que no todos los meses duran lo mismo?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"La fórmula divide las horas presupuestadas entre 4 semanas como aproximación. En meses de 5 semanas laborales, el pacing real será ligeramente inferior al mostrado. Para la mayoría de agencias la aproximación es suficiente; si necesitas precisión al día, un sistema integrado lo resuelve mejor."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"¿Cómo actualizo los desplegables si añado una persona o proyecto nuevo?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"En Excel: ve a la hoja Asignación, selecciona la columna con el desplegable, Datos → Validación de datos, y amplía la lista. En Google Sheets: clic en la celda, icono de desplegable, editar lista. Los nombres deben coincidir exactamente con las hojas Equipo o Proyectos."}}]}]}'::jsonb,
  json_ld_en = '{"@context":"https://schema.org","@graph":[{"@type":"Article","headline":"Free agency resource planning template","description":"Download our Excel/Google Sheets template to manage your team''s capacity, project pacing, and agency margin.","author":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"publisher":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"datePublished":"2026-03-24","inLanguage":"en","mainEntityOfPage":{"@type":"WebPage","@id":"https://taimbox.com/en/blog/agency-resource-planning-template"}},{"@type":"FAQPage","mainEntity":[{"@type":"Question","name":"Do I need macros or VBA for the template to work?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"No. It only uses standard formulas (SUM, IF, SUMIF, VLOOKUP, SUMPRODUCT, COUNTIF) and native conditional formatting. It works in Excel, LibreOffice, and Google Sheets without enabling macros."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"How often do I need to update the template?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Ideally at the start of each week (or the end of the previous one): adjust absences in the Team sheet and add allocations for the new week. Weekly cadence gives you time to react before overload turns into a crisis."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"From how many people does Excel stop being practical?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"There is no magic number; it depends more on the pace of change (new projects, staff changes) than on headcount. In practice many agencies feel the friction between roughly 8 and 15 people with several parallel projects: from that point on, weekly maintenance stops paying off."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Can I use this template alongside a Kanban board (Trello, Asana…)?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Yes. The board manages the flow of tasks; the resource template manages hours and capacity. They complement each other: the board tells you what is being worked on and the template tells you who has hours left to do it."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"What utilization range is “healthy” in an agency?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"As a rough guide, 70–85% of net capacity in many service agencies. Below that, you may have pipeline issues; above 90% you start to see burnout and errors. The ideal point depends on your mix of work (retainers, one‑off projects, internal R&D)."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Does pacing account for months having different lengths?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"The formula divides budgeted hours by 4 weeks as an approximation. In months with 5 working weeks, real pacing will be slightly lower than shown. For most agencies this is accurate enough; if you need day‑level precision, an integrated system is a better fit."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"How do I update dropdowns when I add a new person or project?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"In Excel: go to the Allocation sheet, select the column with the dropdown, Data → Data validation, and extend the list range. In Google Sheets: click the cell, dropdown icon, edit list. Names must match exactly those in the Team or Projects sheets."}}]}]}'::jsonb
WHERE slug = 'plantilla-planificacion-recursos-agencia';

-- gestion-carga-trabajo-equipo-sin-burnout
UPDATE public.blog_posts SET
  blocks_es = '[{"id":"fc15a911-1403-4912-801f-8075543de867","type":"paragraph","html":"Los informes de Gallup y Workhuman (2024) dibujan un panorama duro: una gran mayoría de personas dice haber sentido al menos una vez síntomas de burnout profesional. En marketing y agencias no es raro encontrar equipos en los que casi la mitad describe una tensión constante, no solo un mes malo puntual. Ahí el problema deja de ser «anécdota» y se vuelve un asunto a la vez operativo y de personas."},{"id":"5fa4a830-d54e-4619-82fd-b64ab7d952a4","type":"paragraph","html":"Lo que falla casi nunca es que «no se trabaje». Lo que falla es que el trabajo está mal repartido, nadie ve de un vistazo quién lleva qué, y faltan límites claros cuando entra una petición nueva. Abajo encontrarás definiciones que aclaran el lío entre «quién hace qué» y «con qué medios», señales para detectar la saturación antes del colapso, un marco en seis pasos que puedes llevar a tu próxima reunión y una tabla de métricas para dejar de adivinar."},{"id":"3d6a4892-7c5c-4528-becd-2a56c4a6e60d","type":"callout","tone":"info","html":"La carga no flota en el vacío: vive dentro de la <LocaleLink1>planificación de proyectos</Link1> —fechas, dependencias, quién está disponible y cuándo—. Si quieres ese mapa con calma, todo encaja en la planificación de proyectos. Para cerrar con cifras que sirvan en una reunión de números, los <LocaleLink2>KPIs de rendimiento de la agencia</Link2> entran al detalle. Y si te frustra que todo «se alargue», la <LocaleLink3>Ley de Parkinson y los plazos</Link3> explica por qué, sin límites claros, el trabajo llena todo el espacio que le das."},{"id":"984402a4-d1ac-4717-964e-b56a6f3a5481","type":"toc"},{"id":"425a2e98-a0da-4b3a-860f-83bbc622ed93","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"1. Mapa rápido (por si quieres saltar)","anchorId":"mapa-carga"},{"id":"13ee5a22-e2e5-46c1-9600-3bbbdb4e7562","type":"paragraph","html":"Cada bloque va al grano. Si ya tienes algo claro, salta al siguiente. Lo notas cuando el lunes te venden «tranquilidad»… y a las 11 hay dos urgencias peleándose por el mismo diseñador."},{"id":"f4aa86b3-56cb-4306-8e16-47b5628dc89a","type":"table","headers":["Sección","Qué cierra esta parte","La idea que te llevas"],"rows":[["2. ¿Qué es la carga de trabajo?","Diferencia entre mucho trabajo y carga mal gestionada: planificación, reparto y sostenibilidad.","Gestionar carga es ver quién hace qué y si es sostenible en el tiempo, no solo «estar ocupados»."],["3. Causas del burnout","Estrés puntual vs. agotamiento que se queda; por qué el sistema importa más que el «aguante».","Sin pausas ni reglas claras, el estrés deja de ser un pico y se convierte en fondo."],["4. Señales de riesgo","Cómo detectar saturación antes del crack mezclando intuición y datos.","Mucha gente no dice «no puedo más» hasta tarde; hay que preguntar y mirar reparto y plazos."],["5. Framework en 6 pasos","Pasos concretos para visibilizar, priorizar, repartir con criterio y proteger el foco.","Repartir bien no es el mismo número de tareas para todos: es capacidad real, habilidad y contexto."],["6. Rol del manager","Cultura y liderazgo: qué permites en reuniones y cómo respondes cuando piden aire.","El burnout no es solo «tema personal»; el tono del equipo y los límites marcan el techo."],["7. Burnout ya instalado","Qué hacer cuando el equipo va fundido: varias palancas a la vez (carga, expectativas, apoyo).","Minimizar con frases hechas empeora; hace falta acción visible y repriorizar sin humo."]]},{"id":"e9d6fc88-312f-460b-a5dd-4137880b3f3d","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"2. ¿Qué es realmente la carga de trabajo? (y por qué no es solo «tener mucho trabajo»)","anchorId":"que-es-carga"},{"id":"0d6f95d7-735e-4ac2-99aa-e184e3ad2597","type":"paragraph","html":"Muchos equipos confunden carga alta con carga mal llevada. Gestionar la carga es, en la práctica, planificar quién hace qué, repartir con criterio y mirar si eso es sostenible en el tiempo."},{"id":"61c10d35-8b85-4373-828e-a2dea48ce3f2","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"3. Las causas reales del burnout (que muchos managers no ven)","anchorId":"causas-burnout"},{"id":"5ec5d187-6f9b-4987-9a29-9e776057a8e3","type":"paragraph","html":"El estrés puntual —un lanzamiento, una campaña que despega— puede ser brutal y, aun así, llevable si después hay respiro y las reglas son claras. El burnout es otra historia: se queda, te desconecta del trabajo y te hace sentir que rindes menos aunque sigas esforzándote."},{"id":"7d888c26-1ca9-4589-8eea-8533b3c1de5d","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"4. Cómo detectar que tu equipo está en riesgo: señales tempranas","anchorId":"senales-riesgo"},{"id":"20465b0b-e3a5-4a70-9f39-5a74d1df1b9d","type":"paragraph","html":"¿Cómo saber si el equipo va al límite antes de que alguien reviente? Mezcla intuición y números. Mucha gente no dice «no puedo más» hasta muy tarde."},{"id":"409f8b64-6101-4731-93f4-a304410177a8","type":"visualRef","visualId":"SenalesCargaAlertaVisual"},{"id":"424e953e-85e7-4d0c-908c-069540f6a754","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"5. Framework para gestionar la carga de trabajo de forma sostenible","anchorId":"framework-6-pasos"},{"id":"80807bd8-e4f0-45f2-bd99-09d9741c8c2c","type":"paragraph","html":"Seis pasos que puedes aplicar el lunes que viene, incluso con las mismas herramientas de siempre. Repartir bien no es dar a todos el mismo número de tareas: es repartir según capacidad real, habilidad y el estado actual de cada persona."},{"id":"6ef39a54-c7f6-4c97-92c6-5c36d9f600b0","type":"visualRef","visualId":"CargaTrabajoFrameworkVisual"},{"id":"03da1a10-e217-4b63-aac3-f6442c2dddff","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"6. El rol del manager: liderar sin quemar al equipo","anchorId":"rol-manager"},{"id":"69cf7f0a-f3b7-46d2-b6d3-863a60ead5e8","type":"paragraph","html":"El burnout no es un «tema personal» que se arregla con más fuerza de voluntad. En buena medida es cultura y liderazgo: qué permites en las reuniones, cómo respondes cuando alguien pide margen, y si el reconocimiento solo llega cuando hay incendio."},{"id":"965c322c-74a4-472d-abdf-691dc1d2693b","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"7. Burnout ya instalado: qué hacer cuando es demasiado tarde para prevenir","anchorId":"burnout-instalado"},{"id":"95f91fbc-5891-4d03-8814-669128821e94","type":"paragraph","html":"Si ya estás en fase de «equipo fundido», el peor error es restarle importancia con frases hechas. Hay que actuar a la vez en varios frentes: carga, expectativas y apoyo."},{"id":"5c1fdcfb-3e84-4d1d-a143-cc4b9cce7da4","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"8. Métricas que todo manager debería tener controladas","anchorId":"metricas-carga"},{"id":"4d83fa49-c5bd-4b2b-af65-003b827147cb","type":"paragraph","html":"Si quieres medir la carga sin quedarte solo en el «yo creo que van justos», la tabla de esta guía es un buen punto de partida. Los porcentajes son orientativos: lo que vale en una consultora no tiene por qué valer en una casa de producción."},{"id":"5560ea0c-6967-4b4c-8b93-76044aa3e236","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"9. Herramientas que suelen ayudar (por tipo, sin marcas)","anchorId":"herramientas-workload"},{"id":"098ab789-ffb8-4df9-ae33-88a369448ec5","type":"paragraph","html":"No te voy a vender un nombre propio: lo que importa es qué agujero estás tapando. ¿Necesitas ver quién lleva qué? ¿Te faltan horas reales frente al presupuesto? ¿O saber el clima antes de que explote en público?"},{"id":"3ed7d280-6a53-4e6b-856d-3f07f153d57b","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"10. Conclusión","anchorId":"conclusion"},{"id":"06b0b92e-fced-4d91-8b51-db177a86a274","type":"paragraph","html":"El burnout no es que la gente «no aguante». Suele ser la foto de un reparto de carga y unos límites que no están listos para medirse. La buena noticia es que hay cosas concretas que puedes hacer: ver la carga, decidir prioridades en voz alta, repartir con criterio, recortar alcance cuando toque, proteger el foco y revisar cómo va la semana."},{"id":"c1aa2ea1-f211-4ddb-aed1-f03ea5d02b20","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Preguntas frecuentes","anchorId":"preguntas-frecuentes"},{"id":"2a9db3da-9b31-4b56-9ce8-45330173eeef","type":"faq","items":[{"q":"¿Cuánto es demasiada carga de trabajo?","a":"No hay un número mágico: depende del rol. Pero ojo si la utilización se queda muy por encima del ~85% durante largo rato, si estimado y real nunca coinciden, si hay más retrabajo o si los plazos empiezan a caerse todos a la vez. En la práctica, «demasiado» es cuando deja de ser un pico y se convierte en rutina sin respiro."},{"q":"¿Cómo sé si mi equipo tiene burnout?","a":"Cruza lo que ves (cansancio, cinismo, calidad bajando, gente que se encierra) con lo que miden los datos: plazos, reparto de tareas gordas, quién acumula riesgo. Y no esperes a que alguien lo diga en una reunión: pregunta a menudo y deja sitio para respuestas honestas."},{"q":"¿Qué diferencia hay entre estrés y burnout?","a":"El estrés puede venir con una fecha de caducidad: termina el lanzamiento y baja la tensión. El burnout se queda: agotamiento que no recuperas con un fin de semana, desgana con el trabajo y sensación de ir más lento pese a esforzarte. Ahí hace falta tocar el sistema, no solo «más aguante»."},{"q":"¿Cómo repartir tareas equitativamente en una agencia?","a":"«Equitativo» no es repartir el mismo número de tickets. Es que el riesgo y el esfuerzo vivan repartidos: capacidad real, habilidad, qué tan crítico es cada encargo y en qué fase está el proyecto. Rota lo que pesa para que no siempre caiga en los mismos dos perfiles."},{"q":"¿Hay alguna herramienta imprescindible para la carga de trabajo?","a":"Ninguna salva un equipo sin acuerdos. Lo que cuenta es decidir dónde está «la verdad» (tablero, hoja, ERP) y cumplirla entre todos. Elige categorías —tareas, horas, Gantt, encuestas— según lo que ahora mismo no estás viendo."}]},{"id":"278811d7-93f1-4001-9781-cd8e27ad733e","type":"paragraph","html":"Si te ha picado el gusanillo de pasar de intuición a números que sirvan en comité, aquí van dos lecturas que suelen cerrar el círculo: KPIs de rendimiento en agencias y planificación de proyectos."},{"id":"efd73a06-0685-4c88-896b-028e5571ecf3","type":"cta","text":"Probar Taimbox","href":"/planificador-recursos","variant":"primary"},{"id":"4e733d10-54dc-4e33-911c-8b212ca83fbc","type":"relatedPost","slug":"kpis-agencias-marketing-2026"}]'::jsonb,
  blocks_en = '[{"id":"e9dee19c-396a-449a-aa0c-b702a860461a","type":"paragraph","html":"Reports from Gallup and Workhuman (2024) paint a tough picture: a large majority of people say they have felt symptoms of professional burnout at least once. In marketing and agencies, it''s not uncommon to find teams where nearly half describe a constant tension, not just a one-off bad month. There, the problem stops being ''anecdotal'' and becomes both an operations and a people issue."},{"id":"8b17d3d6-14c5-4ac0-8263-334fcbd2000d","type":"paragraph","html":"What fails is almost never that ''no work is being done''. What fails is that work is badly distributed, nobody sees at a glance who is carrying what, and clear limits are missing when a new request comes in. Below you will find definitions that clarify the mess between ''who does what'' and ''with what means'', signs to detect saturation before collapse, a six-step framework you can steal for your next meeting, and a table of metrics to stop guessing."},{"id":"814ed216-268c-46cc-90ca-aee54b9517e4","type":"callout","tone":"info","html":"Load doesn''t float in a vacuum: it lives inside <LocaleLink1>project planning</Link1> —dates, dependencies, who is available when—. If you want that map with calm, it''s all tied together in project planning. To wrap up with figures that serve in a numbers meeting, the <LocaleLink2>agency performance KPIs</Link2> go into detail. And if it frustrates you that everything ''drags on'', <LocaleLink3>Parkinson''s Law and deadlines</Link3> tells you why, without clear caps, work fills all the space you give it."},{"id":"a3ba2a21-186d-48f2-a348-78d462884985","type":"toc"},{"id":"64720129-e927-4132-98b6-c40c8ce4ca48","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"1. Quick map (if you want to skip ahead)","anchorId":"mapa-carga"},{"id":"b18e7353-c7f3-427e-a59a-56c87a68b725","type":"paragraph","html":"Each block gets straight to the point. If you already have something clear, move on to the next. You notice it when on Monday they sell you ''tranquility''... and by 11 AM there are two emergencies fighting for the same designer."},{"id":"d1861f20-1ad6-465a-b4d2-2e37d465053a","type":"table","headers":["Section","What this part settles","The takeaway"],"rows":[["2. What is workload?","High load vs poorly managed load: planning, distribution, and sustainability.","Managing load means seeing who does what and whether it''s sustainable—not just staying busy."],["3. Causes of burnout","Short-term stress vs exhaustion that lingers; why the system matters more than ''toughing it out''.","Without breaks and clear rules, stress stops being a spike and becomes the baseline."],["4. Warning signs","How to spot overload before someone breaks—blend intuition with numbers.","Many people don''t say ''I can''t cope'' until very late; ask often and watch allocation and deadlines."],["5. Six-step framework","Concrete steps to make work visible, prioritize, distribute fairly, and protect focus.","Fair distribution isn''t the same task count for everyone—it''s real capacity, skill, and context."],["6. The manager''s role","Culture and leadership: what you allow in meetings and how you react when people ask for slack.","Burnout isn''t only a ''personal issue''—team tone and boundaries set the ceiling."],["7. Burnout already set in","What to do when the team is already burnt out: several levers at once—load, expectations, support.","Downplaying with clichés makes it worse; you need visible action and honest reprioritization."]]},{"id":"4b49083f-7d71-46af-b8bf-e5118771aa36","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"2. What is workload really? (and why it''s not just ''having a lot of work'')","anchorId":"que-es-carga"},{"id":"80a6e655-7092-4f3f-894e-ab3f6f0bb95b","type":"paragraph","html":"Many teams confuse high load with poorly managed load. Managing the load is, in practice, planning who does what, distributing wisely and looking at whether that''s sustainable over time."},{"id":"d1528458-ccfd-4a0e-92f3-dec1172c8ea4","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"3. The real causes of burnout (that managers often don''t see)","anchorId":"causas-burnout"},{"id":"748154ce-6a32-46e4-bcd7-4d810511c97f","type":"paragraph","html":"Short-term stress —a launch, a campaign that takes off— can be brutal and yet bearable if there''s a break afterwards and the rules are clear. Burnout is another story: it stays, disconnects you from work, and makes you feel like you''re performing less even though you''re still working hard."},{"id":"5e8aa47b-e09c-4cf3-a7c6-7c7249e19340","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"4. How to detect that your team is at risk: early warning signs","anchorId":"senales-riesgo"},{"id":"29fcc6da-01ed-4576-b2b1-60a61d363832","type":"paragraph","html":"How to know if the team is on the edge before someone explodes? Mix intuition with numbers. Many people don''t say ''I can''t take it anymore'' until very late."},{"id":"e6ef647b-93af-459c-ae25-fc5f9d61336c","type":"visualRef","visualId":"SenalesCargaAlertaVisual"},{"id":"0b01412d-bc71-4124-a2f4-d505f4d205a4","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"5. Framework for managing workload sustainably","anchorId":"framework-6-pasos"},{"id":"64db1632-b2d2-4ea2-b111-e0d4f4e6aaac","type":"paragraph","html":"Six steps you can apply next Monday, even with the same tools as always. Distributing well isn''t giving everyone the same number of tasks: it''s distributing according to real capacity, skill, and the current state of each person."},{"id":"d97fd615-5833-4261-a467-137f62b2fc44","type":"visualRef","visualId":"CargaTrabajoFrameworkVisual"},{"id":"1cdd9a30-5212-4702-beb9-3ca779e454ec","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"6. The manager''s role: leading without burning out the team","anchorId":"rol-manager"},{"id":"06e9cd5e-2dd7-4b31-993d-1fce143feecd","type":"paragraph","html":"Burnout isn''t a ''personal issue'' to be fixed with more willpower. It''s largely a matter of culture and leadership: what you allow in meetings, how you react when someone asks for room, and if recognition only comes when there''s a fire."},{"id":"8d4c0f26-4d54-4888-bdab-de5f846f446a","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"7. Burnout already set in: what to do when it''s too late to prevent","anchorId":"burnout-instalado"},{"id":"52036acd-24c4-4a05-9455-61e6bdb4240d","type":"paragraph","html":"If you''re already in a ''burnt-out team'' phase, the worst mistake is downplaying it with clichés. You have to act on several fronts at once —load, expectations, and support."},{"id":"c7f9df06-4113-49a3-b536-664f23a7ca7f","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"8. Metrics that every manager should have under control","anchorId":"metricas-carga"},{"id":"8cfaf753-bd87-42df-b969-77ffb7e9c13b","type":"paragraph","html":"If you want to measure load without sticking to ''I think they''re on the edge'', this table is a good starting point. The percentages are indicative: what works in a consulting firm doesn''t necessarily work in a production house."},{"id":"fa02c8e5-df95-4d3e-8216-2bb27a5f4d7c","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"9. Tools that usually help (by type, without brands)","anchorId":"herramientas-workload"},{"id":"958af5c4-23a1-4b91-b440-2599b064f0ec","type":"paragraph","html":"I''m not going to sell you a specific name: what matters is what hole you''re plugging. Do you need to see who is carrying what? Are you missing real hours vs budget? Or is it knowing the mood before it explodes in public?"},{"id":"d5fbe882-b073-41f1-9c03-b21194ee58bc","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"10. Conclusion","anchorId":"conclusion"},{"id":"09744933-46b5-43af-9418-ff3cc9f1d607","type":"paragraph","html":"Burnout isn''t that people ''can''t hack it''. It''s often the picture of a workload distribution and limits that aren''t measurement-ready. The good part is that there are concrete things you can do: see the load, decide priorities out loud, distribute wisely, cut scope when needed, protect focus, and review how the week is going."},{"id":"1516e7e1-7f0e-42bb-b8cd-df5e9eb1f4f5","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Frequently Asked Questions","anchorId":"preguntas-frecuentes"},{"id":"73191b27-a8c8-47a1-9ab3-13f51e894f98","type":"faq","items":[{"q":"How much is too much workload?","a":"There is no magic number: it depends on the role. But watch out if utilization stays well above ~85% for a long time, if estimate and actual never match, if there is more rework, or if deadlines start falling all at once. In practice, \"too much\" is when it stops being a peak and becomes a breathless routine."},{"q":"How do I know if my team has burnout?","a":"Cross what you see (fatigue, cynicism, declining quality, people closing themselves off) with what the data measures: deadlines, distribution of heavy tasks, who accumulates risk. And don''t wait for someone to say it in a meeting: ask often and leave room for honest answers."},{"q":"What is the difference between stress and burnout?","a":"Stress can come with an expiration date: the launch ends and tension drops. Burnout stays: exhaustion that you don''t recover from with a weekend, reluctance to work, and the feeling of going slower despite trying harder. That''s when you need to touch the system, not just ''more endurance''."},{"q":"How to distribute tasks equitably in an agency?","a":" \"Equitable\" is not distributing the same number of tickets. It is that risk and effort live distributed: real capacity, skill, how critical each assignment is, and what phase the project is in. Rotate what weighs so it doesn''t always fall on the same two profiles."},{"q":"Is there any essential tool for workload?","a":"None saves a team without agreements. What counts is deciding where ''the truth'' is (board, sheet, ERP) and fulfilling it among everyone. Choose categories — tasks, hours, Gantt, surveys — according to what you are not seeing right now."}]},{"id":"6e13cd7e-b99f-41ba-aca9-8a1975248fed","type":"paragraph","html":"If you''re curious about moving from intuition to numbers that serve in a committee, here are two reads that usually close the circle: Agency performance KPIs and Project planning."},{"id":"4714bfe4-5385-4455-96eb-9550ebd8bd40","type":"cta","text":"Probar Taimbox","href":"/planificador-recursos","variant":"primary"},{"id":"b6a356e5-a284-4cab-924b-16f178522c0e","type":"relatedPost","slug":"kpis-agencias-marketing-2026"}]'::jsonb,
  json_ld_es = '{"@context":"https://schema.org","@graph":[{"@type":"Article","headline":"Cómo gestionar la carga de trabajo de tu equipo sin burnout","description":"Los informes de Gallup y Workhuman (2024) dibujan un panorama duro: una gran mayoría de personas dice haber sentido al menos una vez síntomas de burnout profesional. En marketing y agencias no es raro encontrar equipos en los que casi la mitad describe una tensión constante, no solo un mes malo puntual. Ahí el problema deja de ser «anécdota» y se vuelve un asunto a la vez operativo y de personas.Lo que falla casi nunca es que «no se trabaje». Lo que falla es que el trabajo está mal repartido, nadie ve de un vistazo quién lleva qué, y faltan límites claros cuando entra una petición nueva. Abajo encontrarás definiciones que aclaran el lío entre «quién hace qué» y «con qué medios», señales para detectar la saturación antes del colapso, un marco en seis pasos que puedes llevar a tu próxima reunión y una tabla de métricas para dejar de adivinar.La carga no flota en el vacío: vive dentro de la <LocaleLink1>planificación de proyectos</Link1> —fechas, dependencias, quién está disponible y cuándo—. Si quieres ese mapa con calma, todo encaja en la planificación de proyectos. Para cerrar con cifras que sirvan en una reunión de números, los <LocaleLink2>KPIs de rendimiento de la agencia</Link2> entran al detalle. Y si te frustra que todo «se alargue», la <LocaleLink3>Ley de Parkinson y los plazos</Link3> explica por qué, sin límites claros, el trabajo llena todo el espacio que le das.","author":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"publisher":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"datePublished":"2026-03-26","inLanguage":"es","mainEntityOfPage":{"@type":"WebPage","@id":"https://taimbox.com/blog/gestion-carga-trabajo-equipo-sin-burnout"}},{"@type":"FAQPage","mainEntity":[{"@type":"Question","name":"¿Cuánto es demasiada carga de trabajo?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"No hay un número mágico: depende del rol. Pero ojo si la utilización se queda muy por encima del ~85% durante largo rato, si estimado y real nunca coinciden, si hay más retrabajo o si los plazos empiezan a caerse todos a la vez. En la práctica, «demasiado» es cuando deja de ser un pico y se convierte en rutina sin respiro."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"¿Cómo sé si mi equipo tiene burnout?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Cruza lo que ves (cansancio, cinismo, calidad bajando, gente que se encierra) con lo que miden los datos: plazos, reparto de tareas gordas, quién acumula riesgo. Y no esperes a que alguien lo diga en una reunión: pregunta a menudo y deja sitio para respuestas honestas."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"¿Qué diferencia hay entre estrés y burnout?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"El estrés puede venir con una fecha de caducidad: termina el lanzamiento y baja la tensión. El burnout se queda: agotamiento que no recuperas con un fin de semana, desgana con el trabajo y sensación de ir más lento pese a esforzarte. Ahí hace falta tocar el sistema, no solo «más aguante»."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"¿Cómo repartir tareas equitativamente en una agencia?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"«Equitativo» no es repartir el mismo número de tickets. Es que el riesgo y el esfuerzo vivan repartidos: capacidad real, habilidad, qué tan crítico es cada encargo y en qué fase está el proyecto. Rota lo que pesa para que no siempre caiga en los mismos dos perfiles."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"¿Hay alguna herramienta imprescindible para la carga de trabajo?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Ninguna salva un equipo sin acuerdos. Lo que cuenta es decidir dónde está «la verdad» (tablero, hoja, ERP) y cumplirla entre todos. Elige categorías —tareas, horas, Gantt, encuestas— según lo que ahora mismo no estás viendo."}}]},{"@type":"SoftwareApplication","name":"Taimbox","applicationCategory":"BusinessApplication","description":"Planificador de recursos y tiempo para agencias. Timeboxing, cronograma por horas y reportes de rentabilidad."}]}'::jsonb,
  json_ld_en = '{"@context":"https://schema.org","@graph":[{"@type":"Article","headline":"How to manage your team''s workload without burnout","description":"Reports from Gallup and Workhuman (2024) paint a tough picture: a large majority of people say they have felt symptoms of professional burnout at least once. In marketing and agencies, it''s not uncommon to find teams where nearly half describe a constant tension, not just a one-off bad month. There, the problem stops being ''anecdotal'' and becomes both an operations and a people issue.What fails is almost never that ''no work is being done''. What fails is that work is badly distributed, nobody sees at a glance who is carrying what, and clear limits are missing when a new request comes in. Below you will find definitions that clarify the mess between ''who does what'' and ''with what means'', signs to detect saturation before collapse, a six-step framework you can steal for your next meeting, and a table of metrics to stop guessing.Load doesn''t float in a vacuum: it lives inside <LocaleLink1>project planning</Link1> —dates, dependencies, who is available when—. If you want that map with calm, it''s all tied together in project planning. To wrap up with figures that serve in a numbers meeting, the <LocaleLink2>agency performance KPIs</Link2> go into detail. And if it frustrates you that everything ''drags on'', <LocaleLink3>Parkinson''s Law and deadlines</Link3> tells you why, without clear caps, work fills all the space you give it.","author":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"publisher":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"datePublished":"2026-03-26","inLanguage":"en","mainEntityOfPage":{"@type":"WebPage","@id":"https://taimbox.com/en/blog/workload-management-without-burnout"}},{"@type":"FAQPage","mainEntity":[{"@type":"Question","name":"How much is too much workload?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"There is no magic number: it depends on the role. But watch out if utilization stays well above ~85% for a long time, if estimate and actual never match, if there is more rework, or if deadlines start falling all at once. In practice, \"too much\" is when it stops being a peak and becomes a breathless routine."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"How do I know if my team has burnout?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Cross what you see (fatigue, cynicism, declining quality, people closing themselves off) with what the data measures: deadlines, distribution of heavy tasks, who accumulates risk. And don''t wait for someone to say it in a meeting: ask often and leave room for honest answers."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"What is the difference between stress and burnout?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Stress can come with an expiration date: the launch ends and tension drops. Burnout stays: exhaustion that you don''t recover from with a weekend, reluctance to work, and the feeling of going slower despite trying harder. That''s when you need to touch the system, not just ''more endurance''."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"How to distribute tasks equitably in an agency?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":" \"Equitable\" is not distributing the same number of tickets. It is that risk and effort live distributed: real capacity, skill, how critical each assignment is, and what phase the project is in. Rotate what weighs so it doesn''t always fall on the same two profiles."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Is there any essential tool for workload?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"None saves a team without agreements. What counts is deciding where ''the truth'' is (board, sheet, ERP) and fulfilling it among everyone. Choose categories — tasks, hours, Gantt, surveys — according to what you are not seeing right now."}}]},{"@type":"SoftwareApplication","name":"Taimbox","applicationCategory":"BusinessApplication","description":"Agency resource and time planner. Timeboxing, hourly schedule, and profitability reports."}]}'::jsonb
