-- como-medir-rentabilidad-proyecto-agencia-dejar-vender-horas
UPDATE public.blog_posts SET
  blocks_es = '[{"id":"781251a7-a5fc-4fcd-9a38-213f77a45843","type":"callout","tone":"highlight","html":"<strong>TL;DR — Lo esencial en 3 puntos</strong><br/>Vender horas tiene un techo natural: solo hay tantas horas al día por persona. Las agencias que ganan margen sin inflar plantilla suelen haber cambiado **qué venden**, no cuánto sudan.<br/>El **margen bruto por proyecto** es la métrica que separa quien factura mucho de quien se queda con dinero. Hacer el ejercicio con tus últimos diez proyectos suele ser incómodo y útil a la vez.<br/>El scope creep no es solo «clientes difíciles»: es falta de contenedor. Un protocolo de tres pasos —registrar, cuantificar, comunicar— se puede poner en marcha sin esperar al próximo trimestre."},{"id":"e11d87a7-ae9f-450e-809c-a75510bf363e","type":"paragraph","html":"Si ya leíste por qué <LocaleLink>estar ocupado no significa ser rentable</LocaleLink>, el siguiente paso es incómodo de verdad: mirar los proyectos uno a uno y preguntarte si el precio tenía sentido con el coste real —no con el coste que te gustaría creer."},{"id":"1c3d30d5-2ad2-4066-a9d0-02ae5eb9a879","type":"paragraph","html":"Aquí vas a encontrar <strong>modelos de pricing con pros y contras</strong>, un cálculo de margen que puedes llevar a una hoja sin filosofía, un protocolo de alcance que evita trabajar gratis por omisión, y una forma de enmarcar el trabajo en ciclos cortos para que el tiempo deje de ser un río sin orillas."},{"id":"f03d0427-09f5-438a-a0c6-1b89ca679119","type":"toc"},{"id":"718d21c3-bc52-49b8-b02c-ab7ab26e304c","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"1. Por qué vender horas tiene un techo y cómo romperlo","anchorId":"techo-horas"},{"id":"c713126f-f4c0-4388-891d-9559cde76f92","type":"paragraph","html":"Cuando el precio está atado al tiempo, <strong>la eficiencia se penaliza sola</strong>: si el equipo hace en dos horas lo que antes tardaba cuatro, cobras la mitad por el mismo resultado. Ese incentivo perverso explica por qué muchas agencias se quedan atrapadas en una carrera de más horas o más cabezas."},{"id":"12f11d91-ac71-4ee1-93f8-d5e871a6fc24","type":"paragraph","html":"Te lo encontrarás en el “buenas noticias”: el equipo mejora el proceso, reduce tiempos, y aun así el mes no cumple porque la facturación también baja. Es el techo hablando claro, no tú perdiendo motivación."},{"id":"ab2b2db3-259b-4e9b-8297-ebe02c053d3b","type":"paragraph","html":"Además, el precio hora es fácil de comparar entre proveedores; el precio atado a un <strong>resultado con alcance definido</strong> no lo es tanto. Eso cambia la conversación —si tienes autoridad y datos para sostenerla."},{"id":"94fa6ebf-a821-45de-8148-49d40f1428d1","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Pricing basado en valor: cuándo es realista"},{"id":"cd46e71c-33fa-4e70-8587-7fc3f1f234a1","type":"paragraph","html":"Desvincular el precio del tiempo y acercarlo al impacto para el cliente puede subir margen sin subir headcount. Funciona si tienes datos de resultados previos y track record demostrado; sin eso, es una negociación difícil de ganar. En el fondo, es vender la solución al problema, no el tiempo que tardas en teclearla."},{"id":"e09f4461-728f-47fb-b891-2aa1dcffeb63","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"2. Modelos de pricing: pros, contras y el modelo híbrido","anchorId":"modelos-pricing"},{"id":"2818d386-3719-4f60-aa2c-72321093ce4c","type":"paragraph","html":"No hay un modelo perfecto, pero sí hay modelos que atraen los problemas que no quieres. La cicatriz típica es el fee que parece estable hasta que el cliente mete “un favorcito” cada tres días y el margen desaparece."},{"id":"560373b6-f102-428e-a44e-efe149381a27","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Precio por hora / Time & Materials"},{"id":"386175c9-8333-4010-a785-8dfce68ac388","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>Pros:</strong> Seguridad de cobro por cada minuto invertido."},{"id":"c825f9ac-fb97-41af-a10b-ec1ce4d97f65","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>Contras:</strong> Penaliza la eficiencia y dificulta la previsión de ingresos para el cliente."},{"id":"bc098d21-5b4a-4183-8581-0f195c221704","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Precio fijo por proyecto"},{"id":"d462e953-814d-414b-88c7-64b1cc7837df","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>Pros:</strong> Claridad total para el cliente y premio a la rapidez si tienes procesos finos."},{"id":"4f68eb40-f869-45a9-a650-b6aa15575595","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>Contras:</strong> Todo el riesgo de desviación (scope creep) lo asume la agencia."},{"id":"2cf50af8-84f1-4b5f-9d41-a8f26541bdf4","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Retainer mensual (Fee recurrente)"},{"id":"2df09c82-9003-46e1-8705-26477e135045","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>Pros:</strong> Predecibilidad de caja y relación a largo plazo."},{"id":"6f08df96-933c-4f67-a280-a8e0d3208822","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>Contras:</strong> Tendencia a la «comodidad» del cliente (pide de más) y a la «relajación» de la agencia (mide de menos)."},{"id":"44e2e030-848a-4db8-bca7-e6fdce659fdd","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"El modelo híbrido: lo mejor de dos mundos"},{"id":"c814350d-8c0e-47bf-8039-d11a5d3819cd","type":"paragraph","html":"La mayoría de agencias rentables usan un mix: un **fee base** para el mantenimiento y **proyectos cerrados** para iniciativas nuevas o picos de trabajo. Eso asegura el suelo de ingresos y protege el margen de los extras."},{"id":"6c7b1656-5ef3-4f85-affd-f079573d0dcd","type":"visualRef","visualId":"OcupacionVsRentabilidadChart"},{"id":"6f5e5274-e29b-402c-b6cb-f4370a6cd3b3","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"3. Cómo calcular el margen bruto real por proyecto","anchorId":"calcular-rentabilidad"},{"id":"6d2d1156-4d6b-41b9-a8f7-9aecc577c37a","type":"paragraph","html":"Ojo: el margen neto de la agencia (lo que queda después de pagar oficina, software y administración) importa, pero la batalla se gana en el **margen bruto por proyecto**. Si el proyecto por sí solo no deja aire, la agencia no tiene futuro."},{"id":"e814ba15-ae72-4d81-ab4b-5438a928f3d9","type":"callout","tone":"info","html":"<strong>La fórmula básica</strong><br/>(Ingresos del proyecto − Costes directos) / Ingresos × 100<br/>Donde el **coste directo** incluye las horas del equipo (a coste cargado: sueldo + seguridad social + extras), freelancers y herramientas específicas del encargo."},{"id":"7fd4cc42-804b-4bf7-a2a6-84a21345137e","type":"callout","tone":"highlight","html":"<strong>Referencias rápidas</strong><br/>Saludable: > 50-60%. Tienes aire para cubrir overhead y crecer.<br/>Peligro: < 35-40%. El proyecto apenas paga su propia ejecución; estás subvencionando al cliente con tu estructura."},{"id":"32ba2f2e-c9ff-4aad-914c-c793c7242639","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"4. El protocolo de alcance en tres pasos","anchorId":"scope-protocolo"},{"id":"2ba900b5-cbfe-4056-b81d-005b878a2346","type":"paragraph","html":"El scope creep (alcance que crece) destruye más márgenes que la mala suerte. No se frena con enfados, se frena con un contenedor. La cicatriz es el “pero si esto ya estaba” que te sueltan cuando intentas cobrar la quinta revisión."},{"id":"8a476394-3f4f-42db-a62f-7e76896670a9","type":"list","ordered":true,"items":["<strong>Registrar:</strong> nada se acepta por chat o de palabra sin que entre en el sistema de gestión.","<strong>Cuantificar:</strong> ¿cuántas horas son? ¿qué impacto tiene en la fecha final?","<strong>Comunicar:</strong> «Esto está fuera del alcance original. Podemos hacerlo sumando X al presupuesto o quitando Y de la cola actual». El cliente elige, tú no pierdes."]},{"id":"3b80dd87-6537-4a6e-9295-f0b0d263985e","type":"visualRef","visualId":"ScopeProtocoloInfographic"},{"id":"f8f29173-b879-4a9a-8e71-cfb2f8215f81","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"5. El modelo de sprint: de fee infinito a ciclos cerrados","anchorId":"modelo-sprint"},{"id":"40db35bd-b491-4488-90f6-0a1f035204e4","type":"paragraph","html":"Trabajar por sprints (ciclos de 1 o 2 semanas) ayuda a que el tiempo no se dilate. En lugar de un proyecto de tres meses que se deforma, tienes 6 entregas de dos semanas con objetivos inamovibles. Lo notas cuando el equipo deja de preguntar “¿cuándo acaba esto?” y empieza a decir “esto entra en el sprint que viene”."},{"id":"82e4c9fc-da2f-4f75-a771-b4334163db1d","type":"paragraph","html":"Si quieres conectar el calendario con la capacidad real de tu gente, la <LocaleLink>planificación de recursos del equipo</LocaleLink> cuenta cómo unir fechas y cabezas sin que nadie explote. Y para saber si el ritmo es el adecuado, el <LocaleLink>pacing de proyectos</LocaleLink> te da el pulso en tiempo real."},{"id":"a1a16e9f-9164-4fcc-a7dc-99985abf4cea","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Preguntas frecuentes","anchorId":"preguntas-frecuentes"},{"id":"7fe34c7e-8aef-48cb-b202-ac3b606b6aa8","type":"faq","items":[{"q":"¿Qué margen bruto debe tener una agencia de marketing?","a":"La referencia habitual en agencias de servicios sitúa un margen bruto saludable por encima del 50% por proyecto. Por debajo del 40%, el proyecto difícilmente cubre costes indirectos y overhead de forma sostenible. El margen bruto se calcula como (ingresos – coste directo) / ingresos × 100."},{"q":"¿Cómo se cobra el trabajo extra fuera del alcance en una agencia?","a":"El proceso más efectivo tiene tres pasos: registrar la solicitud en el momento, estimar el tiempo antes de aceptar, y comunicar el impacto al cliente antes de ejecutar. La pregunta que cambia la conversación es: ''¿Lo añadimos ajustando el presupuesto, o lo dejamos para el próximo sprint?''"},{"q":"¿Qué es mejor para una agencia: retainer o precio por proyecto?","a":"Depende del tipo de servicio. El retainer funciona mejor para servicios continuos y bien definidos (SEO, gestión de redes). El precio por proyecto funciona mejor para trabajos puntuales con scope variable. Los datos del sector apuntan a que el modelo híbrido — 60-70% retainer, 30-40% proyectos — ofrece el mejor equilibrio entre predecibilidad y flexibilidad."},{"q":"¿Cómo puedo saber qué proyectos son más rentables en mi agencia?","a":"Calculando el margen bruto real de tus últimos 10-15 proyectos: (ingresos – coste directo total) / ingresos × 100. El patrón que emerge casi siempre es el mismo: 2-3 tipos de proyecto concentran el 80% del margen. Esa información es la base de cualquier decisión estratégica de portfolio de servicios."},{"q":"¿Qué es el pricing basado en valor y cuándo aplicarlo?","a":"Es un modelo en el que el precio se fija en función del valor que el trabajo genera para el cliente, no del tiempo invertido. Tiene sentido cuando la agencia tiene datos de resultados previos y track record demostrable que justifique el precio. Sin esas condiciones, es difícil de sostener en la negociación."}]},{"id":"b4b591d3-1cc3-43db-8200-cb79465adb5b","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Empieza a medir hoy","anchorId":"cta-final"},{"id":"83649a77-f7b2-4af7-b1f5-cd0e168f91bf","type":"paragraph","html":"No esperes a que el Excel te avise de que no queda margen. La rentabilidad se construye decisión a decisión."},{"id":"2d396c2a-647d-44b7-ba45-59f72fe0b45f","type":"cta","text":"Ver herramientas de rentabilidad","href":"/planificador-recursos","variant":"primary"},{"id":"9086ed7d-7d89-4906-bc7c-69a1487a86d6","type":"relatedPost","slug":"planificacion-proyectos-cronograma-recursos"}]'::jsonb,
  blocks_en = '[{"id":"c4cf3f26-c854-4b1f-afeb-259702e94e24","type":"callout","tone":"highlight","html":"<strong>TL;DR — The essentials in 3 points</strong><br/>Selling hours has a natural ceiling: there are only so many hours in a day per person. Agencies that gain margin without inflating headcount have usually changed **what they sell**, not how much they sweat.<br/>The **gross margin per project** is the metric that separates those who bill a lot from those who keep the money. Doing this exercise with your last ten projects is usually both uncomfortable and useful.<br/>Scope creep isn''t just ''difficult clients'': it''s a lack of a container. A three-step protocol —record, quantify, communicate— can be set in motion without waiting for the next quarter."},{"id":"0c165839-7f73-45f5-bf75-4622e5e31f83","type":"paragraph","html":"If you''ve already read why <LocaleLink>being busy doesn''t mean being profitable</LocaleLink>, the next step is truly uncomfortable: looking at projects one by one and asking yourself if the price made sense with the real cost —not with the cost you''d like to believe."},{"id":"b7324725-ac9b-4aa0-9256-c66d7fc56864","type":"paragraph","html":"Here you will find <strong>pricing models with pros and cons</strong>, a margin calculation you can take to a spreadsheet without philosophy, a scope protocol that avoids working for free by omission, and a way to frame work in short cycles so that time stops being a river without banks."},{"id":"d3e2fcb2-01e0-445c-a642-2d749f07e69f","type":"toc"},{"id":"858d85fe-159c-4cd4-95bf-587a34da91a0","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"1. Why selling hours has a ceiling and how to break it","anchorId":"techo-horas"},{"id":"cd048c15-bacf-42d4-95e0-dc594eeb2dd5","type":"paragraph","html":"When price is tied to time, <strong>efficiency penalizes itself</strong>: if the team does in two hours what used to take four, you bill half for the same result. This perverse incentive explains why many agencies get trapped in a race for more hours or more heads."},{"id":"c02befc3-61f2-44fd-8a6b-47dccf5c28a9","type":"paragraph","html":"You''ll find it in the ''good news'': the team improves the process, reduces times, and yet the month doesn''t deliver because billing also drops. It''s the ceiling speaking clearly, not you losing motivation."},{"id":"2a914d50-f689-4dce-8119-fa433bafa83e","type":"paragraph","html":"In addition, the hourly price is easy to compare between providers; the price tied to a <strong>result with defined scope</strong> is not so much. That changes the conversation —if you have the authority and data to sustain it."},{"id":"ecdf716b-bc32-4f91-a2d7-51e452b3ce79","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Value-based pricing: when it''s realistic"},{"id":"f9bd750a-7e4f-44c9-ac6d-7e6fd2b44dbe","type":"paragraph","html":"Decoupling price from time and moving it closer to the impact for the client can increase margin without increasing headcount. It works if you have data from previous results and a proven track record; without that, it''s a difficult negotiation to win. In the end, it''s about selling the solution to the problem, not the time it takes to type it up."},{"id":"aff3b55f-047c-4042-85e4-6fa4ee8bc9d5","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"2. Pricing models: pros, cons, and the hybrid model","anchorId":"modelos-pricing"},{"id":"c3438978-a922-48bc-85fe-b921918ce7c8","type":"paragraph","html":"There is no perfect model, but there are models that attract the problems you don''t want. The typical scar is the fee that seems stable until the client asks for ''a little favor'' every three days and the margin disappears."},{"id":"c6352485-fd5a-4e8b-b671-e820e95b2d0e","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Hourly price / Time & Materials"},{"id":"b1a77707-ee0f-44a9-ae9d-d9a322b245a7","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>Pros:</strong> Certainty of collection for every minute invested."},{"id":"8e594f00-3c8e-46c2-a43c-0ea2ec87e787","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>Contras:</strong> Penalizes efficiency and makes it difficult for the client to forecast income."},{"id":"a49cb3cb-f5f8-4e8a-9bbb-ce0c8b029c51","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Fixed price per project"},{"id":"8b53ddb7-a0e7-4a58-8bb3-00d84144bc17","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>Pros:</strong> Total clarity for the client and a reward for speed if you have smooth processes."},{"id":"6c5a9d0e-429b-4ddb-865c-86cad13d79c9","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>Contras:</strong> The agency assumes all the risk of deviation (scope creep)."},{"id":"c58ec6e3-8f76-47fe-82f6-54f3fd29e196","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Monthly retainer (Recurring Fee)"},{"id":"98545999-7d30-44da-a3bb-a26220432ac9","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>Pros:</strong> Cash flow predictability and long-term relationship."},{"id":"40959873-6c98-4491-a782-f77f2c9d0fe4","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>Contras:</strong> Tendency towards client ''comfort'' (asking for too much) and agency ''relaxation'' (measuring too little)."},{"id":"56b90df3-b021-455d-98b0-a333c50119fc","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"The hybrid model: the best of both worlds"},{"id":"d827549c-3059-4ec7-b3e5-5ea767645e3d","type":"paragraph","html":"Most profitable agencies use a mix: a **base fee** for maintenance and **fixed projects** for new initiatives or peaks in work. This ensures an income floor and protects the margin from extras."},{"id":"602cfb78-d57f-4de8-885e-ec6873cb364f","type":"visualRef","visualId":"OcupacionVsRentabilidadChart"},{"id":"863ed224-12b4-474d-bcfd-1e17e9c7ace6","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"3. How to calculate real gross margin per project","anchorId":"calcular-rentabilidad"},{"id":"b7e5e8f1-55b6-4114-b0d5-67b517f2adf7","type":"paragraph","html":"Note: the agency''s net margin (what''s left after paying for office, software, and administration) matters, but the battle is won in the **gross margin per project**. If the project alone doesn''t leave room to breathe, the agency has no future."},{"id":"98817398-6a77-4d6f-97f0-5fb8025143ac","type":"callout","tone":"info","html":"<strong>The basic formula</strong><br/>(Project Revenue − Direct Costs) / Revenue × 100<br/>Where **direct cost** includes team hours (at fully loaded cost: salary + social security + extras), freelancers, and specific tools for the assignment."},{"id":"565c02dd-540a-4894-b03a-487460bf3718","type":"callout","tone":"highlight","html":"<strong>Quick references</strong><br/>Healthy: > 50-60%. You have room to cover overhead and grow.<br/>Danger: < 35-40%. The project barely pays for its own execution; you are subsidizing the client with your structure."},{"id":"af46f843-a7da-4476-b0bb-f77ed6a00c60","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"4. The three-step scope protocol","anchorId":"scope-protocolo"},{"id":"4eb7f91f-88be-40ba-945d-d211762ac825","type":"paragraph","html":"Scope creep (growing scope) destroys more margins than bad luck. It isn''t stopped with anger; it''s stopped with a container. The scar is the ''but this was already in'' that they tell you when you try to bill for the fifth revision."},{"id":"2f136af7-66a0-4698-8b5a-c7f9a465c02b","type":"list","ordered":true,"items":["<strong>Record:</strong> nothing is accepted by chat or word of mouth without it entering the management system.","<strong>Quantify:</strong> how many hours is it? what impact does it have on the final date?","<strong>Communicate:</strong> ''This is outside the original scope. We can do it by adding X to the budget or removing Y from the current queue.'' The client chooses, you don''t lose."]},{"id":"1c34f4c7-4b04-4fca-8eee-a23f07e42aaf","type":"visualRef","visualId":"ScopeProtocoloInfographic"},{"id":"a0829e10-eae3-47bf-b6de-5b2de23b9f00","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"5. The sprint model: from infinite fee to closed cycles","anchorId":"modelo-sprint"},{"id":"9556bfb1-02c7-41e1-92af-f051f4f20e9c","type":"paragraph","html":"Working by sprints (1 or 2 week cycles) helps time not to dilate. Instead of a three-month project that gets deformed, you have six two-week deliveries with fixed objectives. You notice it when the team stops asking ''when does this end?'' and starts saying ''this goes into the next sprint''."},{"id":"0f4deaf3-f15c-4d16-8fb2-4930a710661b","type":"paragraph","html":"If you want to connect the calendar with your people''s real capacity, the <LocaleLink>team resource planning</LocaleLink> tells you how to join dates and heads without anyone exploding. And to know if the pace is right, <LocaleLink>project pacing</LocaleLink> gives you the pulse in real time."},{"id":"f9a6d361-2811-446b-b076-ef933a0ef2db","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Frequently Asked Questions","anchorId":"preguntas-frecuentes"},{"id":"83eaab8e-66e3-459a-bb94-04e469c4d49e","type":"faq","items":[{"q":"What gross margin should a marketing agency have?","a":"The standard reference in service agencies sets a healthy gross margin above 50% per project. Below 40%, the project hardly covers indirect costs and overhead sustainably. Gross margin is calculated as (revenue – direct cost) / revenue × 100."},{"q":"How is extra work outside the scope charged in an agency?","a":"The most effective process has three steps: log the request at the moment, estimate the time before accepting, and communicate the impact to the client before executing. The question that changes the conversation is: ''Do we add it by adjusting the budget, or leave it for the next sprint?''"},{"q":"What is better for an agency: retainer or price per project?","a":"It depends on the type of service. Retainers work best for continuous and well-defined services (SEO, social media management). Per-project pricing works better for one-off jobs with variable scope. Industry data suggests that the hybrid model — 60-70% retainer, 30-40% projects — offers the best balance between predictability and flexibility."},{"q":"How can I know which projects are most profitable in my agency?","a":"By calculating the real gross margin of your last 10-15 projects: (revenue – total direct cost) / revenue × 100. The pattern that almost always emerges is the same: 2-3 types of projects concentrate 80% of the margin. This information is the basis for any strategic service portfolio decision."},{"q":"What is value-based pricing and when to apply it?","a":"It is a model where the price is set based on the value the work generates for the client, not the time invested. It makes sense when the agency has data from previous results and a demonstrable track record that justifies the price. Without those conditions, it is difficult to sustain in negotiation."}]},{"id":"5bb16f90-70af-475e-89cd-c74f0015b407","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Start measuring today","anchorId":"cta-final"},{"id":"cc81aac4-55f7-4bc0-b01e-7abea4e0f911","type":"paragraph","html":"Don''t wait for Excel to warn you that there''s no margin left. Profitability is built decision by decision."},{"id":"d2efb6c3-f38a-448c-96dc-dc73260dee66","type":"cta","text":"View profitability tools","href":"/planificador-recursos","variant":"primary"},{"id":"9bd609cf-5239-4f7b-968b-1889039c3209","type":"relatedPost","slug":"planificacion-proyectos-cronograma-recursos"}]'::jsonb,
  json_ld_es = '{"@context":"https://schema.org","@graph":[{"@type":"Article","headline":"Cómo medir la rentabilidad real por proyecto en tu agencia (y dejar de vender horas)","description":"De vender tiempo a vender valor: cómo calcular el margen real por proyecto, comparar modelos de pricing y proteger tus beneficios frente al scope creep.","author":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"publisher":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"datePublished":"2026-03-26","inLanguage":"es","mainEntityOfPage":{"@type":"WebPage","@id":"https://taimbox.com/blog/como-medir-rentabilidad-proyecto-agencia-dejar-vender-horas"}},{"@type":"FAQPage","mainEntity":[{"@type":"Question","name":"¿Qué margen bruto debe tener una agencia de marketing?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"La referencia habitual en agencias de servicios sitúa un margen bruto saludable por encima del 50% por proyecto. Por debajo del 40%, el proyecto difícilmente cubre costes indirectos y overhead de forma sostenible. El margen bruto se calcula como (ingresos – coste directo) / ingresos × 100."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"¿Cómo se cobra el trabajo extra fuera del alcance en una agencia?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"El proceso más efectivo tiene tres pasos: registrar la solicitud en el momento, estimar el tiempo antes de aceptar, y comunicar el impacto al cliente antes de ejecutar. La pregunta que cambia la conversación es: ''¿Lo añadimos ajustando el presupuesto, o lo dejamos para el próximo sprint?''"}},{"@type":"Question","name":"¿Qué es mejor para una agencia: retainer o precio por proyecto?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Depende del tipo de servicio. El retainer funciona mejor para servicios continuos y bien definidos (SEO, gestión de redes). El precio por proyecto funciona mejor para trabajos puntuales con scope variable. Los datos del sector apuntan a que el modelo híbrido — 60-70% retainer, 30-40% proyectos — ofrece el mejor equilibrio entre predecibilidad y flexibilidad."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"¿Cómo puedo saber qué proyectos son más rentables en mi agencia?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Calculando el margen bruto real de tus últimos 10-15 proyectos: (ingresos – coste directo total) / ingresos × 100. El patrón que emerge casi siempre es el mismo: 2-3 tipos de proyecto concentran el 80% del margen. Esa información es la base de cualquier decisión estratégica de portfolio de servicios."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"¿Qué es el pricing basado en valor y cuándo aplicarlo?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Es un modelo en el que el precio se fija en función del valor que el trabajo genera para el cliente, no del tiempo invertido. Tiene sentido cuando la agencia tiene datos de resultados previos y track record demostrable que justifique el precio. Sin esas condiciones, es difícil de sostener en la negociación."}}]},{"@type":"SoftwareApplication","name":"Taimbox","applicationCategory":"BusinessApplication","description":"Planificador de recursos y tiempo para agencias. Timeboxing, cronograma por horas y reportes de rentabilidad."}]}'::jsonb,
  json_ld_en = '{"@context":"https://schema.org","@graph":[{"@type":"Article","headline":"How to measure the real profitability per project in your agency (and stop selling hours)","description":"From selling time to selling value: how to calculate the real margin per project, compare pricing models and protect your profits against scope creep.","author":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"publisher":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"datePublished":"2026-03-26","inLanguage":"en","mainEntityOfPage":{"@type":"WebPage","@id":"https://taimbox.com/en/blog/measure-project-profitability-stop-selling-hours"}},{"@type":"FAQPage","mainEntity":[{"@type":"Question","name":"What gross margin should a marketing agency have?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"The standard reference in service agencies sets a healthy gross margin above 50% per project. Below 40%, the project hardly covers indirect costs and overhead sustainably. Gross margin is calculated as (revenue – direct cost) / revenue × 100."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"How is extra work outside the scope charged in an agency?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"The most effective process has three steps: log the request at the moment, estimate the time before accepting, and communicate the impact to the client before executing. The question that changes the conversation is: ''Do we add it by adjusting the budget, or leave it for the next sprint?''"}},{"@type":"Question","name":"What is better for an agency: retainer or price per project?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"It depends on the type of service. Retainers work best for continuous and well-defined services (SEO, social media management). Per-project pricing works better for one-off jobs with variable scope. Industry data suggests that the hybrid model — 60-70% retainer, 30-40% projects — offers the best balance between predictability and flexibility."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"How can I know which projects are most profitable in my agency?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"By calculating the real gross margin of your last 10-15 projects: (revenue – total direct cost) / revenue × 100. The pattern that almost always emerges is the same: 2-3 types of projects concentrate 80% of the margin. This information is the basis for any strategic service portfolio decision."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"What is value-based pricing and when to apply it?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"It is a model where the price is set based on the value the work generates for the client, not the time invested. It makes sense when the agency has data from previous results and a demonstrable track record that justifies the price. Without those conditions, it is difficult to sustain in negotiation."}}]},{"@type":"SoftwareApplication","name":"Taimbox","applicationCategory":"BusinessApplication","description":"Agency resource and time planner. Timeboxing, hourly schedule, and profitability reports."}]}'::jsonb
WHERE slug = 'como-medir-rentabilidad-proyecto-agencia-dejar-vender-horas';

-- por-que-tu-agencia-pierde-rentabilidad-equipo-ocupado
UPDATE public.blog_posts SET
  blocks_es = '[{"id":"f39bd92e-c9f5-4fa4-9cd6-c1319624c037","type":"callout","tone":"highlight","html":"<strong>TL;DR — Lo esencial en 3 puntos</strong><br/>Tener el equipo al 100% de ocupación no significa ser más rentable — por encima del 80%, cada hora extra genera costes ocultos que erosionan el margen más rápido de lo que crece el ingreso.<br/>El context switching puede acercarse al 40% de la capacidad productiva real en algunos entornos. En una agencia con 5 personas, eso equivale a pagar 2 sueldos que no generan valor facturable.<br/>La rentabilidad de una agencia no se construye trabajando más horas — se construye controlando qué tipo de trabajo ocupa cada hora y eliminando los agujeros que nadie ve en el P&L."},{"id":"4b7e4558-761a-4a19-98f6-d51b90cbe3e7","type":"paragraph","html":"El tablero de proyectos siempre tiene algo en curso. Los clientes firman con un «todo bien». El equipo llega antes y sale después. Y aun así, a final de mes, el margen no cuadra con el esfuerzo que ves en la sala o en el chat."},{"id":"fed3f785-ffa0-4dc8-8747-6a02e9475d18","type":"paragraph","html":"No estás loco:<strong>estar ocupado y ser rentable son dos cosas distintas</strong>. Confundirlas es el error más frecuente —y más caro— en la gestión de agencias de servicios. Abajo vas a ver por qué la utilización alta puede destruir margen, qué papel juega el cambio de contexto, cómo el «siempre disponible» digital te cuesta foco, dónde se van las horas que no facturas y qué métricas mirar antes de tomar otra decisión a ciegas."},{"id":"7b956c0b-0544-4448-9416-d7af48d0e9aa","type":"toc"},{"id":"592adcd4-572a-4e12-b88f-f2e3bb86772b","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"1. La trampa de la ocupación: por qué el 100% de utilización destruye márgenes","anchorId":"trampa-ocupacion"},{"id":"19c4d67f-8f94-4c0e-8cdc-b06cbf0b9f03","type":"paragraph","html":"Te tienta pensar que si todo el mundo está a tope, la agencia gana más. El problema es que<strong>sin holgura no hay reacción</strong>: un imprevisto deja de ser una excepción y pasa a ser la norma financiada con horas que no estaban en ningún presupuesto."},{"id":"60809688-9144-46f8-828f-754979d664ab","type":"paragraph","html":"El viernes a las 19:45 tu diseñadora senior no dice “no puedo”. Solo deja de mandar GIFs por Slack, responde con un “ok” seco y, cuando por fin suena el canal, ya ha saltado el retraso al siguiente entregable. Ese retraso no es drama; es margen que se evapora."},{"id":"94b820b7-988c-4905-903e-018d0476adb4","type":"paragraph","html":"Piensa en una agencia de quince personas con cuentas estables: si la utilización media se va al 92% tres meses seguidos, no estás viendo «más compromiso»; estás viendo<strong>un sistema sin colchón</strong>. Cualquier campaña que se mueve, cualquier baja médica o cualquier error de estimación se paga con margen o con calidad —y a veces con las dos."},{"id":"f125a34f-c03a-4dbd-9216-41b34aa8542d","type":"paragraph","html":"La<strong>tasa de utilización</strong>—en la forma más útil para dirección— suele expresarse como:<em>horas facturables trabajadas / horas totales disponibles × 100</em>. Ojo: «facturables» no es lo mismo que «ocupadas»: puedes estar en reuniones internas, formación o herramientas y seguir «ocupado» sin que eso entre en una factura."},{"id":"95dc35e6-f58e-4641-bf42-9c986afe22d4","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Qué es la tasa de utilización y cuál es el rango saludable"},{"id":"9d74fab7-1ddb-4466-b3f4-631a23d72310","type":"paragraph","html":"En la práctica, la referencia habitual del sector sitúa el rango óptimo<strong>entre el 70% y el 80%</strong>para muchos perfiles productivos en agencias de servicios. Por debajo hay capacidad ociosa; por encima, el sistema suele empezar a pagar facturas invisibles: errores, retrabajo y presión sostenida."},{"id":"b075254d-5a0f-48e1-8b84-4b4996f86dac","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Qué pasa cuando se supera ese umbral"},{"id":"528bb28a-43ce-4735-bbd4-ca25b0260761","type":"list","ordered":false,"items":["Cada imprevisto genera<strong>horas extra no planificadas</strong>: el coste es real aunque no tenga línea propia en el Excel del proyecto.","La calidad baja bajo presión sostenida y aparece el<strong>retrabajo</strong>—otra vez coste real, otra vez invisible en el presupuesto original.","El agotamiento acumulado empuja la<strong>rotación</strong>. Y la rotación, en euros, es brutal."]},{"id":"92bcec7d-7bee-4cdc-986b-385e247d6314","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"El coste real de la rotación que nadie incluye en el P&L"},{"id":"705f5d4a-9447-483e-a54e-f5dfc203e3fc","type":"paragraph","html":"Según estudios de<strong>SHRM</strong>(Society for Human Resource Management), sustituir a un empleado puede costar<strong>entre el 50% y el 200% de su salario anual</strong>, según el perfil. Para alguien con un coste anual en torno a 30.000€, hablamos de un rango amplísimo: de 15.000€ a 60.000€ por baja, antes de contar el tiempo en el que el puesto no rinde al 100%."},{"id":"4e6b1fe5-bb4d-42a6-942b-7b1573b5c321","type":"paragraph","html":"Pregunta incómoda:<em>¿cuántas bajas ha tenido tu agencia este año? ¿Ese coste aparece en algún dashboard?</em>"},{"id":"a1b1e224-1c73-4ee7-badb-2fecc6e499d8","type":"paragraph","html":"Fíjate en la zona roja del gráfico:<strong>ese desplome es el coste de perder a tu mejor creativo</strong>porque le obligaste a vivir en el cuadrante de urgencia permanente. No es un número abstracto: es la factura de alguien que ya no puede sostener el ritmo y el margen se va antes que el Excel te avise."},{"id":"0d33a31a-bb8b-43c1-84e1-9d72aa7382cf","type":"paragraph","html":"Cuando la curva vuelve a hundirse a la derecha, no suele ser porque el trabajo sea “malo”: es porque el sistema no deja hueco para pensar con cabeza —y ahí empieza el retrabajo que nadie presupuestó."},{"id":"45fdb019-040b-4b1c-aee3-2bd7c8f7aa05","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"2. El coste invisible que más dinero destruye: el context switching","anchorId":"context-switching"},{"id":"1ee1c74f-a2dc-40e5-8e5b-c26e486dbb1c","type":"paragraph","html":"El<strong>context switching</strong>es el salto mental entre tareas o proyectos que no comparten el mismo marco. No es «hacer varias cosas a la vez»: es<strong>dejar una cabeza puesta y tener que volver a engancharla</strong>en otra. En agencia, el daño se multiplica: el mismo perfil arrastra varios briefs a la vez, con tonos de marca distintos, ritmos distintos y urgencias distintas."},{"id":"abdd5828-b2aa-4dd9-bfa9-d477079a5483","type":"paragraph","html":"Te pasa así: estás cerrando un layout y te entra un “¿me lo pasas en 20 minutos?” de otro cliente. No hay ticket, no hay contexto, y cuando vuelves a tu tarea original ya no es la misma mañana."},{"id":"fe02ada7-0225-4929-9f04-84204663bc3e","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Los datos que hay detrás"},{"id":"2bff9ad7-b6fb-4b25-9e17-2072db458102","type":"list","ordered":false,"items":["Investigaciones de la<strong>Universidad de California en Irvine</strong>(Gloria Mark y equipo) sitúan en torno a<strong>23–25 minutos</strong>el tiempo medio para recuperar el foco profundo tras una interrupción relevante. No es un detalle de productividad personal: es un dato de economía de la atención.","En síntesis de estudios sobre productividad cognitiva en equipos de conocimiento, la dispersión puede consumir<strong>una fracción muy alta</strong>del tiempo disponible —en el orden de lo que muchos equipos resumen como «casi la mitad del día en cambios de tarea».","Traducción a euros (ejemplo hipotético, para orden de magnitud): si alguien con un coste cargado de 50.000€ al año pierde una parte grande de su capacidad por dispersión,<strong>no estás perdiendo «un poco de foco»</strong>: estás financiando capacidad que no se factura."]},{"id":"dab16473-5025-482a-bf14-cf6d200e8697","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"El ejercicio de los 30 segundos"},{"id":"cecaad10-5f20-45a5-ae0e-65b1f60ec935","type":"paragraph","html":"Piensa en una persona de tu equipo: cuántos proyectos lleva abiertos a la vez, cuántas interrupciones de cliente o internas recibe al día, y qué pasa si multiplicas eso por semanas. No hace falta una hoja perfecta:<strong>el ejercicio mental ya duele lo suficiente</strong>como para tomar decisiones."},{"id":"03aef6c1-f271-4964-9ace-f1e60c5c4272","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Las interrupciones que nadie registra"},{"id":"146f7cb5-f33f-4e2f-b43d-f96118e0c219","type":"paragraph","html":"Ninguna de esas líneas aparece como partida en el presupuesto del cliente; todas compiten por la misma atención que debería ir a entregar valor cobrable. Por eso el problema no es «la gente mira el móvil»: es que el modelo de trabajo<strong>premia la reactividad</strong>y encarece el trabajo bueno."},{"id":"0cc53d83-6318-4909-9ebc-33fe991e1acc","type":"list","ordered":false,"items":["Mensajes del cliente en canales donde la respuesta se interpreta como urgencia.","Correos entre reuniones que rompen el bloque de trabajo profundo.","Cambios de prioridad de última hora sin ticket ni registro.","Petición verbal «rápida» que no entra en ninguna estimación."]},{"id":"b5077c16-227b-4277-bca0-6b520f17b27f","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"3. La cultura que lo genera: el presencialismo digital","anchorId":"presencialismo-digital"},{"id":"7e570216-e21b-4117-beef-bdc9b76a37e2","type":"paragraph","html":"El presencialismo clásico —estar en la oficina aunque no rindas— ha mutado: ahora es el<strong>«siempre en línea»</strong>, el verde perpetuo, el correo abierto y la sensación de que responder tarde es fallar. El resultado es el mismo:<strong>la apariencia de disponibilidad sustituye a la entrega de valor medible</strong>."},{"id":"f96696ba-5137-4dd2-8597-75a02d38ed78","type":"paragraph","html":"Lo ves en el chat: el canal tiene a todo el mundo “en verde” y aun así nadie termina una entrega. En una reunión de feedback, los comentarios suenan a prisa, no a criterio: “solo un ajuste rápido” acaba siendo un retrabajo que no cabía en el plan."},{"id":"043759ab-35f7-4136-8a8b-e3358279df34","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Cómo se refuerza sin malicia"},{"id":"dda5fc90-00da-47ef-a065-388466841163","type":"paragraph","html":"La mayoría de mandos no lo hacen a propósito. Suele bastar con una combinación de hábitos que parecen inocuos:"},{"id":"c64c058f-438e-4768-9401-361668ecb9fd","type":"list","ordered":false,"items":["Mensajes fuera de horario que «no exigen» respuesta, pero generan presión implícita.","Responder al cliente en canales visibles para el equipo y normalizar la disponibilidad total.","Elogiar la rapidez de respuesta por encima de la calidad del entregable o del criterio."]},{"id":"af0a1f85-151f-4d72-b76d-37909d045a20","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Tres cambios de liderazgo (sin comprar nada)"},{"id":"29aa839e-4fe0-469f-aa39-c28aaa78ad26","type":"list","ordered":false,"items":["Definir canales síncronos y asíncronos —y respetar la regla desde arriba.","Proteger bloques de no interrupciones en el calendario del equipo.","Medir reconocimiento por resultados, no por horas de presencia digital."]},{"id":"5e707a26-09c7-4c92-8176-5cd5840624d9","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"4. Las horas no facturables: el agujero negro de los márgenes","anchorId":"horas-no-facturables"},{"id":"4031e747-5c5f-49ba-89bc-6c2dee644178","type":"paragraph","html":"Las<strong>horas no facturables</strong>son las que trabajas pero no metes en ninguna factura. Muchas agencias las conocen en teoría; pocas las miden con rigor, así que tampoco las presupuestan bien. El resultado es un P&L que parece «razonable» hasta que empiezas a sumar lo que no se cobró."},{"id":"5b11a511-c149-4874-b80a-9fdc00821604","type":"paragraph","html":"En agencias de servicios creativos, según referencias del sector, esas horas pueden representar<strong>entre el 30% y el 50%</strong>del total trabajado. Si tu ratio cae por debajo de ciertos umbrales, el problema deja de ser «un mes malo» y pasa a ser estructural."},{"id":"6b7ef667-d258-4087-912f-3f8d3d6083a4","type":"paragraph","html":"Mira tu calendario: hay un bloque “alineación” de 45 minutos que nadie llama por su nombre de entregable, pero todos salen con acciones nuevas. Eso, sumado, es tiempo que no se vende y que acaba comiéndose el margen del proyecto."},{"id":"95222004-0155-4160-864c-8cb5d2d9c024","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Categorías que más suelen pesar"},{"id":"3f4e0895-3847-4dee-ac65-e7cdb5aba400","type":"paragraph","html":"Si quieres ordenar<strong>quién hace qué y con qué calendario</strong>, la guía deplanificación de recursos del equipoconecta cronograma, presupuesto y capacidad sin tratarlo como tres mundos distintos. Y te ayuda a que no se te escapen dos sombras típicas: la gestión de herramientas (subir archivos, permisos, estados) y la comunicación fuera de alcance que entra por el chat."},{"id":"fd84a8d5-5303-4814-90f6-9d325e1f3daf","type":"list","ordered":false,"items":["Reuniones internas de coordinación sin entregable claro — media hora que no estaba en el presupuesto.","Correcciones por briefing flojo o incompleto — se rehace, no se avanza.","Preventas que no se cierran — cada “te lo paso luego” es coste sin retorno."]},{"id":"161b81fd-ba09-4a27-8fd6-7cf3a2daaf5a","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Cómo calcular el ratio de horas facturables"},{"id":"8eb38477-9781-432e-b0a2-7a04a91af6a1","type":"paragraph","html":"Fórmula aplicable:<em>(horas facturadas al cliente en el último mes / horas totales trabajadas en el último mes) × 100</em>. Referencias habituales: por encima del<strong>65%</strong>suele ser un terreno «normal»; entre 50% y 65% hay margen de mejora; por debajo del<strong>50%</strong>conviene asumir que el problema es sistémico, no puntual."},{"id":"f243f117-db27-423e-a4cf-cac4ecf21727","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"5. El scope creep silencioso: cómo los proyectos se comen su propio margen","anchorId":"scope-creep"},{"id":"92621e6f-4a69-46fb-9fed-d9f171667f1f","type":"paragraph","html":"El<strong>scope creep</strong>es el alcance que crece sin ajuste de presupuesto. En agencias es casi una constante: la relación continúa, entra petición tras petición y el miedo a «romper el clima» hace que muchas cosas se asuman gratis."},{"id":"4d9965be-c1a7-4325-a062-8146f4c62d41","type":"paragraph","html":"El momento es casi siempre el mismo: el cliente suelta “solo un cambio pequeño” a media tarde. Parece inofensivo… hasta que esa frase termina en nuevas revisiones, reestimaciones y otra vuelta de feedback que ya no cabía en el margen."},{"id":"af06f166-7ceb-4500-a8fd-80e6c41e72e6","type":"paragraph","html":"Si el trabajo no tiene<strong>contenedor temporal</strong>claro, tiende a expandirse: aquí encaja laLey de Parkinson y los plazos de los proyectos—sin topes, el esfuerzo llena el hueco disponible y el margen desaparece en «pulir detalles»."},{"id":"bc2f4576-26ad-4ce1-ae98-902a46dd8c5b","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Cómo cuantificarlo sin complicarte la vida"},{"id":"e61c7d05-523b-496b-9541-bab7bee5fd48","type":"paragraph","html":"Compara horas presupuestadas frente a horas reales en tus últimos diez proyectos. Si la desviación media supera el<strong>20–30%</strong>, el alcance se está moviendo de forma sistemática —no por un mal mes, sino por un patrón."},{"id":"544bc492-e47b-4e41-91f7-99dccae36653","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Por qué es síntoma, no «mala suerte»"},{"id":"2a8704a3-368b-465c-af75-f0e8593cc7cf","type":"paragraph","html":"El problema rara vez es «el cliente es imposible». Lo habitual es que no existan límites claros ni un sitio donde quede registrado qué entra y qué no. La solución es de<strong>proceso y conversación</strong>, no de heroísmo individual."},{"id":"edd669fc-511f-4dea-81ef-cfa5c178286f","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"6. Las métricas que sí predicen si tu agencia es rentable","anchorId":"metricas-prediccion"},{"id":"5c4d562f-2850-4d1c-a9ce-9d375daf0aad","type":"paragraph","html":"La facturación puede subir y el beneficio quedarse plano: sin margen por proyecto, solo estás moviendo volumen. La tabla siguiente es una brújula mensual; si quieres profundizar en el detalle operativo, losKPIs de rendimiento para agencias de marketingdesarrollan cada ratio con ejemplos. Para pasar del diagnóstico a números por encargo, también tiene sentido leercómo medir la rentabilidad real por proyecto."},{"id":"f80341ad-36fd-4376-935b-53596a8af74b","type":"paragraph","html":"Te das cuenta en el comité: si la pregunta recurrente es “¿cuántas horas habéis vendido?”, probablemente estás gestionando el síntoma, no la causa. El P&L no negocia; se mueve con margen por proyecto."},{"id":"0b0dc920-27ad-40c3-ab97-1b8b98187979","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"El error más frecuente: medir ingresos en lugar de márgenes"},{"id":"371664eb-0f92-4414-a189-ee784b8258f6","type":"paragraph","html":"Puedes facturar mucho y quedarte con un margen ridículo si los costes directos se han ido comiendo el proyecto. La facturación es vanidad útil para la foto;<strong>el margen por proyecto y por tipo de servicio</strong>es lo que permite decidir qué vender, a qué precio y con qué equipo."},{"id":"5ddbd825-3804-410d-b82f-2f0d2a2bb3ec","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"7. Qué cambiar esta semana para empezar a recuperar margen","anchorId":"que-cambiar-esta-semana"},{"id":"dfd13b73-989e-47b1-acab-9d0ab29d733e","type":"paragraph","html":"El lunes a las 9:00, cuando el equipo aún está con la primera tanda de mensajes, no necesitas un nuevo framework: necesitas romper un hábito. Lo que midas esta semana te dirá dónde se está fugando el margen."},{"id":"f816ab9d-0d16-4cbe-9cc2-8d28cacf3d85","type":"paragraph","html":"Y una verdad incómoda: si el equipo vive al 90–100% de utilización, no hay buffer; solo hay retraso financiado con calidad y margen. Ajusta ese objetivo antes de seguir “ganando ocupación”."},{"id":"d2a8c275-2b29-445f-b4ee-7021c219fa43","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Preguntas frecuentes","anchorId":"preguntas-frecuentes"},{"id":"95bda6b8-767f-4ee6-bea8-3ff66e4d05e6","type":"faq","items":[{"q":"¿Qué tasa de utilización es saludable en una agencia?","a":"La referencia habitual del sector sitúa el rango óptimo entre el 70% y el 80%. Por debajo de ese umbral hay capacidad ociosa; por encima, el equipo empieza a generar costes ocultos por errores, retrabajo y burnout que erosionan el margen más rápido de lo que crece el ingreso."},{"q":"¿Cómo sé si mi agencia está perdiendo rentabilidad por el context switching?","a":"El indicador más directo es comparar las horas estimadas con las reales en tus últimos 10 proyectos. Si la desviación media supera el 20%, el context switching y las interrupciones no planificadas son parte del problema. También puedes preguntar directamente al equipo cuántos proyectos lleva cada persona simultáneamente."},{"q":"¿Cuántas horas no facturables tiene de media una agencia?","a":"Depende mucho del modelo, pero en agencias de servicios creativos las horas no facturables pueden representar entre el 30% y el 50% del total de horas trabajadas. La forma de saberlo en tu caso es calcular el ratio: horas facturadas / horas totales trabajadas × 100."},{"q":"¿Qué diferencia hay entre ocupación y rentabilidad en una agencia?","a":"Ocupación mide el porcentaje de tiempo que el equipo está trabajando. Rentabilidad mide cuánto margen genera ese trabajo. Son variables distintas: un equipo puede estar al 100% de ocupación y tener márgenes negativos si hay mucho retrabajo, horas no facturables o scope creep no controlado."}]},{"id":"a1b31c34-d341-4d8f-9c48-42cb78196960","type":"relatedPost","slug":"kpis-agencias-marketing-2026"}]'::jsonb,
  blocks_en = '[{"id":"ea9feaf9-0c2f-432d-9d54-3fbcd5856e3d","type":"callout","tone":"highlight","html":"<strong>TL;DR — The essentials in 3 points</strong><br/>Running your team at 100% utilisation does not mean being more profitable — above roughly 80%, every extra hour creates hidden costs that erode margin faster than revenue grows.<br/>Context switching can eat up a huge part of real productive capacity — in some environments approaching 40%. In a five‑person agency, that’s like paying two salaries that don’t generate billable value.<br/>Agency profitability is not built by working more hours — it’s built by controlling what kind of work fills each hour and plugging the holes that never show up explicitly in the P&L."},{"id":"ad2f7cd0-3942-47b7-8818-13e3b3de6756","type":"paragraph","html":"The project board is always full. Clients sign off with a “looks good”. The team arrives early and leaves late. And yet, at the end of the month, the margin doesn’t match the effort you see in the room or in the chat."},{"id":"30063eef-e4cc-4f7e-a1c8-58215b54bd4a","type":"paragraph","html":"You’re not crazy:<strong>being busy and being profitable are two different things</strong>. Confusing them is the most common —and most expensive— mistake in agency management. Below you’ll see why high utilisation can destroy margin, the role context switching plays, how the “always available” digital culture drains focus, where non-billable hours go, and which metrics to watch before you make another blind decision."},{"id":"daebf3df-dd0d-4a97-9b59-4f99b8ec5208","type":"toc"},{"id":"48baada2-8f69-4ab8-a9ee-ffed05e993a7","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"1. The utilisation trap: why 100% destroys margins","anchorId":"trampa-ocupacion"},{"id":"528e67ff-4f83-4197-9ba8-53ec09883f96","type":"paragraph","html":"It’s tempting to think that if everyone is maxed out, the agency makes more money. The problem is that<strong>without slack there is no reaction capacity</strong>: a single unexpected event stops being an exception and becomes the norm — funded with hours that were in no budget."},{"id":"dcec57b4-c44b-4c01-89be-45faa78c49ca","type":"paragraph","html":"On Friday at 7:45 p.m. your senior designer doesn’t say “I can’t”. She just stops sending GIFs on Slack, answers with a dry “ok”, and by the time the channel pings again, the delay has already jumped to the next deliverable. That delay isn’t drama; it’s margin evaporating."},{"id":"688aff13-bb4d-4886-9987-3e7f959f173a","type":"paragraph","html":"Think of a 15‑person agency with stable accounts: if average utilisation creeps up to 92% for three months in a row, you’re not seeing “more commitment”; you’re seeing<strong>a system with no buffer</strong>. Any campaign that shifts, any sick leave, any estimation error gets paid for in margin or quality —often both."},{"id":"9d9f3300-1ebc-45a3-8efe-db5b5e4ef06b","type":"paragraph","html":"The<strong>utilisation rate</strong>—in the most useful version for leadership— is usually expressed as:<em>billable hours worked / total available hours × 100</em>. Note: “billable” is not the same as “busy”: you can spend time in internal meetings, training or tool work and stay “busy” without any of that ever hitting an invoice."},{"id":"1de7f531-6d1e-466e-bc7d-e63bc262c0f1","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"What utilisation is and what “healthy” looks like"},{"id":"16f958b0-e448-40ec-97be-14d0853ab148","type":"paragraph","html":"In practice, industry references often place the sweet spot<strong>between 70% and 80%</strong>for many productive roles in service agencies. Below that you have idle capacity; above it, the system starts paying invisible bills: errors, rework and sustained pressure."},{"id":"776add10-4cbc-4025-9e19-a56d99c7117c","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"What happens when you push past that threshold"},{"id":"5ddd88d6-9f15-4c85-b16d-41af8d824560","type":"list","ordered":false,"items":["Every unexpected event generates<strong>unplanned overtime</strong>: the cost is real even if it doesn’t have its own line in the project spreadsheet.","Quality drops under sustained pressure and<strong>rework</strong>appears —again, real cost that never existed in the original budget.","Cumulative exhaustion increases<strong>turnover</strong>. And turnover, in euros, is brutal."]},{"id":"05abf5a1-2c0e-42ae-b530-663da682d404","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"The real cost of turnover nobody books in the P&L"},{"id":"0bb4cb4d-20f4-4c35-a4ab-cb4fb8cdd6a2","type":"paragraph","html":"According to studies by<strong>SHRM</strong>(Society for Human Resource Management), replacing an employee can cost<strong>between 50% and 200% of their annual salary</strong>depending on the role. For someone with a fully‑loaded annual cost around €30,000, you’re looking at a very wide range: from €15,000 to €60,000 per departure, before counting the period when the seat is not performing at 100%."},{"id":"b8656499-4e22-41f2-8a22-54a5bbd43bab","type":"paragraph","html":"Uncomfortable question:<em>how many voluntary leavers has your agency had this year? Does that cost show up clearly in any dashboard?</em>"},{"id":"6fd59275-fba9-480e-ae64-a3e27994d74c","type":"paragraph","html":"Look at the red area in the chart:<strong>that drop is the cost of losing your best creative</strong>because you forced them to live in the quadrant of permanent urgency. It’s not an abstract number: it’s the bill for someone who can no longer sustain the pace, and the margin goes before the spreadsheet warns you."},{"id":"7a68dcb5-47b1-4f8b-9f74-8b2b4d566a65","type":"paragraph","html":"When the curve drops again on the right, it’s rarely because the work is “bad”: it’s because the system leaves no room to think clearly —and that’s where the unbudgeted rework begins."},{"id":"d2f79fdc-a943-4df4-ae93-9d90f71c429b","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"2. The invisible cost that destroys the most money: context switching","anchorId":"context-switching"},{"id":"aa40c59a-d92b-4cd2-b8d8-a820dc748bb6","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>Context switching</strong>is the mental jump between tasks or projects that don’t share the same frame. It’s not “doing several things at once”: it’s<strong>leaving your head in one place and having to plug it back in</strong>somewhere else. In agencies the damage multiplies: the same person drags several briefs at once, with different brand tones, rhythms and urgencies."},{"id":"4c379e12-89a9-4ab0-9047-26080baa2826","type":"paragraph","html":"It happens like this: you’re closing a layout and a “can you send it in 20 minutes?” pings from another client. There’s no ticket, no context, and when you go back to your original task it’s no longer the same morning."},{"id":"50a05e37-2fd7-43b5-9eba-8c1462d31de8","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"The numbers behind it"},{"id":"9e8a0be1-c0cf-4d0e-badd-befe930add08","type":"list","ordered":false,"items":["Research by<strong>the University of California, Irvine</strong>(Gloria Mark and team) puts the average time to regain deep focus after a relevant interruption at around<strong>23–25 minutes</strong>. This isn’t a minor productivity‑hacks detail; it’s core attention‑economy data.","Syntheses of cognitive‑productivity studies in knowledge teams suggest that dispersion can burn through<strong>a very high fraction</strong>of available time — to the point many teams describe it as “almost half the day in task‑switching”.","Translated into euros (hypothetical example, just for magnitude): if someone with a fully‑loaded cost of €50,000 a year loses a big chunk of their capacity to dispersion,<strong>you’re not losing “a bit of focus”</strong>: you’re financing capacity that never gets billed."]},{"id":"b94f4a65-a494-4ca6-9f49-ae570e707aeb","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"The 30‑second exercise"},{"id":"b53b3c34-e2e2-4f42-ad6e-568122c2a669","type":"paragraph","html":"Think of one person on your team: how many active projects they carry at once, how many client or internal interruptions they get each day, and what happens when you multiply that by weeks. You don’t need a perfect spreadsheet:<strong>the mental exercise hurts enough</strong>to trigger decisions."},{"id":"0094cd9b-2ae4-4ac3-b57a-6949fdd837f4","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"The interruptions nobody tracks"},{"id":"e6a9dfc3-aab3-4829-a77e-59b167fc74ab","type":"paragraph","html":"None of these lines shows up as a budget item for the client; all of them compete for the same attention that should be going into billable value. So the problem isn’t “people check their phones”: it’s that the working model<strong>rewards reactivity</strong>and makes good work more expensive."},{"id":"5a21468d-928c-4175-b293-ba7e10bf4b36","type":"list","ordered":false,"items":["Client messages in channels where fast replies are implicitly treated as urgent.","Emails squeezed between meetings that break deep‑work blocks.","Last‑minute priority changes with no ticket or record.","“Quick” verbal requests that never make it into any estimate."]},{"id":"4f71d9d7-0f39-4112-9daa-404c4f970660","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"3. The culture behind it: digital presenteeism","anchorId":"presencialismo-digital"},{"id":"e00b0bd6-9597-4dea-87f3-d719c5b6dbce","type":"paragraph","html":"Classic presenteeism — being in the office even when you’re not performing — has mutated into<strong>“always online”</strong>: permanently green status, inbox open and the feeling that replying late equals failing. The result is the same:<strong>the appearance of availability replaces the delivery of measurable value</strong>."},{"id":"c50c3b71-bda3-4af1-b8eb-5c1feca9330f","type":"paragraph","html":"You see it in chat: everyone is “green” and yet no one finishes a deliverable. In feedback meetings, comments sound rushed, not thoughtful: “just a quick tweak” ends up as a full round of rework that never fit into the plan."},{"id":"8b265c80-8918-4534-b4a9-9d8f4c37d314","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"How it gets reinforced without bad intentions"},{"id":"c5b66481-d1e8-4880-aaa2-03da3b45071e","type":"paragraph","html":"Most managers don’t do it on purpose. It’s usually a mix of habits that look harmless on the surface:"},{"id":"4f76fc5c-5e0f-4cd3-905c-c6a732c91aae","type":"list","ordered":false,"items":["Messages outside working hours that “don’t require” a reply but create implicit pressure.","Replying to clients in channels the whole team sees, normalising total availability.","Praising fast responses over the quality of the deliverable or the thinking behind it."]},{"id":"7b024a29-f6a7-43a3-bb0a-27f31d4c46c0","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Three leadership shifts (without buying anything)"},{"id":"59e2a741-4eb9-4037-a37a-d64cd12b39b7","type":"list","ordered":false,"items":["Define synchronous vs asynchronous channels — and enforce the rule from the top.","Protect interruption‑free blocks in the team’s calendar.","Reward outcomes instead of digital presence time."]},{"id":"2b0377c1-5370-4309-a580-d361cc2250b7","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"4. Non‑billable hours: the black hole of margins","anchorId":"horas-no-facturables"},{"id":"ea78ea88-84da-4530-ae88-acc2feed2e86","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>Non‑billable hours</strong>are the hours you work but never add to an invoice. Many agencies know they exist in theory; few measure them rigorously, so they rarely budget for them properly. The result is a P&L that looks “reasonable” until you start adding up everything that never got billed."},{"id":"32462be1-a47c-4427-9d61-0c2910c6672f","type":"paragraph","html":"In creative and marketing agencies, sector references suggest these hours can represent<strong>between 30% and 50%</strong>of total time worked. If your ratio drops below certain thresholds, the problem stops being “a bad month” and becomes structural."},{"id":"5a9699a3-6328-45b7-a155-4f0b79b6703a","type":"paragraph","html":"Look at your calendar: there’s a 45‑minute “alignment” block nobody names as a deliverable, but everyone leaves with new actions. Added up, that’s time that never gets sold and ends up eating the project’s margin."},{"id":"e9ccc739-0a7d-43bc-9450-b8b5ce41c269","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Categories that usually weigh the most"},{"id":"a7953729-352f-4c98-ab40-67d05114260b","type":"paragraph","html":"If you want to bring order to<strong>who does what and on what timeline</strong>, the guide onteam resource planningconnects schedule, budget and capacity instead of treating them as three separate worlds. It also helps you catch two usual shadows: tool‑management time (uploading files, permissions, statuses) and out‑of‑scope communication that creeps in through chat."},{"id":"69e4b6a4-7325-42c6-a621-d01f3decce83","type":"list","ordered":false,"items":["Internal coordination meetings with no clear deliverable — half an hour that wasn’t in the budget.","Fixes caused by weak or incomplete briefs — you redo work instead of moving forward.","Pre‑sales that never close — every “I’ll send it over later” is cost with no return."]},{"id":"8d6e141b-d8c9-43a5-8b11-4d0de6cf9b52","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"How to calculate your billable‑hours ratio"},{"id":"54bae348-8e70-444b-a0f3-7bad4718c78f","type":"paragraph","html":"Useful formula:<em>(hours billed to clients in the last month / total hours worked in the last month) × 100</em>. As a rough guide: above<strong>65%</strong>you’re usually in “normal” territory; between 50% and 65% there’s room for improvement; below<strong>50%</strong>it’s safer to assume the problem is systemic, not just a bad month."},{"id":"677acff6-6f44-4f8e-af2d-a6eef6e16cc8","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"5. Silent scope creep: how projects eat their own margin","anchorId":"scope-creep"},{"id":"55166463-2c0b-45b5-bd79-d4dc5384d57c","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>Scope creep</strong>is scope expanding without a matching budget adjustment. In agencies it’s almost a constant: the relationship continues, request after request lands, and the fear of “breaking the vibe” makes a lot of things quietly free."},{"id":"f98ddd47-be5c-4427-a202-be5a70685a0c","type":"paragraph","html":"The moment is almost always the same: the client drops a “just a small change” late in the afternoon. It sounds harmless… until that sentence turns into new rounds of review, re‑estimation and another feedback loop that no longer fits in the margin."},{"id":"cac9d0bd-e320-4f42-80a9-f54d7089fc88","type":"paragraph","html":"If the work doesn’t have a clear<strong>time container</strong>, it tends to expand. This is where theParkinson’s Law and project deadlinescomes in: without hard stops, effort fills the available space and margin disappears into “polishing details”."},{"id":"6a860407-35df-48f9-b442-50a70eb2c0eb","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"How to quantify it without over‑engineering"},{"id":"b7ac1463-4947-4836-bc87-aa09b834d5d4","type":"paragraph","html":"Compare estimated vs actual hours across your last ten projects. If average deviation is above<strong>20–30%</strong>, scope is drifting systematically — not because of one bad month but because of a pattern."},{"id":"b588556f-dc04-41c3-9cde-3a9d6acf163a","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Why it’s a symptom, not “bad luck”"},{"id":"27b40b05-fbb7-4c35-9a13-75a7d58a573f","type":"paragraph","html":"The problem is rarely “the client is impossible”. Much more often, there are no clear boundaries and no single place where what’s in‑scope and out‑of‑scope gets recorded. The fix lives in<strong>process and conversation</strong>, not in individual heroics."},{"id":"d6a90666-8278-40b4-9083-946a392abbde","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"6. The metrics that actually predict whether your agency is profitable","anchorId":"metricas-prediccion"},{"id":"8b3eb5b7-2879-4ee2-ba50-f8abef18fbd2","type":"paragraph","html":"Revenue can grow while profit stays flat: without project‑level margin, you’re just moving volume. The table below is a monthly compass; if you want to dig into operational detail, the piece onperformance KPIs for marketing agenciesunpacks each ratio with examples. To move from diagnosis to per‑project numbers, it’s also worth readinghow to measure real project profitability."},{"id":"47881dda-905f-4284-b03c-00af211467cd","type":"paragraph","html":"You’ll notice it in leadership meetings: if the recurring question is “how many hours did we sell?”, you’re probably managing the symptom, not the cause. The P&L doesn’t negotiate; it moves with project‑level margin."},{"id":"9b4c8b3f-e161-4559-8381-c31d3462116c","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"The most common mistake: measuring revenue instead of margin"},{"id":"e126f371-8c8a-4aa8-971c-045b7cd53180","type":"paragraph","html":"You can bill a lot and still end up with ridiculous margins if direct costs eat the project alive. Revenue is useful vanity for the slide; <strong>margin per project and per service type</strong>is what lets you decide what to sell, at what price and with which team."},{"id":"ff7c189f-0812-4afc-a42c-ca16187c67fe","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"7. What to change this week to start recovering margin","anchorId":"que-cambiar-esta-semana"},{"id":"918ea742-5a58-4acf-b6a9-dc2bafa976e1","type":"paragraph","html":"Monday at 9 a.m., when the team is still facing the first wave of messages, you don’t need a new framework; you need to break a habit. What you measure this week will tell you where margin is leaking."},{"id":"3b916e14-11fa-4dab-badd-86c1ab0f118f","type":"paragraph","html":"And an uncomfortable truth: if your team lives at 90–100% utilisation, there is no buffer — only delay funded with quality and margin. Adjust that target before trying to “win more utilisation”."},{"id":"503cb1b4-53cf-44d3-b8dc-2792e46e11ad","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Frequently asked questions","anchorId":"preguntas-frecuentes"},{"id":"104b29a0-6e5e-420e-a7ff-c6618323fe04","type":"faq","items":[{"q":"What utilization rate is healthy in an agency?","a":"The standard industry reference sets the optimal range between 70% and 80%. Below that threshold, there is idle capacity; above it, the team starts generating hidden costs from errors, rework, and burnout that erode the margin faster than revenue grows."},{"q":"How do I know if my agency is losing profitability due to context switching?","a":"The most direct indicator is comparing estimated hours with actual hours in your last 10 projects. If the average deviation exceeds 20%, context switching and unplanned interruptions are part of the problem. You can also directly ask the team how many projects each person handles simultaneously."},{"q":"How many non-billable hours does an average agency have?","a":"It depends a lot on the model, but in creative services agencies, non-billable hours can represent between 30% and 50% of the total hours worked. The way to find out in your case is to calculate the ratio: billed hours / total hours worked × 100."},{"q":"What is the difference between occupancy and profitability in an agency?","a":"Occupancy measures the percentage of time the team is working. Profitability measures how much margin that work generates. They are different variables: a team can be at 100% occupancy and have negative margins if there is a lot of rework, non-billable hours, or uncontrolled scope creep."}]},{"id":"42a4b6f0-c866-4cbb-a651-704ca5ed0468","type":"relatedPost","slug":"kpis-agencias-marketing-2026"}]'::jsonb,
  json_ld_es = '{"@context":"https://schema.org","@graph":[{"@type":"Article","headline":"Por qué tu agencia pierde rentabilidad aunque el equipo esté siempre ocupado","description":"Analizamos por qué tu agencia pierde rentabilidad.","author":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"publisher":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"datePublished":"2026-03-26","inLanguage":"es","mainEntityOfPage":{"@type":"WebPage","@id":"https://taimbox.com/blog/por-que-tu-agencia-pierde-rentabilidad-equipo-ocupado"}},{"@type":"FAQPage","mainEntity":[{"@type":"Question","name":"¿Qué tasa de utilización es saludable en una agencia?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"La referencia habitual del sector sitúa el rango óptimo entre el 70% y el 80%. Por debajo de ese umbral hay capacidad ociosa; por encima, el equipo empieza a generar costes ocultos por errores, retrabajo y burnout que erosionan el margen más rápido de lo que crece el ingreso."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"¿Cómo sé si mi agencia está perdiendo rentabilidad por el context switching?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"El indicador más directo es comparar las horas estimadas con las reales en tus últimos 10 proyectos. Si la desviación media supera el 20%, el context switching y las interrupciones no planificadas son parte del problema. También puedes preguntar directamente al equipo cuántos proyectos lleva cada persona simultáneamente."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"¿Cuántas horas no facturables tiene de media una agencia?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Depende mucho del modelo, pero en agencias de servicios creativos las horas no facturables pueden representar entre el 30% y el 50% del total de horas trabajadas. La forma de saberlo en tu caso es calcular el ratio: horas facturadas / horas totales trabajadas × 100."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"¿Qué diferencia hay entre ocupación y rentabilidad en una agencia?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Ocupación mide el porcentaje de tiempo que el equipo está trabajando. Rentabilidad mide cuánto margen genera ese trabajo. Son variables distintas: un equipo puede estar al 100% de ocupación y tener márgenes negativos si hay mucho retrabajo, horas no facturables o scope creep no controlado."}}]}]}'::jsonb,
  json_ld_en = '{"@context":"https://schema.org","@graph":[{"@type":"Article","headline":"Why your agency loses profitability even when the team is always busy","description":"We analyze why your agency loses profitability.","author":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"publisher":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"datePublished":"2026-03-26","inLanguage":"en","mainEntityOfPage":{"@type":"WebPage","@id":"https://taimbox.com/en/blog/why-agency-loses-profitability-busy-team"}},{"@type":"FAQPage","mainEntity":[{"@type":"Question","name":"What utilization rate is healthy in an agency?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"The standard industry reference sets the optimal range between 70% and 80%. Below that threshold, there is idle capacity; above it, the team starts generating hidden costs from errors, rework, and burnout that erode the margin faster than revenue grows."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"How do I know if my agency is losing profitability due to context switching?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"The most direct indicator is comparing estimated hours with actual hours in your last 10 projects. If the average deviation exceeds 20%, context switching and unplanned interruptions are part of the problem. You can also directly ask the team how many projects each person handles simultaneously."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"How many non-billable hours does an average agency have?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"It depends a lot on the model, but in creative services agencies, non-billable hours can represent between 30% and 50% of the total hours worked. The way to find out in your case is to calculate the ratio: billed hours / total hours worked × 100."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"What is the difference between occupancy and profitability in an agency?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Occupancy measures the percentage of time the team is working. Profitability measures how much margin that work generates. They are different variables: a team can be at 100% occupancy and have negative margins if there is a lot of rework, non-billable hours, or uncontrolled scope creep."}}]}]}'::jsonb
WHERE slug = 'por-que-tu-agencia-pierde-rentabilidad-equipo-ocupado';

-- capacidad-calendario-vs-capacidad-productiva-equipo
UPDATE public.blog_posts SET
  blocks_es = '[{"id":"b288bd50-43f6-4e87-a49f-2d4f8be3c5d3","type":"paragraph","html":"La escena se repite en muchas agencias: el lunes todo parece encajar en el calendario, el martes aparecen dos urgencias, el miércoles se encadenan reuniones de «solo 30 minutos» y el viernes acabas negociando una fecha que el lunes dabas por cerrada. No es falta de compromiso; es que <strong>la capacidad que ves en el calendario no es la capacidad que realmente construye entregables</strong>."},{"id":"05f31bff-ba40-47f6-9d25-4468f21b4dc3","type":"paragraph","html":"Aquí vamos a separar capas, sin humo: qué parte del tiempo es solo ocupación visible, qué parte sí mueve trabajo con nombre y apellidos, qué señales puedes observar antes de que el equipo se queme y qué decisiones prácticas puedes tomar esta misma semana para dejar de prometer con una foto engañosa."},{"id":"41c1d995-4dba-426e-9dd0-9cffb5b41791","type":"callout","tone":"info","html":"Si quieres alinear fechas, presupuesto y personas en una misma conversación, empieza por la guía de planificación de proyectos con cronograma y recursos . Y si tu problema ya es la sobrecarga silenciosa, la guía de carga de trabajo sin burnout te da señales tempranas y lenguaje para actuar a tiempo."},{"id":"0e06b5de-3748-4498-a99c-22d873edaceb","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"1. Mapa rápido (para no perderte)","anchorId":"mapa-capacidad-calendario-productiva"},{"id":"3eac2209-1e0f-4aca-8a7a-864f3d50dc71","type":"paragraph","html":"Este artículo está pensado para escanear y aplicar. Si solo puedes leer una parte hoy, entra por la checklist del punto 5 y vuelve luego al resto."},{"id":"7f3fc648-db11-4b36-8661-e2075941ec37","type":"table","headers":["Sección","Qué aclara","Resultado práctico"],"rows":[["2. Por qué el calendario miente","Diferencia entre hueco visible y bloque útil de ejecución.","Dejas de prometer fechas apoyándote en horas ficticias."],["3. Entregables frente a ocupación","Cómo distinguir actividad de avance real.","Instalas señales observables en la reunión de seguimiento."],["4. Capacidad neta el lunes","Cuatro decisiones simples para ordenar la semana.","Recuperas foco sin comprar herramientas ni reorganizar media empresa."],["5. Checklist y anti-patrones","Guion semanal para managers y errores que se repiten.","Conviertes una charla difusa en acuerdos concretos."]]},{"id":"1dc1e453-6ad6-4a80-acbe-dd00f395c674","type":"toc"},{"id":"12f42bb0-e40a-4f9f-939b-e3a14a409860","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"2. Por qué el calendario «verde» no es promesa de entrega","anchorId":"calendario-verde-engana"},{"id":"ed13aeed-5d6f-4afe-899d-928a5a8802b4","type":"paragraph","html":"El calendario registra <strong>compromisos</strong>; el trabajo real exige <strong>continuidad</strong>. Un bloque de dos horas entre reuniones puede quedarse en veinte minutos útiles cuando sumas preparación, cambios de contexto, mensajes urgentes y decisiones pendientes de otra llamada. Ese coste rara vez aparece en la vista semanal, pero sí aparece en los retrasos."},{"id":"f70861d7-0df0-457d-a3e0-48de0183ee12","type":"paragraph","html":"La señal de alerta no es solo operativa: también es humana. Lo notas cuando alguien empieza a entregar tarde y con menos criterio, cuando el canal del proyecto se vuelve seco y cuando el equipo vive en modo reacción. Si planificas solo con huecos visibles, estás midiendo escaparate; no capacidad productiva."},{"id":"9c70d056-0403-40b2-b4c6-515df12d14d6","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"3. La pregunta incómoda: ¿qué entregable avanzó hoy?","anchorId":"entregables-contra-calendario"},{"id":"97c9097c-d644-419b-ac21-142e93fdcdf8","type":"paragraph","html":"Un día lleno de actividad puede cerrar en cero avance real. Por eso conviene cambiar la pregunta de seguimiento: no «¿estuvimos ocupados?», sino «¿qué entregable se movió de forma observable?». Si no puedes señalar un cambio concreto en un activo del proyecto, esa supuesta capacidad no existió para planificación."},{"id":"6ca372d9-5ab2-4908-8799-f94d3282cd5d","type":"paragraph","html":"Este cambio de lenguaje evita una trampa clásica: confundir reuniones, mensajes y coordinación con progreso. Coordinar es necesario, pero no puede comerse toda la semana sin dejar rastro en lo que el cliente va a recibir."},{"id":"b39ab274-f7e0-4607-a041-42973ccb909e","type":"table","headers":["Señal en el calendario","Lectura optimista","Lectura operativa real"],"rows":[["Seis reuniones de 30 minutos en un día","«Solo son tres horas»","Se fragmenta la jornada y el trabajo profundo se desplaza a última hora."],["Bloque de foco de 45 minutos","«Ya está protegido»","Sin reglas de interrupción, ese bloque es decorativo."],["Semana ligera de reuniones externas","«Tenemos aire»","El aire se lo comen retrabajos, revisiones no previstas y cambios de alcance."]]},{"id":"969e7f41-6b0d-4342-8f1c-2df400f26b3e","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"4. Capacidad neta: qué puedes cambiar el lunes sin comprar nada","anchorId":"lunes-capacidad-neta"},{"id":"64fe8d66-97a8-430a-adca-e05ee6997b3f","type":"paragraph","html":"Antes de abrir otro tablero, toma cuatro decisiones visibles en la herramienta que ya usa el equipo:"},{"id":"7106b4f6-c252-43d6-94ca-e153e621e73a","type":"list","ordered":false,"items":["<strong>Buffer explícito</strong>: nadie debería planificarse al 100 % de su agenda. Si no hay colchón, estás planificando retrasos.","<strong>Regla de reuniones</strong>: fija ventanas para coordinación y protege bloques largos de ejecución en días clave.","<strong>Timeboxing de entregables</strong>: cada bloque de trabajo profundo debe tener entregable, no un «misc» genérico.","<strong>Métrica mínima semanal</strong>: cuántas horas fueron de construcción real y qué entregable se movió con ellas."]},{"id":"a31dbdcd-7a17-4252-ba12-aa681153c55d","type":"paragraph","html":"Cuando alguien diga «esto es demasiado proceso», devuelve una sola pregunta: ¿cuántas fechas movimos el último mes sin cambiar alcance? Esa cifra suele ordenar la conversación."},{"id":"360678b3-a845-49de-9558-bddb0fb58098","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"5. Checklist semanal y anti-patrones que drenan capacidad","anchorId":"checklist-capacidad-productiva"},{"id":"be7fc436-7f15-4984-903c-219b0b5d7429","type":"paragraph","html":"Usa esta checklist en 20 minutos cada lunes. Si dos o más puntos salen en rojo, no necesitas motivación extra: necesitas ajustar carga."},{"id":"048a0c0c-3a31-4a2c-b7cf-67a4262b2ce9","type":"paragraph","html":"La idea no es controlar por controlar, sino detectar fricción antes de que se convierta en retrasos crónicos o desgaste del equipo."},{"id":"5ab1e728-e113-4a9d-bbb5-919018405065","type":"list","ordered":true,"items":["<strong>Revisión de bloques largos</strong>: ¿cada perfil crítico tiene al menos dos bloques de 90 minutos esta semana?","<strong>Entregables con dueño</strong>: ¿todo compromiso de la semana tiene responsable y definición de «hecho»?","<strong>Topes de reuniones</strong>: ¿hay días que superan el límite pactado de coordinación?","<strong>Colchón de imprevistos</strong>: ¿está reservado y visible o está «fiado» al esfuerzo extra?","<strong>Riesgos tempranos</strong>: ¿ya sabes qué fecha puede romperse si entra una urgencia adicional?"]},{"id":"9e27eaf1-c7b6-4b47-894a-d6a1da2d4fe2","type":"table","headers":["Anti-patrón","Qué lo delata","Cómo corregirlo"],"rows":[["Calendario al 100 %","Todo el mundo «ocupado» y ninguna capacidad de respuesta.","Introduce buffers por rol y baja carga comprometida antes de aceptar más trabajo."],["Bloques de foco simbólicos","Hay bloques en agenda, pero siempre se rompen por urgencias internas.","Define reglas de interrupción y un canal único para escalados reales."],["Seguimiento sin entregables","Muchos estados «en progreso», pocos artefactos terminados.","Pide evidencia semanal de avance por entregable, no por tarea suelta."],["Optimismo por defecto con clientes","Se prometen fechas sin validar capacidad neta.","Separa compromiso externo de capacidad interna y comunica rangos realistas."]]},{"id":"c341d623-7734-496d-a3be-ff0bbbfd2f4a","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"6. Lecturas para cerrar el círculo","anchorId":"leer-siguiente-capacidad"},{"id":"d8bb8efc-2b41-4a26-adcd-d5adf7719373","type":"paragraph","html":"Si quieres profundizar, entra por el punto que más te está costando sostener en tu operación diaria."},{"id":"7dfe8b79-868a-4885-8c4c-cf9ca187fc36","type":"list","ordered":false,"items":["<strong>Qué es el timeboxing</strong> — cómo acotar alcance dentro de una caja de tiempo sin quemar al equipo.","<strong>Ley de Parkinson</strong> — por qué el trabajo se expande cuando no pones límites claros.","<strong>KPIs para agencias</strong> — qué números sí predicen margen y salud operativa."]},{"id":"b44af5d8-e915-4661-aff9-6d4cb261aa4f","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Preguntas frecuentes","anchorId":"faq-capacidad-calendario"},{"id":"99c3fc06-ac9b-4b17-b373-8b2302331103","type":"faq","items":[{"q":"¿Qué diferencia real hay entre capacidad calendario y capacidad productiva?","a":"La capacidad calendario es el tiempo que parece libre en agenda. La capacidad productiva es el tiempo continuo que realmente permite avanzar entregables sin interrupciones críticas. Para planificar bien, manda la segunda."},{"q":"¿Qué señal temprana indica que estamos sobreprometiendo?","a":"Cuando el equipo acumula estados «en progreso» pero no cierra entregables semana tras semana. Suele venir acompañado de fechas que se mueven por «detalles» y de trabajo profundo desplazado a última hora."},{"q":"¿Cómo calculo una capacidad neta realista por persona?","a":"Parte de horas contratadas y resta reuniones recurrentes, administración, soporte, coordinación y un colchón de imprevistos. Lo que queda debe incluir bloques largos de ejecución; si solo quedan huecos cortos, la planificación está inflada."},{"q":"Mi cliente exige una fecha cerrada desde el inicio. ¿Cómo lo gestiono?","a":"Puedes comprometer fecha externa, pero valida primero capacidad interna. Si no hay margen, ofrece rango o plantea qué alcance sale del sprint. Prometer por presión comercial suele acabar en retrabajo, desgaste y pérdida de credibilidad."},{"q":"¿Una herramienta de planificación arregla esto por sí sola?","a":"No. La herramienta da visibilidad, pero el cambio real llega con reglas compartidas: límites de reuniones, definición de entregable, buffers y decisiones de prioridad cuando entra una urgencia."}]},{"id":"aac8cbed-4a2b-48e4-a1b7-2b0b2e773914","type":"paragraph","html":"Si quieres que ventas, operaciones y equipo técnico trabajen con la misma foto de capacidad útil, el planificador de recursos de Taimbox te ayuda a aterrizar estos acuerdos en la semana real."},{"id":"ecde386c-4b68-471e-bbdb-d269e60c6ecf","type":"cta","text":"Explorar el planificador","href":"/planificador-recursos","variant":"primary"},{"id":"b6e2a42b-0a7b-4642-82ae-6851252cbe20","type":"relatedPost","slug":"planificacion-proyectos-cronograma-recursos"}]'::jsonb,
  blocks_en = '[{"id":"180ec7eb-5921-44be-be6d-5854a28e4e14","type":"paragraph","html":"You have probably seen this in agency life: Monday looks tidy on the calendar, Tuesday brings two urgent requests, Wednesday gets swallowed by \"just 30-minute\" meetings, and by Friday you are renegotiating a date that looked safe three days earlier. This is not a commitment issue. It is a planning issue: <strong>calendar capacity is not the same as productive capacity</strong>."},{"id":"6636fc28-d4f3-49ef-8aa1-6630a070e631","type":"paragraph","html":"This guide breaks it down in practical terms: what part of your week is visible busyness, what part truly moves named deliverables, which early signals point to hidden overload, and which low-effort changes you can make this week to stop promising against a misleading picture."},{"id":"4540d57b-069d-49ab-8633-688ff988c212","type":"callout","tone":"info","html":"If you want one shared language for dates, budget, and people, start with project planning with schedule and resources . If your issue is already silent overload, workload management without burnout gives you early warning signs and practical framing."},{"id":"1dd2709e-78e4-4ffd-8a7a-2e62bff454d3","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"1. Quick map (so you can scan fast)","anchorId":"mapa-capacidad-calendario-productiva"},{"id":"c3a97ee2-2ff9-4729-a19d-69c8fca0c9b9","type":"paragraph","html":"This article is meant to be applied, not just read. If you only have ten minutes, jump straight to section 5 and run the checklist."},{"id":"31b0118b-ac34-40f5-9a7f-826bbdf9dcc4","type":"table","headers":["Section","What it clarifies","Practical outcome"],"rows":[["2. Why the calendar lies","The gap between visible free slots and usable focus blocks.","You stop committing based on fictional hours."],["3. Deliverables vs busyness","How to separate activity from genuine forward motion.","You bring observable signals into status reviews."],["4. Net capacity on Monday","Four lightweight decisions to reshape the week.","You recover focus without new tools or a big reorg."],["5. Weekly checklist and anti-patterns","A manager script plus common traps that drain teams.","You replace fuzzy updates with concrete agreements."]]},{"id":"bddd95f3-1ecd-45fb-a081-372b82ae1736","type":"toc"},{"id":"77850130-7c34-46e3-8c73-2e99af9df246","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"2. Why a \"green\" calendar is not a delivery promise","anchorId":"calendario-verde-engana"},{"id":"2dac11b0-f8dd-4df9-82a5-22333df61cf0","type":"paragraph","html":"Calendars track <strong>commitments</strong>. Delivery work needs <strong>continuity</strong>. A two-hour slot between meetings can shrink to twenty useful minutes once you account for prep, context switching, urgent pings, and decision leftovers from prior calls. That hidden tax rarely appears in planning views, but it always appears in missed dates."},{"id":"0a10086d-d8c5-4349-a1b9-a40e1ab41edd","type":"paragraph","html":"The signal is not only operational, it is human. You see it when quality drops, replies turn terse, and the team stays in reaction mode. If your planning logic trusts empty slots alone, you are measuring availability theatre, not productive capacity."},{"id":"ffb855fa-bbc7-4b2c-a944-f1e52902bde1","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"3. The uncomfortable question: what deliverable moved today?","anchorId":"entregables-contra-calendario"},{"id":"b8b29983-ea00-478d-8e31-bca0027de76b","type":"paragraph","html":"A fully booked day can still end with zero tangible progress. Change the review question from \"Were we busy?\" to \"Which deliverable moved in a visible way?\" If you cannot point to a concrete change in an active deliverable, that capacity did not exist for planning purposes."},{"id":"8a613572-54b6-49e4-908c-aba1987fbbcf","type":"paragraph","html":"This wording shift prevents a classic mistake: treating meetings, chats, and coordination as progress by default. Coordination matters, but it cannot consume the week while leaving no trace in what the client will actually receive."},{"id":"d0e6be97-e0f0-452c-8a47-a316fbeadc5f","type":"table","headers":["Calendar signal","Optimistic reading","Operational reading"],"rows":[["Six 30-minute meetings in one day","\"Only three hours\"","The day gets fragmented and deep work is pushed late."],["A 45-minute focus block","\"It is protected\"","Without interruption rules, that block is symbolic."],["A light week of external calls","\"We have breathing room\"","Rework, unplanned reviews, and scope tweaks fill the gap."]]},{"id":"46af1f9b-0cb7-4c08-a976-2ba251e3dbaa","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"4. Net capacity: what you can change on Monday without buying anything","anchorId":"lunes-capacidad-neta"},{"id":"b1d88c05-1516-43e0-bb46-2b7b1cf8aed9","type":"paragraph","html":"Before introducing another tool, make four visible decisions in the system your team already uses:"},{"id":"4fbb8530-3329-4349-b0e7-245956329830","type":"list","ordered":false,"items":["<strong>Explicit buffer</strong>: nobody should be planned at 100% calendar load. No cushion means planned delays.","<strong>Meeting rule</strong>: define coordination windows and protect long execution blocks on key days.","<strong>Timeboxing for deliverables</strong>: deep-work blocks must be tied to a deliverable, not generic \"misc\".","<strong>One weekly metric</strong>: how many hours were true build time and which deliverable moved because of them."]},{"id":"30310c8b-e6f4-4f7f-b694-3c0e048ec115","type":"paragraph","html":"When someone says \"this is too much process\", ask one question: how many dates moved last month without scope changes? That usually resets the conversation."},{"id":"d7262ce5-5555-4e78-bf87-95fbd62de98a","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"5. Weekly checklist and anti-patterns that drain real capacity","anchorId":"checklist-capacidad-productiva"},{"id":"72354f77-695f-4a0f-b6ef-b5b1694e7638","type":"paragraph","html":"Run this checklist every Monday in twenty minutes. If two or more items are red, you do not need a motivation speech; you need a workload adjustment."},{"id":"93cc9eba-6446-4aca-895f-6becb12576fd","type":"paragraph","html":"The goal is not control for its own sake. It is to catch friction early, before it turns into chronic delays or team burnout."},{"id":"e65679c5-4603-43a7-aa0c-ecdabf1d2a02","type":"list","ordered":true,"items":["<strong>Long focus blocks</strong>: does each critical role have at least two 90-minute execution blocks this week?","<strong>Deliverables with ownership</strong>: does every commitment have one owner and a clear definition of done?","<strong>Meeting limits</strong>: are any days above your agreed coordination threshold?","<strong>Visible contingency buffer</strong>: is it explicitly reserved or silently outsourced to overtime?","<strong>Early risk signal</strong>: do you already know which date breaks first if one more urgent item lands?"]},{"id":"8e292400-0d16-4a29-872b-24b283be9f72","type":"table","headers":["Anti-pattern","How it shows up","How to fix it"],"rows":[["100% calendar booking","Everyone looks busy, nobody can absorb surprises.","Add role-based buffers and reduce committed load before taking more work."],["Symbolic focus blocks","Focus time exists in calendars but gets broken every day.","Set interruption rules and one escalation path for true urgencies."],["Status updates without deliverables","Plenty of \"in progress\", very little shipped.","Request weekly evidence by deliverable, not by scattered task count."],["Default optimism with clients","Dates are promised before net capacity is validated.","Separate external commitment from internal capacity and communicate realistic ranges."]]},{"id":"9a21ec49-846e-4a3c-b198-4cc87bb89dbd","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"6. Related reads to close the loop","anchorId":"leer-siguiente-capacidad"},{"id":"2650b99a-f7cd-4194-a867-f6711f69a43d","type":"paragraph","html":"Go deeper based on the bottleneck that hurts most in your current operating model."},{"id":"6e2bc01a-ed30-4cb2-b3f3-5a77ba0ba675","type":"list","ordered":false,"items":["<strong>What is timeboxing</strong> — how to constrain scope inside a fixed time box without burning people out.","<strong>Parkinson''s law</strong> — why work expands when you do not set clear limits.","<strong>Agency KPIs</strong> — the metrics that actually predict operational health and margin."]},{"id":"ab85f17f-1ec2-4b7e-802e-7e0c55e49439","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Frequently asked questions","anchorId":"faq-capacidad-calendario"},{"id":"3f584afc-c479-411b-8bbc-b577f1e92cc3","type":"faq","items":[{"q":"What is the practical difference between calendar capacity and productive capacity?","a":"Calendar capacity is time that appears free in scheduling views. Productive capacity is uninterrupted execution time that can move deliverables forward. For reliable planning, productive capacity is the one that matters."},{"q":"What early signal tells me we are overpromising?","a":"When \"in progress\" items pile up while completed deliverables stay flat week after week. It usually comes with repeated date shifts and deep work pushed into late hours."},{"q":"How do I estimate realistic net capacity per person?","a":"Start from contracted hours and subtract recurring meetings, admin, support, coordination, and a contingency buffer. What remains must include long execution blocks; if only short slots are left, your plan is overloaded."},{"q":"My client asks for a hard date upfront. How should I handle it?","a":"You can commit externally, but validate internal capacity first. If margin is thin, offer a date range or agree which scope leaves the sprint. Selling certainty without capacity usually ends in rework and trust erosion."},{"q":"Can a planning tool solve this by itself?","a":"No. Tools improve visibility, but results come from shared operating rules: meeting limits, clear deliverables, explicit buffers, and priority decisions when urgency appears."}]},{"id":"2d91ccd8-238a-4592-8470-81e8c2fc18ce","type":"paragraph","html":"If you want sales, operations, and delivery teams to work from the same picture of real capacity, Taimbox helps you turn these principles into weekly execution habits."},{"id":"f4535114-5d27-45f2-8e3a-bec39c6cc641","type":"cta","text":"Explore the planner","href":"/planificador-recursos","variant":"primary"},{"id":"117561f1-425d-474c-bf12-8f76a7b5e7fb","type":"relatedPost","slug":"planificacion-proyectos-cronograma-recursos"}]'::jsonb,
  json_ld_es = '{"@context":"https://schema.org","@graph":[{"@type":"Article","headline":"Capacidad calendario vs capacidad productiva: por qué un equipo ocupado no siempre entrega","description":"Guía práctica para agencias: señales observables, checklist semanal y anti-patrones para diferenciar ocupación de avance real y planificar fechas con más credibilidad.","author":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"publisher":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"datePublished":"2026-05-06","inLanguage":"es","mainEntityOfPage":{"@type":"WebPage","@id":"https://taimbox.com/blog/capacidad-calendario-vs-capacidad-productiva-equipo"}},{"@type":"FAQPage","mainEntity":[{"@type":"Question","name":"¿Qué diferencia real hay entre capacidad calendario y capacidad productiva?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"La capacidad calendario es el tiempo que parece libre en agenda. La capacidad productiva es el tiempo continuo que realmente permite avanzar entregables sin interrupciones críticas. Para planificar bien, manda la segunda."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"¿Qué señal temprana indica que estamos sobreprometiendo?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Cuando el equipo acumula estados «en progreso» pero no cierra entregables semana tras semana. Suele venir acompañado de fechas que se mueven por «detalles» y de trabajo profundo desplazado a última hora."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"¿Cómo calculo una capacidad neta realista por persona?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Parte de horas contratadas y resta reuniones recurrentes, administración, soporte, coordinación y un colchón de imprevistos. Lo que queda debe incluir bloques largos de ejecución; si solo quedan huecos cortos, la planificación está inflada."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Mi cliente exige una fecha cerrada desde el inicio. ¿Cómo lo gestiono?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Puedes comprometer fecha externa, pero valida primero capacidad interna. Si no hay margen, ofrece rango o plantea qué alcance sale del sprint. Prometer por presión comercial suele acabar en retrabajo, desgaste y pérdida de credibilidad."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"¿Una herramienta de planificación arregla esto por sí sola?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"No. La herramienta da visibilidad, pero el cambio real llega con reglas compartidas: límites de reuniones, definición de entregable, buffers y decisiones de prioridad cuando entra una urgencia."}}]},{"@type":"SoftwareApplication","name":"Taimbox","applicationCategory":"BusinessApplication","description":"Planificador de recursos para agencias: capacidad útil, entregables y rentabilidad en una sola vista operativa."}]}'::jsonb,
  json_ld_en = '{"@context":"https://schema.org","@graph":[{"@type":"Article","headline":"Calendar capacity vs productive capacity: why a busy team still misses deliverables","description":"Practical agency guide with observable signals, a weekly checklist, and anti-patterns to separate visible busyness from real output and set more credible delivery dates.","author":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"publisher":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"datePublished":"2026-05-06","inLanguage":"en","mainEntityOfPage":{"@type":"WebPage","@id":"https://taimbox.com/en/blog/calendar-capacity-vs-shippable-team-capacity"}},{"@type":"FAQPage","mainEntity":[{"@type":"Question","name":"What is the practical difference between calendar capacity and productive capacity?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Calendar capacity is time that appears free in scheduling views. Productive capacity is uninterrupted execution time that can move deliverables forward. For reliable planning, productive capacity is the one that matters."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"What early signal tells me we are overpromising?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"When \"in progress\" items pile up while completed deliverables stay flat week after week. It usually comes with repeated date shifts and deep work pushed into late hours."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"How do I estimate realistic net capacity per person?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Start from contracted hours and subtract recurring meetings, admin, support, coordination, and a contingency buffer. What remains must include long execution blocks; if only short slots are left, your plan is overloaded."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"My client asks for a hard date upfront. How should I handle it?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"You can commit externally, but validate internal capacity first. If margin is thin, offer a date range or agree which scope leaves the sprint. Selling certainty without capacity usually ends in rework and trust erosion."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Can a planning tool solve this by itself?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"No. Tools improve visibility, but results come from shared operating rules: meeting limits, clear deliverables, explicit buffers, and priority decisions when urgency appears."}}]},{"@type":"SoftwareApplication","name":"Taimbox","applicationCategory":"BusinessApplication","description":"Resource planning for agencies: useful capacity, deliverables, and profitability in one operational view."}]}'::jsonb
